set config_drive_format to vfat

 Fix known libvirt issue with live_migration of instances
 if ISO9660 formatted config drive is used.

Upstream Change-Id: Ie65e4b36e74acedfd840ee306f8e39833ffbad39

Change-Id: Ieb4c3a71baff11874031631ba38fd9e37197ed87
Related-Bug: #1246201
Closes-Bug: #1491841

commit_message:
Script to release cycle-with-intermediary

Script used for Swift 2.4.0 release, should be usable for any
cycle-with-intermediary items. Will probably be refactored at
some point with other release tools, but it's a good reference
to keep outside of my hard disk. This script currently only
tags on master, so it can't be used for release branch (or stable
branch) releases.

This also removes swiftrc.sh which was previously used to tag
RCs on intermediary releases of Swift. We don't do RCs on
cycle-with-intermediary items, so no point in keeping this one
around.

Change-Id: I3722e9cf222ed432a67f980bd4cd62ab83b14670

commit_message:
Remove -T option from build.py

The -T option is no longer necessary to be specified on each build.
The defaults work well enough, so remove -T 1000 from the documentation.

Change-Id: I13a9a4ac6b3f402d8ca0ba57fa1dbfd19a82ae1f

commit_message:
Cleanup tempest docs a bit

This commit fixes a few things in the tempest docs. First it fixes all
of the sphinx warnings and enables fail on warn to ensure we're using
valid sphinx everywhere. It also adds a link from the configuration
guide to the sample config file.

Change-Id: I3ad645a6bbfa46b4498e1732410743e46d6eb0cb

[{'created': '2015-09-03 15:38:37.000000000', 'message': 'Fix upload_image error in stackrc

This commit fixes error caused by adding default image path to IMAGE_URLS without ','
If user sets IMAGE_URLS in localrc like
IMAGE_URLS="path1, path2" (with a space after the comma)
the we get an error "binary operator expected" in
if [ -n $IMAGE_URLS ] condition and a comma will not be added to the end of IMAGE_URLS
In the code below we add default image path(path3) to IMAGE_URLS and we get
IMAGE_URLS="path1, path2path3"

Change-Id: I6543f7178c49a42c71ad9df4cdb4c6e78cbf7758
'}]
commit_message:
Fix upload_image error in stackrc

This commit fixes error caused by adding default image path to IMAGE_URLS without ','
If user sets IMAGE_URLS in localrc like
IMAGE_URLS="path1, path2" (with a space after the comma)
the we get an error "binary operator expected" in
if [ -n $IMAGE_URLS ] condition and a comma will not be added to the end of IMAGE_URLS
In the code below we add default image path(path3) to IMAGE_URLS and we get
IMAGE_URLS="path1, path2path3"

Change-Id: I6543f7178c49a42c71ad9df4cdb4c6e78cbf7758

commit_message:
Modify tests to load trustee user from plugin

Use the new auth plugin format to load authentication for the trustee
user rather than reading it from auth_token middleware options.

By doing the test modification as a separate patch we are assured that
the older style auth loading and the new one both work.

Change-Id: I72d81bd96b183d32697cbf259187ac0df13028c4

Miguel: so i think that only applies because heat was expecting to take the auth_url from the keystone_authtoken section which it assumed was a v2 url.

commit_message:
Use auth plugin for trustee

Create a new config section for configuring the user that trusts are
assigned to. This section should be configured like any other auth
plugin however it should not provide scoping information.

Closes-Bug: #1446918
DocImpact: Creates a new section 'trustee' that contains the credentials
           for the user that will receive delegated roles.
Change-Id: Idead7f505c41a55356f3670b322cbb831d442276

commit_message:
Support use_autoconfig in sahara node group templates

Since 0.10.0 python-saharaclient has ability to specify
use_autoconfig parameter when creating node group templates.
This patch adds support for this feature to
OS::Sahara::NodeGroupTemplate resource in Heat.

Change-Id: I47121d00fd1fedf1f5805c84754cb8f6b509711d

commit_message:
Support volume_local_to_instance in sahara node group templates

Since 0.9.0 python-saharaclient has ability to specify
volume_local_to_instance parameter when creating node group templates.
This patch adds support for this feature to
OS::Sahara::NodeGroupTemplate resource in Heat.

Change-Id: I17ea492bfc32bf1d362b4dfd5c8cd84ef45eebab

commit_message:
Add console_scripts entry points for all heat services

As a follow-up to Ibfd54e7b1bae700e4fb49a32e5bf7c00d1f104d9,
moving all the scripts from bin/ to setuptools entry points.

The devstack change is here: Iffb6d09bfef593d854b38e68200ae6039c4727e7

partial blueprint upgrade-tests

Change-Id: Ic8f5b8dc85098de752bbf673c4b15c06fdc4162a

commit_message:
Remove iso8601 dependency

The parse_isotime() from oslo.utils does exactly that in a slightly
better way, so no need to use that one here.

Change-Id: I1bf7f60f2bf8e5848a2a1f3a2a55b6d379641900

commit_message:
Add an empty policy.d in UT to satisfy oslo_policy requirement

While running UT, oslo_policy automatically loads files in
policy.d.
If this directory doesn't exist, oslo_policy fails.

Change-Id: I37d76e2c48d23dcf964121ad0214f1f027aba2d8
Closes-bug: #1484553

I don't think we want this behavior, current behavior makes more sense to me.

You should be able to change the limit even if it will make the tenant/project be over the limit for some time.  Otherwise you have to wait until the tenant/project is below the new limit before you can change it.  This wait makes no sense to me, as you could end up never being able to change the limit."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-02 13:56:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

@Gorka, IMHO, one most important function of quota is making explicit limit in system that tell people "you can't create resources over the limit line". So a question is "what's your purpose to change the quota limit lower when there is existing resources?", I think the answer should be "In order to no more resources can't be created by users." So we just need to change the limit equal to used+reserve number of resource in current. Otherwise, under current behavior, other users may ask "why used number of volume is more than the limit of quota, but I can't create one more volume?"'}, {'account_id': 15961, 'date': '2015-07-03 03:06:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Sorry, Wanghao. I prefer to Gorka's opinion. Users can decrease the quota, and the old resources can continue to be used, but no new resource is allowed."}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-07-03 03:26:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-07-03 03:35:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@LisaLi, That's not conflict with this patch. User can decrease the quota, but not be allowed to lower than number of current existing resource(you just need to set the limit equal to used+reserve number, that user can't create new resource any more). Not impact to old resource, they can be used as usual."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-03 04:28:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

(1 comment)

If there are use cases where you want to check the current usage before updating the quota, you can do that today with the current APIs and tooling that accounts for how you want to handle that situation.  So there's not really a hard requirement for this that I see.

Having this option in the API also doesn't really help with the hard part, which is "what do I do now that the quota-update operation has failed?"  If the answer is "contact the user and tell them to reduce usage", you can already handle that with the current quota behavior and monitoring.  With the bonus of not having to come back and update the quota again.

But I can see the value -- I'd be somewhat ok with it if the new parameter had a different name.  If others decide to go with this approach, that needs to be changed.'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2015-07-13 02:12:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

I still don't quite get the problem this change is trying to solve.  I mean I understand with the new optional parameter setting to True, Cinder stops you from updating quota is the lower than quota usage.  
I am trying to understand the actual problem Wang Hao tries to solve: '...users whom I faced to have complained why existing resources more than quota limit but they can't create resource any more'.  There is nothing much Cinder can do if end users don't understand the rationale to lower quota than existing quota usage, and deployers/admins can choose the way to reduce quota and they should communicate better in the case when they decide to lower quota then usage.  If cloud admin failed to follow the right procedure to update the quota (1. check quota usage; 2. change quota), even with your change, admin will have to check quota usage to make it work.  What's the gain/benefit?"}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-07-13 06:37:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-07-13 08:14:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

First of all, thanks Gorka help me to explain the design of this feature. :)
@Eric and winston, IMHO, there is a main problem that some users whom I faced to can't understand: What's the purpose that admin reduce quota lowner than existing usage? Limit user to can't create any resources any more? But why reduce quota just equal the current usage, it has same function. Make user to delete their resources lower than the new limit line? It's weak if user don't want to do that deletion and also bring some confusion to other users that I have mentioned. I understood there may be 100 reasons to show me why admin can reduce the quota lower than usage, and I don't want to object them too. But I hope this change can bring some new usage to update quota: 1. When admin use client(could be third party) to update the quota limit, they should check quota usage first as winston mentioned, if they don't or forget, anyway, they will change failed if quota is lower than usage, since we give the ability to cinder it will stop them to do that thing and make admin back to check quota usage. 2. If admin know what they are doing and just need to reduce the limit lower for some reason, fine, take the option argument '--force' or '--skip_validation' to update the quota. In personally, I felt this routine may be more improvement and little confusion with this. I knew Eric said that of course we can implement this purpose by using current APIs, it's a alternatives, but it depends on the application which is top on cinder I think, and is hard to have consistent."}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2015-07-13 09:13:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

>IMHO, there is a main problem that some users whom I faced to can't understand: What's the purpose that admin reduce quota lowner than existing usage? 
It seems to me that the best way to solve your problem is better communication (documentation).  Explaining the situation when reducing quota to lower than usage is needed.  And let them know what good practice is: always check quota usage before updating quota if they fear to make mistakes.
If your users are cloud end users, 

> Limit user to can't create any resources any more? But why reduce quota just equal the current usage, it has same function. Make user to delete their resources lower than the new limit line? It's weak if user don't want to do that deletion and also bring some confusion to other users that I have mentioned.
Reduce the quota to certain number is because sometime deployers want to.  For example, one of our customers is migrating from one AZ to another.  Its tenant is shared among individual developers who may not be informed such change.  If reduce the quota to its current usage, then freed quota is likely to be reused (and we did saw that).  What would you do? 
>But I hope this change can bring some new usage to update quota: 1. When admin use client(could be third party) to update the quota limit, they should check quota usage first as winston mentioned, if they don't or forget, anyway, they will change failed if quota is lower than usage, since we give the ability to cinder it will stop them to do that thing and make admin back to check quota usage. 
2. If admin know what they are doing and just need to reduce the limit lower for some reason, fine, take the option argument '--force' or '--skip_validation' to update the quota.
I don't think Cinder should be changed to make lazy if not incompetent admin's life easier.  Actually giving them a warning hardly helps because checking the quota usage is still needed nevertheless."}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-07-13 10:20:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@winston, I agree with you that we should make better communication to tell user what situation you should update quota lower than usage and what situation you shouldn't. And admin/users indeed should always check the quota usage before update the quota. I feel it's not conflict with this change and this change will force incompetent admin to check the quota usage and think clear what they want to do then choice a  right argument value."}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-07-14 07:03:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 12493, 'date': '2015-07-14 07:28:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

[{'created': '2015-07-02 12:12:02.000000000', 'message': "Validate value when user update quota

Cinder now doesn't check the existing reousrces when user lower the quota
sets. It shouldn't allow to update the quota of this resource lower than
existing number.

This patch make code to validate the update value of quota and ensure the
value can't be lower than existing resource.

APIImpact
If the update value is lower than existing resource, API will return
400 Bad Request.

Change-Id: I24428ce53e5d10e77235f372bb6d0b70ea672412
Closes-Bug: #1470706

Cinder now doesn't check the existing resource when user lower the quota
sets. It shouldn't allow to update the quota of this resource lower than
existing number.

This patch make code to validate the update value of quota and ensure the
value can't be lower than existing resource.

{

  "force": 'True'/'False'
}
If force=True and the update value is lower than existing resource,
API will return 400 Bad Request.

Change-Id: I24428ce53e5d10e77235f372bb6d0b70ea672412

sets. It should have a option action that doesn't allow to update the
quota of resources lower than current usage.

value can't be lower than existing resource.

Add an optional boolean argument 'force' with default value True.
{

  "force": 'True'/'False'
}

commit_message:
Validate value when user update quota

Cinder currently doesn't check the existing resource
when user lowers the quota sets. It should have an optional
action that doesn't allow to update the quota of resources
lower than current usage.

This patch adds code to validate the update value of quota and
ensure the value can't be lower than existing resource.

APIImpact
Add an optional boolean argument 'skip_validation' with default value True.
{
  "quota_set": {xxxx},
  "skip_validation": 'True'/'False'
}
If skip_validation=False and the update value is lower than existing resource,
API will return 400 Bad Request.

Change-Id: I24428ce53e5d10e77235f372bb6d0b70ea672412
Closes-Bug: #1304234

commit_message:
Increase timeout for separate services tests

- Default timeout for os services to be ready
is 5 minutes that is not enough sometimes.
Increased that value to 15 minutes.

Change-Id: I649a9222e90bce9badd3fd904c60e4b9c528ebac
Closes-Bug: #1490629

commit_message:
Use database_user_create in Heat bootstrap

The register operation was using database_user which is also a global
variable in group_vars/all.yml. This results in Heat being undeployable
because database_user is overwritten.

Change-Id: I78b2db34b7c99142040390c7258b7e81d3770835
Closes-bug: #1491980

commit_message:
Fixed issue 1484502

OSTF test failes in dual hypervisor mode, because
when ostf test try to launch a instance it
random chooses from nova or vcenter
availability_zone.

-add param availability_zone in methods of creating servers and volume

Closes-bug:#1484502

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-02 14:43:29.000000000', 'message': "Allow arbitrary source archive name to be imported into Dockerfile

Currently we cannot import source archives with names different
than expected by hardcoded line in Dockerfiles. This worked well
for Openstack services' tarballs where we expected SERVICE-* root
folder after extraction or kanaka-noVNC for nova-novncproxy docker.
The latter fails if one tries to clone or get tarball under other
names. This fix allows any archive or repo name to be imported as
tarball into dockerfile.

Change-Id: I869a6a19afaf0e93925572746c22b7589b6600c9
Closes-Bug: #1491415

The latter fails if one tries to clone or get tarball under other
names. This fix allows any archive (tar,tgz,zip) or repo name to be
imported into dockerfile.

Change-Id: I869a6a19afaf0e93925572746c22b7589b6600c9
Closes-Bug: #1491415
"}]
commit_message:
Allow arbitrary source archive name to be imported into Dockerfile

Currently we cannot import source archives with names different
than expected by hardcoded line in Dockerfiles. This worked well
for Openstack services' tarballs where we expected SERVICE-* root
folder after extraction or kanaka-noVNC for nova-novncproxy docker.
The latter fails if one tries to clone or get tarball under other
names. This fix allows any archive (tar,tgz,zip) or repo name to be
imported into dockerfile.

Change-Id: I869a6a19afaf0e93925572746c22b7589b6600c9
Closes-Bug: #1491415

commit_message:
[rpc] pull: removed a hack to avoid object backport triggered

Since oslo.versionedobjects 0.8.0, the object is not backported if the
requested version is the same as the latest known.

Change-Id: Ia1e9aa77b75261e4b2d2b24f31250ce2a2f028a7

commit_message:
Workaround for Manila gate failure

Instead of installing a tag novaclient we use the master
in git. This fix can be reverted if novaclient has a new version
tag.

Change-Id: I15ba39a18bd94fe818cc936b9763925384a72d0f
Partial-Bug: #1491262

[{'created': '2015-08-17 20:45:03.000000000', 'message': 'Implement manage/unmanage snapshot in Pure drivers

This adds implementations for manage_existing_snapshot,
manage_existing_snapshot_get_size, and unmanage_snapshot for
PureFCDriver and PureISCSIDriver.

Similar to the implementation of the manage/unmanage volume these will
need a volume_ref containing a ‚Äòname‚Äô key and value that matches an
object in Purity. In this case it will need to be the full name of a
snapshot object.

Due to this requiring a rename of the snapshot it will only be available
if using Purity REST API v1.4 or greater. If using a lower version an
exception will be raised.

Change-Id: Icb788e6cc0ee0e13393a12bc6aaccc57e1d491fd
Implements: blueprint pure-manage-snapshot

commit_message:
Implement manage/unmanage snapshot in Pure drivers

This adds implementations for manage_existing_snapshot,
manage_existing_snapshot_get_size, and unmanage_snapshot for
PureFCDriver and PureISCSIDriver.

Similar to the implementation of the manage/unmanage volume these will
need a volume_ref containing a ‚Äòname‚Äô key and value that matches an
object in Purity. In this case it will need to be the full name of a
snapshot object.

Due to this requiring a rename of the snapshot it will only be available
if using Purity REST API v1.4 or greater. If using a lower version an
exception will be raised.

Change-Id: Icb788e6cc0ee0e13393a12bc6aaccc57e1d491fd
Implements: blueprint pure-manage-snapshot

commit_message:
Enable py34 tests for pluggable ipam backend

Enable neutron.tests.unit.db.test_ipam_pluggable_backend.
It was disabled after extending ipam tests to run db_base_plugin tests,
which are not py34 compatible yet.

Change-Id: I3ae491fa79d4c3311a86e98db3fb2f7d5926a0ba

commit_message:
Redis Clustering Initial Implementation

Implements the CLI and python-API methods to support the
clustering commands, including the new cluster scaling
commands.

Change-Id: Icc9b4eea8ed7db1455692823d29586088cfc9434
Implements: blueprint redis-cluster

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-16 21:57:10.000000000', 'message': 'Account for changing target capacity when batching rolling updates

If the size of a scaling group is changed at the same time as a rolling
update is initiated, there may actually be more members in service to count
toward the minimum than the algorithm takes into account (due to assuming
that the size never changes at the same time as the update). This change is
required to match the functionality of rolling updates in ResourceGroup,
though it may still be suboptimal in some scenarios.

Change-Id: I3c30a57eebb4040a2ca638e41975303e81eaa7f3

commit_message:
Invert logic of counting in InstanceGroup _get_batches()

Count the number of members we have updated, not the number we have
remaining. This makes future refactoring slightly easier.

Change-Id: I3c30a57eebb4040a2ca638e41975303e81eaa7f3
Partially-Implements: blueprint scaling-group-common

commit_message:
Allowing job binaries to be edited

Adding a table row option to be able to edit a given
job binary object.  Also adding a tests for the new
functionality.

Change-Id: I7733797d4ab5de0db731da7160437f60f8e5c214
Implements: bp allow-editing-of-job-binaries

commit_message:
Add support for MariaDB datastore in Trove

A specification for this change was submitted and reviewed in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/211330/

This patchset adds the hooks and configurations options required.
No operation has been reimplemented, MariaDB 5.5 behaves exactly
as MySQL 5.5. Because of this, this patchset depends on the MySQL
Manager Refactor, which makes it possible to the MariaDB driver to
inherit the implementation of the MySQL driver.

Implements blueprint mariadb-datastore-support

Change-Id: Ia1d77fee82b08b24f5f379ee1534f335db97fd57
Depends-On: I633273d438c22f98bef2fd1535730bcdb5e5cff0

commit_message:
MariaDB 5.5 image building scripts

Updates redstack script to support mariadb as a valid datastore.
Adds elements for MariaDB 5.5 for Ubuntu and Fedora.
Keeps the dependency with Percona XtraDB to handle backups and replication
in MariaDB 5.5.

Change-Id: I05ce0ce2f5f64f72413d4035b03d62111f89b784
Depends-On: I633273d438c22f98bef2fd1535730bcdb5e5cff0
Implements: blueprint mariadb-datastore-support

I understand the development process now.
What should I do?
Do I wait for someone to implement this feature?'}, {'account_id': 10215, 'date': '2015-05-28 14:56:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi WonChon, in the kilo cycle the Trove community decided to move to a gerrit-based review of the bp/spec process.  That means each bp must have a spec that can be reviewed by the community, and the spec needs to be approved before any code can be considered.  I guess we dropped the ball in that the bp in question wasn't linked to the proper spec (there are some permissioning issues that need to be sorted out), however that doesn't change the process.  So the next step is to wait until the spec is approved.  Since I wrote the spec, I assigned the work to myself (and have begun the implementation).  We'd love to have you contribute, however - is there any other work you'd be interested in contributing?"}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2015-05-28 18:10:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Change-Id: I1bd391f8e3f7de12396fb41000e3c55be23c04ee
'}, {'created': '2015-06-15 21:37:43.000000000', 'message': 'Add Redis backup/restore functionality

Performs backup using the Redis CLI to persist data to the file system,
then streams the result to swift.

Performs restore by replacing the data file with the Swift backup

commit_message:
Add Redis backup/restore functionality

Performs backup using the Redis client to persist data to the file
system, then streams the result to swift.

Performs restore by replacing the data file with the Swift backup
and starting the server again in the correct manner.

Note: Running the int-tests require that volume_support is set
to false in the test.conf file.

To run:
./redstack install
./redstack kick-start redis
(vi /etc/trove/test.conf and change volume_support to false)
./redstack int-tests --group=backup (or --group=redis_supported)

Co-Authored-by: hardy.jung <hardy.jung@daumkakao.com>
Co-Authored-by: Peter Stachowski <peter@tesora.com>

Depends-On: I633273d438c22f98bef2fd1535730bcdb5e5cff0
Implements: blueprint redis-backup-restore
Change-Id: I1bd391f8e3f7de12396fb41000e3c55be23c04ee

commit_message:
Update from global requirements

Because the patch from the sync bot keeps auto-rebasing
and we need to get this in sooner than later.

This is really needed because we've landed code that requires
oslo.versionedobjects>=0.9.0 and are broken downstream without
that.

Change-Id: I4446b148472aa56be05346b80dc3c0add939a726

commit_message:
Increase PyKMIP version to 0.4.0

PyKMIP has released version 0.4.0. This new release provides an
improved interface for communicating with a KMIP device. This release
is being used in Barbican by the KMIP secret store.

Change-Id: I744b4863ec05e4e96748f081fb1e369a1aea9e77

commit_message:
Add keystoneauth to global requirements

It seems that keystoneauth is very close to a 1.0 release and
in order for anyone to be able to use it, it needs to be in
the global requirements.

Change-Id: Idc65048b57d4e34ac7fa29ccd2167e78726c2aa1

And the guide users may be confused if "restart" is used here while "start" is used elsewhere without a note.
So I prefer adding a note here, this will also help a guide user understand better.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-09-04 03:04:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

The httpd service will not restart if it is already running,
which leads to the dashboard verify operation failed,
so add this note.

Change-Id: Ia4697531e8638d2a91e2f65d94aa7c55c4a6d4bb
Closes-Bug: #1490485
'}, {'created': '2015-09-02 01:37:01.000000000', 'message': 'add a command note

which leads to the dashboard verify operation failed,
so add this note (rdo and obs version)

Change-Id: Ia4697531e8638d2a91e2f65d94aa7c55c4a6d4bb

commit_message:
add a command note

The httpd service will not restart if it is already running,
which leads to the dashboard verify operation failed,
so add this note (rdo and obs version)

Change-Id: Ia4697531e8638d2a91e2f65d94aa7c55c4a6d4bb
Closes-Bug: #1490485

commit_message:
Release python-novaclient 2.28.0

This is mostly needed for some key fixes once we deployed v2.0 on v2.1
with 8349aff5a and 4a18f7d3b which we should release before we close out
liberty.

The version is 2.28.0 rather than 2.27.1 because of 9b7dd38 which looks
like a feature that slipped in without a blueprint or bug.

Related-Bug: #1491579
Related-Bug: #1491325

Change-Id: I978e82a699b9f33898926c13332bb6461a0e4dae

Well, this *replaces* the existing gate test, and will fail on every CR besides https://review.openstack.org/#/c/167885/ so I am not sure how useful it is for testing (since we are already testing against that CR with the experimental job that this is copied from). That CR also Depends-On this CR, so it should be a fairly smooth transition if we +2/+W that one first.'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-09-01 01:30:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

i think you want to be really careful about having the depends around the wrong way here.

it's quite possible we look at this, assume the project is ready and merge this and suddenly everything is broken for you.  this change should be depending on the changes in barbican to add the new scripts etc."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-09-01 07:28:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Is it possible to have both depend on each other, so they can only merge simultaneously? Or does "depends-on" require not only +W, but that the other CR actually *merges*?'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-09-01 07:29:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Also the problem is that the other side literally *can't merge* until this does, so having the depends-on relationship flipped would never work."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-09-01 07:31:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Workflow-1

I'll workflow -1 this until the other change is already +2/+W, will that satisfy your concerns? Then once the other change is +W, I'll take off the -W here. Honestly worst case is that we quickly merge the other side, but I think this is safer."}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-09-01 08:00:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

my preference in this situation in the future is to see the project handling both ways of doing things for a short time.

we then switch the job here, with a period of non-voting to ensure things are ok, then purge the old job.  that way we don't break anything at any point and it makes approving changes no-brainers."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-09-01 20:36:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Is there a more descriptive name for the gate job than adding "-new"?  It seems OK now, but it will seem weird in a few months. :-)'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-09-02 00:55:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Won't be there more than a day or two -- the new gate code on the barbican side will merge, then this will merge, then all tests should pass for a few days, then we'll remove the old gate jobs and rename these, removing the "-new", then remove the backwards-compatible code on the barbican side. That should all happen within the next few days (hopefully before we cut L3).'}, {'account_id': 7764, 'date': '2015-09-02 11:26:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2015-09-02 17:41:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8623, 'date': '2015-09-03 14:49:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10873, 'date': '2015-09-03 14:50:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-09-03 18:04:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Code-Review+1

Yeah, can we find another way to express the intent of the job other than -new?

-new will get old fairly fast.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-09-04 01:13:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

commit_message:
Update Barbican Gate to use new Devstack config

This will merge the experimental new-plugin job into the existing gate
job, removing the experimental job in the process as it was only for
testing these changes.

I went looking for the index being created on MySQL. Its not in the models.py description, so that part of this change on target. However, there is an index for a recent devstack:

 mysql> show create table instance_system_metadata \G
 *************************** 1. row ***************************
       Table: instance_system_metadata
 Create Table: CREATE TABLE `instance_system_metadata` (
  `created_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  `updated_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  `deleted_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  `id` int(11) NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `instance_uuid` varchar(36) NOT NULL,
  `key` varchar(255) NOT NULL,
  `value` varchar(255) DEFAULT NULL,
  `deleted` int(11) DEFAULT NULL,
  PRIMARY KEY (`id`),
  KEY `instance_uuid` (`instance_uuid`),
  CONSTRAINT `instance_system_metadata_ibfk_1` FOREIGN KEY (`instance_uuid`) REFERENCES `instances` (`uuid`)
 ) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8
 1 row in set (0.00 sec)

For installs that are created without running Havana, this is created in migration 216. This bit worries me, because its actually one of a large number of indexes only created for mysql:

    mysql_pre_indexes = [
        Index('instance_type_id', instance_type_projects.c.instance_type_id),
        Index('project_id', dns_domains.c.project_id),
        Index('fixed_ip_id', floating_ips.c.fixed_ip_id),
        Index('network_id', virtual_interfaces.c.network_id),
        Index('network_id', fixed_ips.c.network_id),
        Index('fixed_ips_virtual_interface_id_fkey',
                  fixed_ips.c.virtual_interface_id),
        Index('address', fixed_ips.c.address),
        Index('fixed_ips_instance_uuid_fkey', fixed_ips.c.instance_uuid),
        Index('instance_uuid', instance_system_metadata.c.instance_uuid),
        Index('iscsi_targets_volume_id_fkey', iscsi_targets.c.volume_id),
        Index('snapshot_id', block_device_mapping.c.snapshot_id),
        Index('usage_id', reservations.c.usage_id),
        Index('virtual_interfaces_instance_uuid_fkey',
              virtual_interfaces.c.instance_uuid),
        Index('volume_id', block_device_mapping.c.volume_id),

        Index('security_group_id',
              security_group_instance_association.c.security_group_id),
    ]

I think we need to work out which of these other indexes are missing from non-mysql databases, and if so if it makes sense to create them."}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-08-17 10:20:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

commit_message:
Adds instance_uuid index for instance_system_metadata

DB migrating script don't create index on
instance_system_metadata.instance_uuid for SQLite,
PostgreSQL and IBM DB, it cause the listing instances
have low performance. Adds instance_uuid index
for these DB.

Change-Id: I8a6425b00fe5f491b1bd98b7b335e7d8b13eaf33
Closes-Bug: #1480029

commit_message:
Use domain checking for user_role provider

Enforce domain name checking by using domain_check method.

Note: Implements the following user story:
62-keystone-v3-implement-support-for-default-domain-if-no-domain

Change-Id: I5fbcb2ee356703ef8f0166fb5c569cf975b9560b

commit_message:
Log and report trace on service operation fails

This patch adds exception logging to the swift service API. Each
operation that results in failure of any operation will now log
the exception as well as report a timestamp and full stack trace
in the results returned by the service API calls.

Change-Id: I7336b28354e7740ea7d048bdf355e3c1a1b4436c

commit_message:
Refactor InstanceGroup batch size check

Since we can now calculate the batch count externally, just pass that in.
Also, create an intermediate variable total_pause_time to eliminate
repitition and make the code a little more self-documenting.

Change-Id: Icceac0142055e7262985aa61a425d503c3929a42

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-04 08:51:49.000000000', 'message': "Add metods for checking scoped tokens

Refactor _check_scoped_token_attributes so it doesn't check existence of
project or domain key in the token payload.
Add to methods _check_project_scoped_token_attributes and
_check_domain_scoped_token_attributes that compare present and expected
project and domain respectively. Also, those two methods use internally
_check_scoped_token_attributes for validating token input.

Change-Id: I36db5e06f41de0977f1b29d6118b7a370c9f838b
"}, {'created': '2015-08-26 13:49:48.000000000', 'message': "Add methods for checking scoped tokens

Refactor _check_scoped_token_attributes so it doesn't check existence of
project or domain key in the token payload.
Add to methods _check_project_scoped_token_attributes and
_check_domain_scoped_token_attributes that compare present and expected
project and domain respectively. Also, those two methods use internally

commit_message:
Add methods for checking scoped tokens

Refactor _check_scoped_token_attributes so it doesn't check existence of
project or domain key in the token payload.
Add to methods _check_project_scoped_token_attributes and
_check_domain_scoped_token_attributes that compare present and expected
project and domain respectively. Also, those two methods use internally
_check_scoped_token_attributes for validating token input.

Change-Id: I36db5e06f41de0977f1b29d6118b7a370c9f838b

commit_message:
Fix blacklist_file option exclude regex generation

This commit fixes the regex generation from the blacklist_file option.
Previously it was only generating an exclude regex (unless a regex was
also provided) this however wasn't working with testr. This was due
to how testr uses the regex certain regexes which just had the
lookahead exclude was not actually excluding the tests. However,
adding a real regex match fixes this issue. So this commit adds logic
to guess a regex that always matches to make the exclude portion work.
This is a hack until we can fix the testr regex filter logic to handle
just a lookahead exclude properly. (most likely need to change a
re.match to a re.search)

Change-Id: Ic36aa1fd4b829c21f2ba74ced7dbf0dabbea6d10

commit_message:
Add JSON-Schema note to api_plugins.rst

Nova v2.1 API validates a request with JSON-Schema, and there are
some specific usage on that. This patch adds it to the rst file
for the implementation hint.

Change-Id: I4edac8b6b53d198f2a237bb163b8975528319c9b

currently,the cpu notifications has extremely verbose metadata which
is list of all metrics in message. ie, each meter has metadata like:

  u'metrics': [
       {'timestamp': u'2013-07-29T06:51:34.472416',
        'name': 'cpu.frequency', 'value': 1600,

the proposed metadata removes all data already included in meter:

"}]
commit_message:
fix metadata for compute cpu notifications

currently,the cpu notifications has extremely verbose metadata which
is list of all metrics in message. ie, each meter has metadata like:

  u'metrics': [
       {'timestamp': u'2013-07-29T06:51:34.472416',
        'name': 'cpu.frequency', 'value': 1600,
        'source': 'libvirt.LibvirtDriver'},

       ...

       {'timestamp': u'2013-07-29T06:51:34.472416',
        'name': 'cpu.user.time', 'value': 17421440000000,
        'source': 'libvirt.LibvirtDriver'}],

    ...
    }

the original metadata pre-declarative notifications is:

    {'timestamp': u'2013-07-29T06:51:34.472416',
     'name': 'cpu.frequency',
     'value': 1600,
     'source': 'libvirt.LibvirtDriver',
     'event_type': 'compute.metrics.update',
     'host': <publisher_id>}

the proposed metadata removes all data already included in meter:

    {'source': 'libvirt.LibvirtDriver',
     'event_type': 'compute.metrics.update',
     'host': <publisher_id>}

Change-Id: I2c8d4ba7768cba378b931acbfe84a29549da7f8b

commit_message:
Fix API directories on the doc

The commit Ic19f2d019c2c78f1de14a0eced85e84f2d2cec28 has changed
API directory structure, but we forgot to update the corresponding
doc. This patch updates it.

commit_message:
Update tag version to 11.2.1

The tag version - which is used for the repository folder
referenced when building/synchronising the wheels - was
mistakenly left at 11.1.2 for the 11.2.0 release.

This is a patch to update the tag for a fast follow release
of 11.2.1.

Change-Id: I11f141585af3f799528cd9146e41bf035ebdb099

commit_message:
Replaces print with print() for py 2/3 compatibility

This patch replaces print with print() to comply with
the newer python version i.e. python3.

Partially-Implements: Blueprint neutron-python3

Change-Id: Id92a7d292b832f07c79da8a42ac90b99d8c2c0cc

commit_message:
Enhanced error checking in get_discovery_url

get_discovery_url should never return an empty
URL. Added check and exception for this situation.

Co-Authored-By: Vilobh Meshram <vilobhmm@yahoo-inc.com>

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1491178
Change-Id: I2d5b3996c0ee53f40399ca3fd0d6b987daa26f79

Hi Matt

 > 2. I'm also a bit confused, the previous patch in this
 > series removes the schema, and then this patch looks
 > like it adds it back more or less exactly the same.

The removed schema is for "get a specific version" API, not for "get the list of versions" API. And it was added for Nova v3 API and it was never used for v2 API.
The schemas are almost the same, but some differences. In addition, the schema file name was not good by comparing the other schemas.

I tried to fix it for applying to this API, but the differences seemed to make confusions.
So I removed it and added it as a fresh schema for reviewing again from fresh viewpoints.'}]

commit_message:
Add test for Nova list-versions API

This commit adds a test that does a GET on the raw endpoint to
ensure that the nova version GET does the right thing.

Co-Authored-By: Ken'ichi Ohmichi <oomichi@mxs.nes.nec.co.jp>

Related-Bug: #1491579
Change-Id: I5ee09891cd1b62a87d25284be961c2027cdbd82a

I put this information on the spec -- adding that here as well for visibility:

So IMO, the trove-manage command provides a really poor user experience for this, and translating those commands directly would leave us with an equally frustrating user experience for our APIs.

I've been thinking about this quite a bit, and I think that it would make for a much cleaner and simpler API if all we exposed through the API were datastore versions, and we handled the management / creation of the datastore internally.

All this would mean is that if we got an API call to create a datastore version, and the corresponding datastore doesn't exist, we'd create it. If one already exists, we'd simply use that one.

Doing this has two distinct advantages: 1. Cuts the complexity -- the number of APIs that we need to support is reduced by half 2. Provides for a better UX -- you only need 1 call to register a new datastore/version as opposed to the 2-3 calls that were required previously. 

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-07-08 10:21:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2015-07-20 05:40:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I agree with SlickNik and I think he has captured my sentiments better than I could. My objections to the API being proposed are largely that they aren't really a good API. As SlickNik points out making an API out of it is not a happy option.

I agree, we need an API for this, but lets come up with a good one."}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-08-09 09:12:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-09 10:49:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

}

commit_message:
Implements Datastore Registration API

Adds the mgmt APIs for

1. Add a new datastore-version.
2. Reset the attributes of an existing datastore-version.
3. List datastore-versions.
4. Get details of a datastore-version.
5. Delete existing datastore-version.

In order to simplify the process of registering an image for a new
datastore/datastore-version the datastore would be managed behind the
scenes. This means that when creating a datastore-version, a datastore
will be automatically created, if it does not already exist.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint datastore-registration-api
Depends-On: I915baa4c5c8bbe3f0483bcaeaa5ce95044d35bf7
Change-Id: If79a03962abc41033dfe6e6ec1e335b243bb74f7

commit_message:
Implements Datastore Registration API

Adds the mgmt APIs for

1. Create datastore-version.
2. List datastore-versions.
3. Get details of a datastore-version.
4. Update the attributes of an existing datastore-version.
5. Delete a datastore-version.

Added the code to management.py and the unit-tests,
this code would help for writing integration tests to trove
for the newly added management-apis.

Change-Id: I915baa4c5c8bbe3f0483bcaeaa5ce95044d35bf7
Implements: blueprint datastore-registration-api

commit_message:
Remove Nova v3 version API schema

The commit Ia8e03aad49c524e5c3df110f0737eee3262b93e6 added a response
schema for Nova v3 version API. However the v3 API has been removed
but we forgot to remove it.
This patch removes it for the cleanup before adding the response
schema of Nova v2/v2.1 version API.

Change-Id: I5e96630fe9d4ae424df7064f4f759497c634f02c

commit_message:
objects: Hook migration object into Instance

Make sure we can access the migration context from the Instance object.
Also add some of the methods that will be used for manipulating the
migration context of the instance so as to avoid more than a single
version bump.

Change-Id: I52d7c13460fbb16dea107724da392df64f62bc51
Related-blueprint: migration-fix-resource-tracking

@Alex

After some investigation, I think we need to accept the different validation behavior between nova-network and neutron as backend here.

Now if neutron is enabled, "" of both name and description are accepted like:

 $ nova secgroup-create "" ""
 +--------------------------------------+------+-------------+
 | Id                                   | Name | Description |
 +--------------------------------------+------+-------------+
 | 1d55c11e-661d-4fc8-add5-0797e850ba7a |      |             |
 +--------------------------------------+------+-------------+

but if nova-network is enabled, string length of them should be 1 or larger because of http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/nova/tree/nova/compute/api.py#n3853

So I think current code seems enough in this situation.
If not, we will break the existing users which specify the above sample.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-07-29 12:43:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Workflow-1

After discussing this on irc, we are thinking the validation behavior should be the same between nova-network and neutron as possible.

In this case, we can implement the validation way for checking the existences of name and description in a request body and these value types.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-16 03:27:20.000000000', 'message': 'Not pass secgroup values if not specified

Now Nova passes None to Neutron as security group values when clients
don't specify these values on "create a security group" API. That
causes Neutron returns a BadRequest response and the creation fails.

On Neutron's "create a security group" API, both name and description
are optional. So this patch adds type checks before getting values
without the existence checks.

In addition, if clients don't specify these values, this patch makes
Nova don't pass these values to Neutron without None. After that,
clients can create a security group without name and description like
Neutron ones.

Change-Id: I45c92d77c083838fbb7c5146e43c3b661e14c42d
Closes-Bug: #1460875

commit_message:
Add secgroup param checks for Neutron

If using nova-network, "create a security group" API call fails
unless specifying name or description. On the other hand, if calling
Neutron API directly without Nova proxy, we can create a security
group without name or description.

This patch enforces to specify both name and description even if using
Neutron for consistent validation behavior between nova-network and
Neutron.

Change-Id: I45c92d77c083838fbb7c5146e43c3b661e14c42d
Closes-Bug: #1460875

commit_message:
List credentials by type

Currently the only attribute that you can filter a credential list by is
user_id. I want to be able to list by user_id and credential type (a
required field) so that I only get back my EC2 credentials (for example)
when I do a list.

Change-Id: I91f8fb15a2e9a8326059d7a60d2bf1b4c4aa6daa
Closes-bug: #1460492
bp list-credentials-by-type

commit_message:
filter pre_assigned_dev_names when finding disk dev

when finding disk dev we should filter pre_assigned_dev_names,
otherwise it returns the used dev name and then causing not creating
new disk dev.

Change-Id: I5f7ed979284c5e6e3569e9b503cb8c93c3e47ab3
Closes-Bug: #1471307

Shouldn't this be a standard size request-id length across openstack projects?"}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2015-08-06 17:29:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

as mentioned in the commit message initial set to 0 so this is backwards compatible with our current behavior.

The https://review.openstack.org/#/c/210026/ sets it something sensible and we can debate what that sensible value should be.'}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2015-08-06 17:31:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2015-08-06 17:32:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think this looks good, but I have a question.  Suppose a glance admin sets this at 64 and some other openstack project notices this same problem, implements a similar fix, but their admin sets it to 68.  Someone makes a request to that other service with a 68-char request ID, and that service contacts glance for some reason.  At that point, your code will throw an exception ending the request.  I'm just wondering whether it would be better to just strip the request-id header in this case instead of throwing an exception."}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2015-08-06 17:32:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Abhishek please ping me when you have a +1 on this and will remove -W'}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2015-08-06 17:33:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

For such interop cases we need a standard size. Good topic for CPL meeting.'}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2015-08-06 17:39:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Brian,

I see your point but I don't really agree. Our basic behavior is to fail early what ever we do and we don't truncate other oversized data either. IMHO if there is other OpenStack projects that accepts Request IDs sent to the service and/or forwards it to Glance, the admins needs to correlate their limits between services.

Would be horrible if for example swift would just truncate the objects sent because glance admin set larger large_object_size that swift admin."}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2015-08-06 17:44:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Erno,

I think you're right.  I guess what I was really getting at is that the length needs to be coordinated among the various projects."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-06 19:52:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add mechanism to limit Request ID size

Adding 'max_request_id_length' defaulting to 0 for backportability.

DocImpact
SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1482301
Change-Id: Ie68afe7610a414bbcc42ff3bee33a9779303c115

commit_message:
Fix permission issue of server group API

Server group was created by tenantA, but it can
be shown and deleted by tenantB. Fix this permission
issue, and update test cases.

Change-Id: Ib0b96d536f7b085ef047cb8206de05f9bedc004f
Closes-Bug: #1466390

commit_message:
libvirt: enable live migration with serial console

When migrating an instance that uses serial console, the domain XML
must be changed to reflect the serial console configuration of the
target host.

Also prevent live migration when serial console is enabled and the
libvirt version is not able to process modified domain XML.

Change-Id: I654e444584124334e34d4673db6464cc2f2b822e
Partial-Bug: #1455252

commit_message:
deprecate db2 nosql driver

the db2 nosql product is not in development anymore as IBM has moved
on to an alternate solution. the existing driver code is untested
in the community and IBM products are moving off of it. this patch
marks db2 nosql driver for deprecation.

Closes-Bug: #1491819
Change-Id: Ic4e906615931143744f25d70935bdb8138a6b93a

This needs to be fixed very badly. However, I'm concerned that we have to resort to interpreting VIF information to determine that an error has occurred. It seems to me that the neutron client and API should be indicating an error has occurred instead of encapsulating it as port information, especially when the port is invalid. I'll add neutron to the the bug report and comment."}, {'account_id': 12175, 'date': '2015-03-06 08:09:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Brent
If I understand you correctly that neutron client should raise a exception
and in nova we catch it , instead of find the port binding information explictly ?'}, {'account_id': 6681, 'date': '2015-03-16 11:39:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Eli - yes, that is what I was originally asserting. Now that I have looked at it again, I realize you are relying on show_port() to get this information. I would agree that throwing an exception from show_port() doesn't make a lot of sense. However, stuffing an error code in binding_type seems really arbitrary and bogus - there should be a status field or something for this kind of thing. Unfortunately, it looks like neutron's ML2 code makes heavy use of this type of thing. I'll need to look at it further on the neutron side to find out if this is deliberate and required or is a flaw that was simply perpetuated. In any case it doesn't seem to be a good reason to hold up this patch.

However, I would love to know what the reasoning behind needing the show_port() when we just called create_port(). That is, why is the information that we rely on being available through show_port() immediately after calling create_port() not available when we call create_port(). This additional call for something that is a pretty basic code path seems wrong. Is this something we can address so the show_port() call isn't required?"}, {'account_id': 6681, 'date': '2015-03-16 19:11:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

@Eli - I checked with Bob Kukura on the binding_failed type and confirmed that it is more of a transient condition than an error condition so my previous reservations regarding neutron throwing an exception are not correct. And also verified that the port extensions aren't part of the reply on create_port (unfortunately) making show_port a necessity. So with that in mind, I'm going to take my -1 back."}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-03-16 21:27:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

[{'created': '2015-02-16 03:41:08.000000000', 'message': "Neutron: Check port binding status

Neutron api creates/uses a port which the port vif_type is
'binding_failed' without any verification, this leads libvirt
driver failed to create instance, and cause vif driver raise
a wrong exception message when binding failed.
this patch addes a new exception PortBindingFailed to indicats
the port binding failed.
Closes-Bug: 1390336
Co-authored-by: Alex Xu <hejie.xu@intel.com>

Change-Id: I66763ff5293473d1283d55f76dfe33d153abaaec

commit_message:
Neutron: Check port binding status

Neutron api creates/uses a port which the port vif_type is
'binding_failed' without any verification, this leads to libvirt
driver failing to create instance, and cause vif driver to raise
a wrong exception message.

This patch adds a new exception PortBindingFailed to indicate port binding
failed. If port is newly created, delete it if PortBindingFailed exception
catched.

Closes-Bug: #1390336
Change-Id: I66763ff5293473d1283d55f76dfe33d153abaaec

commit_message:
Fix hooks for dealing with member actions

This patch ensures that operations like add_router_interface
are correctly dispatched to the plugin.
It does so by introducing fairly ugly hacks in the
resource_identifier, and attribute_population pecan hooks.

This is however the best possible solution wiht the current
infrastructure which basically relies on hooks for request
dispatching.

Change-Id: I34880d1ce796cfd6f81d16fc1b9fd8387b5db056

commit_message:
Deprecate LDAP Resource Backend

Change 8ff5520713251ec247eeeb783f140d757cbdceb0
deprecated LDAP Assignment, which meant our
current Assignment + Resource backends. This was
officially deprecated in Kilo, however the deprecation
notice on resource was missed.

This change adds the missing bit: deprecate LDAP
Resource backend.

Closes-Bug: #1476347

Change-Id: Ie564f3a7dd586ced3aed72ad1eb57934e6911d4e

commit_message:
Remove errant } in create-zanata-xml for Horizon

This causes the Zanata CLI utility to print an error message about
accepted variables, and it may cause problems for the parser.

Change-Id: If46bd2baf8ee12394b61a9d505fd9f7e690f1b23

commit_message:
Make liberty actually allowed in features.yaml

We had liberty defined but didn't allow it. Actually allow it so that
requirements cross branch testing can work.

Change-Id: I2bd6b06f8c2fde530bb0262817ec212c5fd4088c

commit_message:
Fix ubuntu image builds due to revert in tarball names

The format for the SHA256SUMS file was reverted so that they now refer to
the images using the release code name (e.g. trusty) as opposed to the
release version nomenclature (e.g. ubuntu 14.04). This is causing ubuntu
based image builds to fail. This reverts the fix which explicitly specifies
the release version name since this is no longer available.

Reverts: I36bfba75c22b0a153eda2fcc3137fcefa9a29536
Change-Id: I633273d438c22f98bef2fd1535730bcdb5e5cff0
Depends-On: Ie43bc969425795b5ba9e9ee988e0caa8e86ce354

commit_message:
Requeuing event with workload_partitioning on publish failure

when workload_partitioning is enabled,
publishing of samples occurs in the
pipeline listeners. If publishing fails
when single publisher is configured, event
will not be requeued or ack'ed.

This fix requeues or acks the event based on
ack_on_event_error.

Change-Id: I8f2f889736c8897e5b15952ab32308cf33205c3f
Closes-Bug: 1488202

commit_message:
Add timeout to keystone requests

Our agent is timing out on getting keystone tokens and the
monasca url adding in the ability to set a timeout for these
requests

commit_message:
Deprecate create Discover without session

The comments indicated that creating a Discover without a
session is deprecated, but there was no warning generated.

Also, updated the Discover() parameter docstrings with the
standard deprecation info (e.g., in what release it's
deprecated and when we might remove it).

bp deprecations

Change-Id: I1d42b74aa72c15b95ac3c365b40d8c622869ed7e

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-03 15:17:18.000000000', 'message': "workaround for RAX repose configuration

The RAX Repose environment is blocking access to the API version
information by local policy, returning a 401 before we even get to
Nova itself. While this in clearly incorrect behavior, it is behavior
in the field, and we should not break all our users on that cloud.

This catches the 401 and translates that so that it's the equivalent
of only supporting v2.0. We will be taking these API calls to defcore,
and intend to remove this work around once that is done.

Change-Id: I2072095c24b41efcfd58d6f25205bcc94f1174da

commit_message:
workaround for RAX repose configuration

The RAX Repose environment is blocking access to the API version
information by local policy, returning a 401 before we even get to
Nova itself. While this in clearly incorrect behavior, it is behavior
in the field, and we should not break all our users on that cloud.

This catches the 401 and translates that so that it's the equivalent
of only supporting v2.0. We will be taking these API calls to defcore,
and intend to remove this work around once that is done.

Change-Id: I2072095c24b41efcfd58d6f25205bcc94f1174da
Related-Bug: #1491579

commit_message:
Don't assume oscomputeversions is correctly deployed

The paste pipeline that's "above" the /v2/ and /v2.1/ urls is the
oscomputeversions dispatcher, which should provide 300 redirects to
versions in question. Previously the code that was trying to discover
information about the current version did so via a GET of something
that looked like /v2. On an upstream compatible OpenStack this
actually triggers a 300 and redirect to /v2/ for the real answer.

On deployed public clouds, oscomputeversions is sometimes not deployed
at all, or front end blocking by the load balancer does
weirdness. Sometimes with a 401, sometimes a hang.

This fixes the way that first request is made that should avoid the
300 redirect entirely. The code probably should have done this
originally, but it was tested with upstream configuration that worked
fine in this case.

This fix is tested against HP Cloud (the only pub cloud I have creds
with). Before this fix "nova list" hangs trying to get the supported
versions, after the fix it works as expected.

Change-Id: I1692380fe8d340e5c044f46dd0b103c7550d2c7d
Closes-Bug: #1491579

commit_message:
hyperv: convert driver to use nova.objects.ImageMeta

Convert the hyperv driver and related files to make use of
the nova.objects.ImageMeta object. Where an image_meta
dict is passed in via the virt API, it is converted to
object form before being used.

Change-Id: I673cb728b57419f68c6369c5f0f3351cbe5f65bf

commit_message:
Convert identity defaults to keystone v3 api

At this point all our function calls should be using the V3 APIs anyway
so switch the authentication credentials to v3 compatible ones and
remove all the hacks we added to force v3 API calls.

Implements: bp keystonev3
Change-Id: If92d3e11b9a363454f77527783b6d25f4da9c249

commit_message:
Implement TODO for version listing

Return a list of currently enabled API versions building
the response in the same way as it is done for the eventlet
WSGI API in order to ensure backward compatibility.

The only version listed is obviously 2.0, but the solution
devised in this patch allows version controller for self
declaring the version they implement.

This patch also replaces the use of _lookup when such method
is not strictly necessary.
To this aim, the minimum version of Pecan has been bumped to
1.0 as previouse releases did not support dots "." as valid
characters in URI path segments.

Change-Id: Ia748194b2c07a04a711d32ce8058a006e73621ef

(2 comments)

The 'server_type' should be either 'vm' or 'bm'. Maybe it can be 'container' in the future.

Currently, magnum hard-code server_type to be 'vm' in many places for historical reason. We have debated whether we should add a 'server_type' field in the baymodel. The opposing point of view is that 'server_type' is a redundant information since the flavor/image field already indicates the server is a baremetal or VM. I think the team doesn't have a consensus on this yet.

Therefore, fixing the hard-coded 'vm' looks like a tech debt. commit_message:
Updates the node count key for all types of bay

By default the key to get node count is "number_of_minions"
which is not true for baymodels other than kubernetes
and it raises "KeyError" so that status of bay will not
be updated.

Closes-Bug: #1489725
Change-Id: I9f6a8ebbc26f501d54ef97937329845a12002d6c

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-03 06:18:35.000000000', 'message': 'agent_ilo doesnt boot up the image

The boot and deploy interfaces are not yet implemented
in agent_ilo driver. The boot.clean_up_ramdisk should be
called only when the driver has the boot and deploy
implemented.

Closes bug: #1491704

Change-Id: I291ae426671e3c0289cc1264ae46cf3a9021b27f
'}, {'created': '2015-09-03 07:41:55.000000000', 'message': 'agent_ilo fails to bring up instance

Since boot is a core interface, there is an attribute
task.driver.boot for every driver and hence hasattr
cannot be used to check if the driver has a boot
interface.  This commit fixes the coding error.

Closes bug: #1491704

Change-Id: I291ae426671e3c0289cc1264ae46cf3a9021b27f
'}]
commit_message:
agent_ilo fails to bring up instance

Since boot is a core interface, there is an attribute
task.driver.boot for every driver and hence hasattr
cannot be used to check if the driver has a boot
interface.  This commit fixes the coding error.

Closes bug: #1491704

Change-Id: I291ae426671e3c0289cc1264ae46cf3a9021b27f

commit_message:
Remove 'is_valid_event' method

This method is no longer needed as ironic now has
access to the automaton provided 'is_actionable_event'
method that provides an equivalent api.

Change-Id: Ib0edd2da7e36b91c3fba306133f011db5a87019f

commit_message:
Set correct tenant id when python-client init

If tenant name with chinese characters, an
'UnicodeEncodeError' exception raised when the tenant
creating a stack with a nova server. To set correct
tenant id instead of tenant name when novaclient init
is the best way to avoid this problem.

Also this patch fix this problem for glanceclient and
cinderclient.

Change-Id: Ifc8ab70c69453344156d25aba4291769bb7fe117
Closes-Bug: #1488881

commit_message:
initial python monasca-common code in monasca_common

This is the start of a python monasca-common package.
Initially it has a common python logging config,
common oslo opts, and mysql common code.

Change-Id: I15c32b72fc42a8c5ce9eeedf20ca3a11907bf29f

commit_message:
Obfuscate Token in Debug Mode

Our client prints out the users token in each curl request.
These debug statements than get passed up to our other services
that use the client if on debug mode so we could be printing the
token in log files. We needed to remove that.

Change-Id: I6dd6c0f171f03f6715abd59b26e9f59de5b0bb9b

commit_message:
Add a session cache of can_access call results

This patch adds a decorator and function to all horizon components so
that the results of calls to can_access are cached in the session. This
should prevent large numbers of calls to APIs when can_access functions
need to get information from services. The cache is stored in
session['allowed'] using self.__class__ as the key, this ensures each
key is human readable and can be easily mocked out in future tests.

Change-Id: Ic65e4cb6499ecae4b09dd525416656a6f41853f5
Closes-Bug: 1367716

commit_message:
scenario001: deploy Nova

This patch deploy Nova:
* RabbitMQ, MySQL and Keystone resources
* Common nova service bits
* API, scheduler, conductor, console, compute (with qemu), cert, client,
  consoleauth, vncpoxy, neutron parameters
* Neutron configuration to talk to Nova API
* neutron_metadata_proxy_shared_secret parameter to talk to neutron
  metadata proxy

Change-Id: I9d46ba69df624a372abb84e22b1e8e28c84e23a7

commit_message:
scenario001: deploy Neutron

Deploy Neutron service and resources (rabbitmq user, mysql database,
keystone resources).
It will deploy:
* Neutron Server using ML2 / OVS plugin
* Neutron Agent using ML2 / OVS agent
* Neutron L3 & DHCP & Metering & Metadata & LBaaS agents

Change-Id: Ic799386a27c711b6f26e50279704e67cad6faccd

commit_message:
Use proper href attribute from vswitch object

This change is to use related_href property of vswitch
rather than href.  This way, comparisons in other objects
using vswitch_uri will match.

Change-Id: I22f78e6d14e1f2a796179066115bb1a7ed784563
Closes-Bug: 1492017

commit_message:
Adding documentation

This adds documentation for Bandit and all plugins, in RST format.
To build the new documentation you can use the new tox target:

  tox -e docs

This will spit out various formatted output into the docs/build
folder.

Change-Id: I012b5e321fad81e6064044745c8e7cb0c5e1b6ac
Closes-Bug: 1474796

Hi Dave, thanks for doing this work, unfortunately I really don't think we want to be doing things in this way. I would like to propose an alternative approach. The Statement buffer is intended to break up the code into chunks for the prepose of presenting accurate/nice issue reports to the user. This feels like something that should be done after processing the AST and not before. Thus, I would like to invert the flow. This would then work something like the following, we run tests on the raw AST tree produced from the source code file, identify issues and then use the statement buffer logic to extract the appropriate code block given the identified AST node(s). This way we don't need to make this code any more complex and can actually simplify it while still solving the problem. Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 15304, 'date': '2015-06-02 14:21:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I have made some changes to add additional scope awareness to the
StatementBuffer class. Additional functions have been added to allow
you to retrieve the lines of the parent of a given line, or all
children of a given line. Used in combination, it is possible to
retrieve all siblings of a given line.

StatementBuffer also now holds an archive of the AST of every statement
in it's unaltered state, which can be accessed using the new get_node
function, for example calling get_node(get_parent(line_no)) will
return the parent node of the given line, which includes the AST
of that node and all child nodes. Note, all the new functions take
a line number as a parameter, and return line numbers, or an AST
node for get_node().

Read the code for more info, or contact dave.belcher@hp.com for help

commit_message:
Added additional scope functions to StatementBuffer

I have made some changes to add additional scope awareness to the
StatementBuffer class. Additional functions have been added to allow
you to retrieve the lines of the parent of a given line, or all
children of a given line. Used in combination, it is possible to
retrieve all siblings of a given line.

StatementBuffer also now holds an archive of the AST of every statement
in it's unaltered state, which can be accessed using the new get_node
function, for example calling get_node(get_parent(line_no)) will
return the parent node of the given line, which includes the AST
of that node and all child nodes. Note, all the new functions take
a line number as a parameter, and return line numbers, or an AST
node for get_node().

Read the code for more info, or contact dave.belcher@hp.com for help

Change-Id: I2b0a6910fde06a8d02ea7878e1552719640302b2

commit_message:
Initial stab at pbr and version passing.

This patch updates the build system to use pbr. It also
passes the Horizon and App Catalog UI plugin versions
to the application repository as part of the ajax request
so we can more easily determine when v1 api support can
be removed in the future.

Change-Id: Ic407d45a09b00d97ff7492b6597693524522153d

commit_message:
Avoid returning volume metadata in DotHill driver

DotHill driver returns volume metadata on create volume.
It is not needed and causing CI failures.

Change-Id: Idbe16fcff60ed0c3cfa1f4ba66ca549c6dd9a1d8
Closes-Bug: #1487165
Co-Authored-By: Lakshman <lakshminarayanat@vedams.com>

commit_message:
Initial Murano support

First stab at Murano support. Supports plugin autodetection,
importing Packages and Bundles, installation detection
and launch support.

commit_message:
Add Keystone User/Group RoleAssignment resources

This is the second patch of two to allow roles to be added to existing
users. This patch adds two new resources:

  OS::Keystone::UserRoleAssignment
  OS::Keystone::GroupRoleAssignment

These resources will grant a user or group role(s) within the given
project or domain.

Change-Id: I4002fc245b1b21d99d95740b7d15642fd8f9e26d
Closes-Bug: #1477218

keystone resources.

commit_message:
Make RoleAssigment class to RoleAssigmentMixin class

Functionality defined in RoleAssigment class is used only in another classes.
This patch makes RoleAssigment to RoleAssigmentMixin class:
 - was removed inheritance from Resource class
 - function names were updated to remove any relationships with Resource
   base methods
 - properties schema was moved out from class
 - validate method was renamed and disctributes for other resources,
   which are inherited from RoleAssigmentMixin
 - corresponding inherited resources and tests were updated

Change-Id: I67c1205406647b89c7c61097fa4dc5f4a463d9f8

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-19 21:49:20.000000000', 'message': "allow configurable pipeline partitioning

existing code will create queues from the cartesian product of the
set of pipelines and the set of agents. these queues are identified
by pipe_type-pipe_name-agent_id. the problem arises where if an agent
dies, any messages left on it's queue will be lost as agent_id's tend
to be unique.

this patch changes the logic so rather than using the number of agents
as the set we build our cartesian product from, we use a set of numbers
of a configurable size. by default, it will be a set of 10 so that queues
are created from the product set of the set of pipelines and the set
{0, 1, 2, 3, ... 9}. similarly, the pipelines queues will be identified
by pipe_type-pipe_name-x, where x is value from numerical set. this
way, if an agent dies, the queues are still known and can be
redistributed and processed among the active agents.

Change-Id: I35e3afdd2c9f97ab5bc6bb89531bd20308c5f8c0
Closes-Bug: #1486754

way, if an agent dies, the queues are still known and can be
redistributed and processed among the active agents.

Change-Id: I35e3afdd2c9f97ab5bc6bb89531bd20308c5f8c0
Closes-Bug: #1486754
"}]
commit_message:
allow configurable pipeline partitioning

existing code will create queues from the cartesian product of the
set of pipelines and the set of agents. these queues are identified
by pipe_type-pipe_name-agent_id. the problem arises where if an agent
dies, any messages left on it's queue will be lost as agent_id's tend
to be unique.

this patch changes the logic so rather than using the number of agents
as the set we build our cartesian product from, we use a set of numbers
of a configurable size. by default, it will be a set of 10 so that queues
are created from the product set of the set of pipelines and the set
{0, 1, 2, 3, ... 9}. similarly, the pipelines queues will be identified
by pipe_type-pipe_name-x, where x is value from numerical set. this
way, if an agent dies, the queues are still known and can be
redistributed and processed among the active agents.

Change-Id: I35e3afdd2c9f97ab5bc6bb89531bd20308c5f8c0
Closes-Bug: #1486754

commit_message:
Add support for drizzle jdbc connector

Mysql jdbc connector returns an Integer when querying period and period.
Drizzle jdbc connector returns a Long. Adding appropriate conversions
that are used by monasca-api and monasca-thresh.

Change-Id: I4282b7de3fcbd82b3196bce1b4379076eff60bbc

subject: [WIP] Initial work for multinode support
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 3153, 'name': 'Emilien Macchi', 'email': 'emilien@redhat.com', 'username': 'emilienm'}, {'_account_id': 4162, 'name': 'Paul Belanger', 'email': 'pabelanger@redhat.com', 'username': 'pabelanger'}, {'_account_id': 8482, 'name': 'Colleen Murphy', 'email': 'colleen@gazlene.net', 'username': 'krinkle'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-19 23:57:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2015-08-20 00:01:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This is adding a new script to install modules to a different location, when I really think the root cause of the test failures is that we need to run as root. Even if we install r10k and the modules in a non-privileged-user-friendly location, we still need to run puppet itself as root. Do you disagree?'}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 00:07:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

My issue with the current script, is we don't need root permissions to install gems.  I do not know why we are defaulting to that, I likely know why, but we should not use sudo for this.

To me, it is a personal preference. Install modules that you need into the local directory, then have puppet run (as root) from it. This way, we don't pollute the local file system for untracked modules.  Especially if we are doing puppet apply, if we are using a puppet master, that is a different discussion."}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 00:08:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I should also note, there is discussion in -infra to move our system-config / project-config files from /etc/puppet/modules. We'd likely default into /opt/ or some other path."}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 00:13:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Another reason for this, which I forgot, is I plan to hack in --noop support as well, for fast failing local testing.  While this will not be used in the gate, it will allow somebody to use there current laptop to quickly test puppet and not affect the root file system.'}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2015-08-20 00:18:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> My issue with the current script, is we don't need root permissions to install gems. I do not know why we are defaulting to that, I likely know why, but we should not use sudo for this.

For testing gems it makes sense to isolate gems in a local environment. r10k is a deployment utility so it should be installed globally.

> To me, it is a personal preference. Install modules that you need into the local directory, then have puppet run (as root) from it. This way, we don't pollute the local file system for untracked modules. Especially if we are doing puppet apply, if we are using a puppet master, that is a different discussion.

A personal preference does not dictate best practice. Typical mode of operations (which is something we should be striving toward since we intend to imitate what people are using in production environments) is to install in /etc/puppet/modules or /etc/puppet/environments/$environment/modules. Otherwise we have to modify the modulepath in puppet.conf or always run puppet apply with $MODULEPATH set.

> This way, we don't pollute the local file system for untracked modules.

We can rm -rf /etc/puppet/modules/* as a pre-suite step, which we do already in the beaker-rspec acceptance tests.

In summary I feel that this patch makes a lot of workarounds for something that I don't see as a real problem."}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2015-08-20 00:22:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> Another reason for this, which I forgot, is I plan to hack in --noop support as well, for fast failing local testing. While this will not be used in the gate, it will allow somebody to use there current laptop to quickly test puppet and not affect the root file system.

I support this initiative. I wish this had been voiced up front, as we cannot have a productive open discussion if we don't all know the plan.

What about having the script accept an environment variable to set the module install path? And perhaps this is something that could be done in the future patch that adds --noop support?"}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 00:23:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Fair enough, this is my attempt at running the puppet-openstack-integration module locally.

Again, requiring sudo to install gems, unmanaged by puppet, does not make sense.  Best practice or not, requiring un-necessary root access for bash script is just dangerous.  If this can be installed as non privileged users, I do so. Other wise, I no easy way of tracking what gets installed onto the file system.

I don't see this as unreasonable request, do you?"}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 00:27:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yes, in fact, I am going to use this patchset to fully support all the initial features I am wanting to do with this module. Multi-node, --noop support, minus sudo, the works.

I plan work on this and try to get a demo in place for mid-cycle, so I can better explain and even show people how it works.  

Sadly, I missed out on the initial design of this module, and been hoping the mid-cycle will get us all a better plan to be head down on it.

Either way, consider this patch a WIP. And feel free to continue working on the other patchset.  For the moment, I'll yield to the plan you and the others have for the module.  Does that work?"}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2015-08-20 00:38:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> Again, requiring sudo to install gems, unmanaged by puppet, does not make sense. Best practice or not, requiring un-necessary root access for bash script is just dangerous. If this can be installed as non privileged users, I do so. Other wise, I no easy way of tracking what gets installed onto the file system.
> I don't see this as unreasonable request, do you?

Not unreasonable, but since this is a throwaway node I don't see it as necessary.

As a compromise, could we remove r10k from the Gemfile, and keep the gem install r10k but add --install-dir to install to a local directory? This gives us control over the privileges needed but also keeps the Gemfile cleaner, prevents r10k from being bundle installed in lint tests, and allows the install_modules.sh script to be used on a remote node that doesn't have access to the Gemfile."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-20 01:02:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1
