> Yes, in fact, I am going to use this patchset to fully support all the initial features I am wanting to do with this module. Multi-node, --noop support, minus sudo, the works.

I look forward to this! I think a challenge we have been having here is not knowing what your vision is and not connecting the dots between the work being done now and goals for the future.

> I plan work on this and try to get a demo in place for mid-cycle, so I can better explain and even show people how it works.

In the spirit of Open Design and Open Development I would rather collaborate than work privately on private designs. We can come up with good solutions if we share all of our ideas up front. If we work privately and then present a solution, we risk the group misunderstanding the question the solution tries to answer, and we risk the solution being something that conflicts with established conventions or expectations. To that end, it would be nice if this demo you plan to work on was accompanied by a blueprint on which we can discuss the problems we want to solve and how we would like to solve them.

> And feel free to continue working on the other patchset. For the moment, I'll yield to the plan you and the others have for the module. Does that work?

This sounds very dispirited and I am sorry for that.

My feeling is that this repo is not a module and it is not intended to be used by our end-users, so I think moving quickly with what we have in the other patches, which is a very simplistic design to just get us off the ground, and then continuing to iterate and expand is a good idea.

We don't have a defined set of requirements, which a blueprint would help with. Right now, just having "set up a single-node openstack and run tempest on it" would be sufficient progress.'}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 01:19:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-20 01:47:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

I agree, this is the big issue I am trying to overcome. I cannot any sort of puppet-spec for the puppet module / project.  Except single node running tempest. As an new contributor to this team, it has been frustrating at time trying to work inside that constraint.  If there is something more official, please link to me a blueprint, I've not been able to find anything.

Again, non of my code will be private, its simply going to be a WIP / demo on a way I see it working.  If time permits, before the mid-cycle I want to get a spec in place for it too.

Dispirited, no / maybe. You and emilien seem to have and existing plan how you see it working.  Any patch I've proposed and either been reverted or pushed down the road.  The truth is, moving out of the way will allow the code to be merged and gates put in place.  Right or wrong, I am blocking this process right now. And don't want to be the reason for this."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-08-20 12:45:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> Dispirited, no / maybe. You and emilien seem to have and existing plan how you see it working.

Let me quote Colleen who exactly summarized our current plan:
" (...) very simplistic design to just get us off the ground, and then continuing to iterate and expand (...) "

> Any patch I've proposed and either been reverted or pushed down the road.

Your patch broke the CI of all our modules having Beaker jobs. I had to fix the CI as soon as possible because all patches were blocked in the gate because of that. This is not my favorite decision I had to take and *I'm sorry for that*. It was not intended to reject your code or whatever again, I wanted to bring CI back.

> Right or wrong, I am blocking this process right now. And don't want to be the reason for this.

Colleen is right, you should bring your voice up to the front and work with the team rather than "plan work on this and try to get a demo in place for mid-cycle". Puppet group is a team and we all use to work together. We don't want individual efforts, and I hope we will make progress on this together.

To summarize the plan, I suggest to:

* Paul to write a blueprint (best option), or an etherpad or whatever we can easily review in the team.
* Me to finalize and make work the basic structure that we initiated together.

I hope we can get both for the mid-cycle, so we can validate the blueprint and start coding.'}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 21:13:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 21:19:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 21:26:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 4162, 'date': '2015-08-20 21:28:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-20 21:35:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

[WIP] Initial work for multinode support

This is dependant on zuulv3 support, so lets mock some of that for now.  We be
using ansiable to handle orchestration.

commit_message:
fix novaclient functional tests for new devstack config

The novaclient functional tests assumed computev21 as a type in the
service catalog. We're defaulting compute in devstack to v21 now, so
this no longer works. This is probably far too coupled to devstack
atm, however until we get to unversioned service catalog, this is what
we need to do.

Change-Id: Ifb0056924b20f62d75d13a7b4aae829df61a5396

hi all -

I never saw this patch.   Are we confident allowing an "expand" to proceed across several major releases at once without any "contract" occurring at all, and then later a "contract" that also spans several major releases at once?  The rationale for the separate heads was so that expand/contract would always be in a per-major-release "sawtooth" type of pattern - expand liberty, contract liberty, expand mitaka, contract mitaka.   by flattening it into a single stream we add more assumptions about the safety of expands and contracts and how they are organized.'}]

commit_message:
Dropped release name from migration branch labels

Since the plan is to attach first Mitaka scripts to Liberty branches
with down_revision, and since labels are inherited from all other
revisions in the chain, using release names in branch labels would mean
that the following commands would be valid:

neutron-db-manage upgrade liberty_expand@<some_revision_from_mitaka>
neutron-db-manage upgrade mitaka_expand@<some_revision_from_liberty>

which may be confusing to users.

So let's drop release names from branch labels and use expand@head and
contract@head to access latest migrations.

Change-Id: Id524d7673ad248c831f6dbb3a6f2f3c50094acae
Partially-Implements: blueprint online-schema-migrations

[{'created': '2015-09-03 11:14:15.000000000', 'message': "Fixing haproxy-playbook fails when installing on multiple hosts

This bug is triggered when haproxy is deployed on multiple hosts
and external_lb_vip is different than the internal one.
As all host receive the same configuration, and are expected
to restart the haproxy service more than once
(once during role and once post_tasks), the playbook will fail,
because the restart of the service fails. The restart of the
service fails on some hosts because haproxy tries to
start/bind to an ip the host doesn't have (avoiding ip conflicts)

This allows haproxy to bind on non_local addresses by
addng a sysctl change in the playbook: net.ipv4.ip_nonlocal_bind = 1
The sysctl is changed for the containers/systems
when external_lb_vip is different than internal address and
the number of haproxy hosts is more than one thanks to a group_var.

Side-effect: other services are able to bind on non-local addresses
if the sysctl is changed.

This could be overriden by setting the variable haproxy_bind_on_non_local
in your user_* variables. If set to false, then the ip_non_local_bind
sysctl won't be changed.

Closes-Bug: #1487409

commit_message:
Fixing haproxy-playbook fails when installing on multiple hosts

This bug is triggered when haproxy is deployed on multiple hosts
and external_lb_vip is different than the internal one.
As all host receive the same configuration, and are expected
to restart the haproxy service more than once
(once during role and once post_tasks), the playbook will fail,
because the restart of the service fails. The restart of the
service fails on some hosts because haproxy tries to
start/bind to an ip the host doesn't have (avoiding ip conflicts)

This allows haproxy to bind on non_local addresses by
addng a sysctl change in the playbook: net.ipv4.ip_nonlocal_bind = 1
The sysctl is changed for the containers/systems
when external_lb_vip is different than internal address and
the number of haproxy hosts is more than one thanks to a group_var.

Side-effect: other services are able to bind on non-local addresses
if the sysctl is changed.

This could be overriden by setting the variable haproxy_bind_on_non_local
in your user_* variables. If set to false, then the ip_non_local_bind
sysctl won't be changed.

Closes-Bug: #1487409

Change-Id: I41b3a5a4ba2d48192b505e3720456a77484aa92b
(cherry picked from commit 9df04fed70eb9f9e84f6da2ac5bb4d94df037fe6)

commit_message:
Raise exceptions from BanditConfig rather than exit

Application code shouldn't be calling sys.exit since it prevents the
caller from being able to continue if it wants and it makes unit
testing more difficult. Raise an exception instead.

Change-Id: I12e46ba564912ba2b55f18bbe5b5b6c81f6d7c78

commit_message:
Add driver and driver_info fields to Port

This will allow the network providers change to specify the networks
driver by port, rather than as a config option for all nodes managed by
a conductor. It will also allow for metadata used by the networks driver
to be placed in driver_info, such as switchport and switch ID for the
neutron_plugin driver.

Change-Id: I7229c4797ce3776592b1f3625552ba5963b26389
Implements: blueprint network-provider

commit_message:
Activate pep8 check that _ is imported

Remove the specification in tox.ini that _ is a builtin so that
it will no longer assume that _ does not need to be imported.
This helps ensure that the _ from i18n is used.

Activating this check did not flag any violations.

Change-Id: I1f156dbcd17b32c43c23731161d76ed2904f187f

commit_message:
Added snmp declarative hardware pollster

The snmp declarative hardware pollster loads the metric definition from
a special yaml file and can poll those metrics. This enables the
developers to modify the yaml file only to add new snmp metrics without
writing any new python code.

Added a new classmethod interface build_pollsters for PollsterBase. The
pollster plugin which implements this interface should return a list of
tuple (name, pollster), where name is the meter name it will return, and
pollster is the pollster object instances. All the pollsters returned by
this would be wrapped in stevedore extensions in
PollsterBase.get_pollster_extensions().

This pollster doesn't get registered temporarily to avoid duplicating
samples. Will be registered in the following patches when old snmp
pollsters are deleted.

Implements: blueprint declarative-snmp-metrics

Change-Id: I5abbe704cc08ea84aacf742eda7cee215141c3bb

commit_message:
Added CORS support to Keystone

This adds the CORS support middleware to Keystone, allowing a deployer
to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client may
break the single-origin policy and access the API directly. Included
are Keystone's auth headers, so that anyone activating this
middleware does not have to explicitly enable them.

OpenStack CrossProject Spec:
   http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/cors-support.html
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
OpenStack Cloud Admin Guide:
   http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/cross_project_cors.html

Change-Id: If58ad7d952ace9211f0ed8beff8552c216262382

with the id being HP_MAP

Hey Tom,

I'm still not sure why this is needed. The client would pretty much just does a curl command and needs a valid keystone token in order for it to be performed.
Note: You can also always do a mapping list and see all the mapping ids, if its enabled in policy.json

So the only thing I can think of is:
"identity:list_mappings": "rule:admin_required" 

and you don't want the non-admin user to get try and guess mapping names getting 404s until they find a valid one and then they can see that mapping, they will get 500 instead and will think there is another problem and stop. That may not be the case since the the guesses will most likely be automated.

This also messes with an admin who is able to get secrets, he/she will go an unexpected error and won't know whats going on.'}, {'account_id': 8866, 'date': '2015-08-27 20:55:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Even with this more information, I think that we shouldn't do this, since this will just be painful to the ops.

I recommend for you create a bug in the launchpad, and ask for some core to triage this bug, but imho I didn't see any benefits in change this exception and raise a 500."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-27 22:04:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

i also think it is unnecessary.'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2015-08-28 08:29:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Hi Tom,

1) As other have already pointed out stricly CRUD operation on mappings are reserved for admins. Therefore I don't see any security risk with current approach. In fact, admin should be able to detect quickly what's going on and obfuscating root cause of the problem by giving ambiguous error codes is IMHO not a way to go.

2) If your main concern was that server may be misconfigured and user cannot authenticate due to miscofiguration and then he should get HTTP 500 instead of MappingNotFound exception - can explain where is may help malicious users to break into system? OK, something is for sure misconfigured, but again, user reporting Mapping not Found exception will give better hint to admins rather. 

3) When it comes to returning HTTP 500 on mapping GET operations - we should also change the logic for all other entities - users, domains, tokens, projects and whatever we have in Keystone. I think your initial intention was to return HTTP 5000 when mapping is not found when user wants to authenticate, right? Then I can somehow understand your reasoning, yet I am not super convinced it's a good way.

4) Lastly, what was the reason for raising exception.UnexpectedError(mapping_id=mapping_id) if not for giving some information about missing mapping and...eventually revealing where the problem may be? 

Oh, and please remove my gmail account from the reviewers list adn add my cern one :-)"}, {'account_id': 17123, 'date': '2015-08-28 13:51:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thank you guys for all you awesome responses.  I am new to Openstack and am excited to be working somewhere where people are this vocal. 

@Marek I am going to try to write some tests to show cases where the server should be returning a 500 error instead of a 404 error.  Then I will open a bug for the problem.  I do agree with you we should keep it non-ambiguous for the admin and ambiguous for the user.'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2015-08-28 13:59:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Tom,

Yep, as soon as you find real use cases where current design would lead to security risk we will probably change it :-) 
While i said errors exposed to admins should not be ambiguous I didn't say they should be for users. I do not have super string opinions on that matter to be honest."}, {'account_id': 7725, 'date': '2015-09-03 18:47:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
MappingNotFound should be a UnexpectedError

The client shouldn't see a MappingNotFound error when they have an
incorrect mapping.  This is a security issue and is releasing too much information to the client. We fix this issue by making the
error more ambiguous, throwing a 'UnexpectedError'
instead.

We also updated test cases that expected a '404 Not Found' error
instead of a '500 Internal Server Error'.

Change-Id: I543907b403c20f39cea152474b95e675deb1a46a
Co-Authored-By: Christopher J. Schaefer <cjschaef@us.ibm.com>

Sahara was removed from default services that run DevStack in gates
We need to remove these scenarios from rally.yaml and add separate job
for Sahara

Change-Id: Id9a8cb0d6c251a2b736d7f0d79a15d1255d46c8b

commit_message:
Added note about multiple values for some filters

The aggregate_image_properties_isolation and aggregate_instance_extra_specs
filters are capable of accepting multiple values as a comma-separated list.
This change specifies that in the documentation. Note that the original bug
touches two other filters as well (aggregate_multitenancy_isolation_filter
and availability_zone_filter), however these aren't mentioned in this book.

Change-Id: If2a3f0757fde2e63a86f5c212579d78f4113ea0e
Closes-Bug: 1427706

commit_message:
Return multiple iSCSI portals in VNX Cinder driver

Return multiple iSCSI portals (using keys target_portals, target_iqns
and target_luns) in VNX Cinder driver whether the multipath option
is used or not. A single portal is continuously being returned in
target_portal, target_iqn and target_lun for drivers other than
libvirt driver.

Change-Id: Ibfd989d10a65a3b87647f3d7a4ff3596d822eec9

commit_message:
Add experimental puppet-unit job for single node

Here we are adding a experimental job to loop over all our puppet-unit
specs on a single host. We can do this, because we are sandboxing all
our gems into local directories.

Change-Id: I1c32f8dd7e03ef883d4e88cadf488b3f51eeddca
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Added the support of Glance Artifact Repository

This patch adds a support of 'Murano Package' Glance artifact type to
the murano client. The ArtifactRepo class wraps the standard Glance's
V3 client and provides access to Glance Artifacts as to Murano
Packages.
Another class, called PackageManagerAdapter provides a temporary
facade which makes artifact-based packages compatible with the legacy
packages.

Depends-on: I11efa3758cea5eb459a101d62c93355f34bb42f9
Change-Id: I35d71bb7c03b23b01722e060c3ef770a24168ada
Implements-Blueprint: artifact-repository-support

commit_message:
Glance MuranoPackage Artifact

Adds an artifact type for Glance V3 to define murano package, its
specific properties and binary objects (full package, logo and a ui
definition).

As a temporary workaround to simplify search a 'keywords' field is added
to contain display name and tags word-by-word, so any of them may be
used to locate a package. This will be inefficient in terms of DB
performance, but at least not worse then the legacy solution.

Implements-blueprint: artifact-repository-support
Change-Id: I11efa3758cea5eb459a101d62c93355f34bb42f9

commit_message:
Don't use positional for keypair loaded

This may cause problems in the future using a positional
parameter here if the order changes.

Change-Id: I9f37620b2f12453d86bddbb631ae3f0b8eb30580

commit_message:
Introduce wildcards to blacklist_calls plugin

This change makes it so wildcards can be used in bandit.yaml when
configuring function calls that should be alerted on.  For example, it
allows 'telnetlib.*' to be set as a blacklist entry, and will then
alert on a call to telnetlib.Telnet() and any other functions in that
namespace.

It uses stdlib's fnmatch, which means the wildcards are Unix shell
style.

This change also hijacks the telnetlib import check, adding a wildcarded
blacklist calls check as described above and adjusting tests and
example naming accordingly.

Change-Id: I0ff5891282ab762fd3dfc0447b20028d81d9afef

ceilometer/event/converter.py has the code that processes default traits. That code should be updated to treat tenant/project and user ids as default traits so that we do not have to add them to each thing in the yaml file. The event_definitions.yaml file has a mix of things using tenant_id and things using project_id. These are synonymous, so I would suggest always filling both (from the default traits handling mentioned above, not the yaml). [{'created': '2015-08-11 11:17:49.000000000', 'message': "Add user_id,project_id traits to audit events

The ceilometer audit events currently don't have user/project
information associated with it. This is required to apply RBAC.
This changeset will add user_id and project_id traits to the
audit events namely *.http.*

Change-Id: If4034342c4e60d519f0ec96ae8895dcf78f8ad3b
blueprint: events-rbac
"}, {'created': '2015-08-11 13:06:42.000000000', 'message': "Add user_id,project_id traits to audit events

The ceilometer audit events currently don't have user/project
information associated with it. This is required to apply RBAC.
This changeset will add user_id and project_id traits to the
audit events namely *.http.*

Change-Id: If4034342c4e60d519f0ec96ae8895dcf78f8ad3b
blueprint: events-rbac
"}, {'created': '2015-08-13 12:06:19.000000000', 'message': "Add user_id,project_id traits to audit events

The ceilometer audit events stored at the ceilometer database
currently don't have user_id/project_id associated with them
even though this information is available as part of the event
message payload. The user_id and project_id information has to
be stored as traits so that there's user/project context for each
event and these traits are required to apply RBAC-based rules
and filters on events. For eg., presence of these traits enable
db queries - like get all events for a project/user against events
The audit event definition in the events yaml file already stores
payload.initiator.id as initiator_id but the initiator_id trait
is not a common trait across all events and thus this trait cannot
be used to apply RBAC filter against events.This changeset will

commit_message:
Add user_id,project_id traits to audit events

The ceilometer audit events stored at the ceilometer database
currently don't have user_id/project_id associated with them
even though this information is available as part of the event
message payload. The user_id and project_id information has to
be stored as traits so that there's user/project context for each
event and these traits are required to apply RBAC-based rules
and filters on events. For eg., presence of these traits enable
db queries - like get all events for a project/user against events.
The audit event definition in the events yaml file already stores
payload.initiator.id as initiator_id but the initiator_id trait
is not a common trait across all events and thus this trait cannot
be used to apply RBAC filter against events.This changeset will
thus add user_id and project_id traits to the audit events namely
*.http.* and add useri_id and project_id as default traits for all
events.

DocImpact

Change-Id: If4034342c4e60d519f0ec96ae8895dcf78f8ad3b
blueprint: events-rbac

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-21 11:26:00.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Update how neutron migrations are handled

We're seeing some neutron db sync failures in master branch (liberty).
It looks like there may be a few issues with the way we're handling
migrations:

1. We're not capturing the correct information in the 'Check last DB
   revision' task as the first line returned by 'neutron-db-manage
   history' is a header (this also means that the 'Inspect on disk
   neutron DB revision' task will never do what we intend).
2. We delegate 'Check last DB revision' to 'neutron_all' group, but in
   an ideal world this is probably only necessary on 'neutron_server'.
3. When stopping neutron server to run 'Perform a Neutron DB Upgrade',
   we're only stopping it on groups['neutron_server'][0], while all
   other neutron server containers are up servicing requests.
4. Perform a db stamp, which doesn't appear to be necessary.

This change makes the following changes:

1. Checks if migrations have previously run, and if not runs a
   'neutron-db-manage upgrade heads'
2. If migrations have previously run:
   a) it runs an online migration against liberty_expand@head alembic
      branch.
   b) it stops all neutron-server services
   c) it runs an offline migration against liberty_contract@head branch
   d) t starts all neutron-server instances

TODO: Currently, we upgrade liberty_expand@head and
      liberty_contract@head (shutting down neutron-server in the
      proceses), even if there are no pending migrations.  We need to
      find a clean way to check what migration we are on and compare to
      alembic HEADS file to see if we're up to date.  Unfortunately,
      'neutron-db-manage current' doesn't indicate which migration is
      in which alembic branch, so you would have to further grep for
      each migration in the neutron migrations code to determine the
      branch.

NOTE: Liberty introduces the split alembic branches for online/offline
      migrations, see [1] for more information.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/neutron/devref/alembic_migrations.html

Change-Id: I1176b5fe12cad1ee732486ae179e76deea5623e1
Closes-Bug: #1486593

"}, {'created': '2015-09-01 13:30:51.000000000', 'message': "Update how neutron migrations are handled

We're seeing some neutron db sync failures in master branch (liberty).
It looks like there may be a few issues with the way we're handling
migrations:

1. We're not capturing the correct information in the 'Check last DB
   revision' task as the first line returned by 'neutron-db-manage
   history' is a header (this also means that the 'Inspect on disk
   neutron DB revision' task will never do what we intend).

3. When stopping neutron server to run 'Perform a Neutron DB Upgrade',
   we're only stopping it on groups['neutron_server'][0], while all
   other neutron server containers are up servicing requests.
4. Perform a db stamp, which doesn't appear to be necessary.

This change makes the following changes:

1. Bumps neutron SHA to include 43c00a9, which introduces new
   --expand / --contract upgrade options (otherwise, you have to
   specify liberty_expand@head / liberty_contract@head which may no
   longer work when neutron gets bumped in the future)

   'neutron-db-manage upgrade heads'

   b) it stops all neutron-server services
   c) it runs an offline migration against contract alembic branch
      using 'neutron-db-manage upgrade --contract'
   d) it starts all neutron-server instances

commit_message:
Update how neutron migrations are handled

We're seeing some neutron db sync failures in master branch (liberty).
It looks like there may be a few issues with the way we're handling
migrations:

1. We're not capturing the correct information in the 'Check last DB
   revision' task as the first line returned by 'neutron-db-manage
   history' is a header (this also means that the 'Inspect on disk
   neutron DB revision' task will never do what we intend).
2. We delegate 'Check last DB revision' to 'neutron_all' group, but in
   an ideal world this is probably only necessary on 'neutron_server'.
3. When stopping neutron server to run 'Perform a Neutron DB Upgrade',
   we're only stopping it on groups['neutron_server'][0], while all
   other neutron server containers are up servicing requests.
4. Perform a db stamp, which doesn't appear to be necessary.

This change makes the following changes:

1. Bumps neutron SHA to include 43c00a9, which introduces new
   --expand / --contract upgrade options (otherwise, you have to
   specify liberty_expand@head / liberty_contract@head which may no
   longer work when neutron gets bumped in the future)
2. Checks if migrations have previously run, and if not runs a
   'neutron-db-manage upgrade heads'
3. If migrations have previously run:
   a) it runs an online migration against expand alembic branch using
      'neutron-db-manage upgrade --expand'.
   b) it stops all neutron-server services
   c) it runs an offline migration against contract alembic branch
      using 'neutron-db-manage upgrade --contract'
   d) it starts all neutron-server instances
4. It removes the temporary pin introduced in
   https://review.openstack.org/218572 as the SHA bump includes the
   upstream fix https://review.openstack.org/218723

TODO: Currently, we upgrade expand and contract branches (shutting down
      neutron-server in the proceses), even if there are no pending
      migrations.  We need to find a clean way to check what migration
      we are on and compare to alembic HEADS file to see if we're up to
      date.  Unfortunately, 'neutron-db-manage current' doesn't indicate
      which migration is in which alembic branch, so you would have to
      further grep for each migration in the neutron migrations code to
      determine the branch.

NOTE: Liberty introduces the split alembic branches for online/offline
      migrations, see [1] for more information.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/neutron/devref/alembic_migrations.html

Change-Id: I1176b5fe12cad1ee732486ae179e76deea5623e1
Closes-Bug: #1486593

commit_message:
Add advanced checks to net templates tests

Perform advanced cheks in tests for networking
templates feature:

 * run network verification before/after
   environment deployment;

 * check IP settings on slaves correspond
   to network configuration in template;

 * check that services are listening on
   networks according to assigned network
   roles in template.

Also increase deployment timeout to 180 minutes.

Related blueprint templates-for-networking
Closes-bug: #1491768

Change-Id: I40b898e24942502654310a842178941198157b60

commit_message:
Fix usage of netaddr '.broadcast'

netaddr 0.7.16 changed the behavior of IPNetworks with /31 and /32
prefixes to make their 'broadcast' attribute return None. This patch
replaces the use of the attribute with a -1 index lookup to get the
last address instead.

Closes-Bug: #1490380
Change-Id: I97d71c4051882ddd9e496c78cfbce840ad7a2b67
(cherry picked from commit 6324f7f23d5debecf7201a371050e20527550a8c)

In the function Cinder.backup.API.import_record(), there are following codes:
        backup = objects.Backup(context=context, **kwargs)
        backup = objects.TemporaryBackupImport()
        first_host = hosts.pop()
        self.backup_rpcapi.import_record(context,
                                         first_host,
                                         backup,
                                         backup_service,
                                         backup_url,
                                         hosts)
        return backup

I think it should be changed to 
        backup = objects.Backup(context=context, **kwargs)
        backup = objects.TemporaryBackupImport()
        first_host = hosts.pop()
        # here is the change. 
        backup =      self.backup_rpcapi.import_record(context,
                                         first_host,
                                         backup,
                                         backup_service,
                                         backup_url,
                                         hosts)
        return backup'}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-07-03 04:04:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-14 21:35:08.000000000', 'message': "Fix backup metadata import missing fields

When importing backup metadata only required fields were being imported,
and all other fields were being ignored.

This lead to some serious problems when importing metadata back, since
you would lose not only the original Volume ID, but also relevant parent
id information needed to restore incremental backups.

This patch fixes this by importing everything back.

Since API creates a Backup with its own ID we have several cases:
 - Imported backup ID doesn't exist in DB: Update API Backup record with
   the new backup ID
 - Imported backup ID exist in the DB:
   * Backup is available, deleted, error: Update existing record and
     delete from the DB the record that was created by the API
   * In other case: Raise exception

Closes-Bug: #1455043
Change-Id: Ia42ba73e9078d993c63f8e16308151ad11721ea9

commit_message:
Fix backup metadata import missing fields

When importing backup metadata only required fields were being imported,
and all other fields were being ignored.

This led to some serious problems when importing backups back, since
you would lose not only the original Volume ID, but also relevant parent
id information needed to restore incremental backups.

This patch fixes this by importing everything back and creating backup
records with the right ID.

Closes-Bug: #1455043
Closes-Bug: #1476416
Depends-On: Id7ab6e174c1fe85772477f03059c4f457c5c8b17
Change-Id: Ia42ba73e9078d993c63f8e16308151ad11721ea9

Cloud Foundry Service Broker API initial commit

In this commit we added new murano service called murano-cfapi.
It's Cloud Foundry Service Broker API implementation for OpenStack.

* add new entrypoint for murano-cfapi
* add provision/deprovision operations for Cloud Foundry.

partial-implement: bp cloudfoundry-api-support

commit_message:
Use addCleanup rather than tearDown

addCleanup is safer since it's called even if there's an exception
in setUp.

Change-Id: I28d219b5bf0bb14bde757f8f7582ba8ccf3bc679

commit_message:
Use testtools rather than unittest

Some tests used unittest as the base class while others used
testtools. All the tests now use testtools since it provides more
functionality.

testtools fails if the tearDown doesn't call the super
implementation so this is fixed.

testtools also uses assertRaises differently.

Change-Id: I010010d1eaf32c82b78f72946fef3f59d2305818

commit_message:
Remove redundant quotes in bandit.yaml

Yaml will automatically interpret data types and strings in this
case for the most part.  Some special characters such as '.' still
need to be escaped with quotes.

Change-Id: Ib3237fe52e1c144b9ad6d641c1359ed5e3ab75c6

commit_message:
Changed readme so that example retrieves certificate

Made a change to the URL that the readme uses to demonstrate basic
Anchor functionality. This reflects the default CA setup in the
simple config.json that Anchor ships with today.

Note: The examples for auth/config are still outdated but at least
the README example usage works. auth/config updates can be covered
in another bug/commit.

Change-Id: I17b9580956baa5644b9a437a4da86ed232c4a76a

'}, {'created': '2015-08-30 22:03:57.000000000', 'message': 'Version-aware YAML loading

* Refactoring of "packages" Python package
* Now MuranoPL YAML classes can be parsed by different engines
depending on Format string in package manifest

With this change MuranoPL classes will no longer
be read and parsed (including YAQL expressions parsing)
upon package load but only on first class access and
with ability to peak different parsers depending on
format version specified in manifest. As a consequence
it is now possible to use different YAQL engines for
different package format versions. Also startup
time was greatly improved as unneeded classes are no more
parsed and logos and UI forms are not loaded.

commit_message:
Version-aware YAML loading

* Refactoring of "packages" Python package
* Now MuranoPL YAML classes can be parsed by different engines
depending on Format string in package manifest

With this change MuranoPL classes will no longer
be read and parsed (including YAQL expressions parsing)
upon package load but only on first class access and
with ability to peak different parsers depending on
format version specified in manifest. As a consequence
it is now possible to use different YAQL engines for
different package format versions. Also startup
time was greatly improved as unneeded classes are no more
parsed and logos and UI forms are not loaded.

Partially implements: blueprint murano-versioning

Change-Id: I23fc5da1a43b405d526438329dc04aed589dee13

commit_message:
Restores back plugin support

During reworking of how MuranoPL works with packages and
removal or class-loader plugin support code was broken and
temporary disabled. This commit restores previous functionality
using new PackageLoader and MuranoPackage classes

Change-Id: Id43807bfbb9093ddf9a1fbd9273d2fc34e8e5f59

'}, {'created': '2015-08-30 21:56:26.000000000', 'message': 'Package versioning

With this change MuranoPackage become first-class DSL citizens.
Packages have version, runtime_version (that is specified 
in Format attribute of manifest file) and list of classes.
Previously engine use to have package loader which had most
of load functionality and class loader that mostly act as an
adapter from package loader to interface that DSL used to 
get classes. Now class loader is none and replaced with 
package loader at the DSL level. Package loader is responsible
for loading package by either package or class name (as it was 
before) and semantic_version version spec (like ">=1.2,<2.0").
Package loader can keep track of several versions of the same
package.

Also package now have requirements each with version spec.
All class names that encounter in application code are
looked up only within requirements. As a consequence 
packages that use other packages without referencing
them explicitly will break. An exception from this rule
is core library which is referenced automatically.


Partially implements: blueprint murano-versioning

commit_message:
Package versioning

With this change MuranoPackage becomes first-class DSL citizen.
Packages have version, runtime_version (that is specified
in Format attribute of the manifest file) and a list of classes.
Previously engine used to have package loader which had most
of "load" functionality and class loader that mostly acted as an
adapter from package loader to interface that DSL used to
get classes. Now class loader is gone and is replaced with
package loader at the DSL level. Package loader is responsible
for loading packages by either package or class name (as it was
before) plus semantic_version spec (for example ">=1.2,<2.0").
Package loader can now keep track of several versions of the same
package.

Also packages now have requirements with version specs.
All class names that are encountered in application code are
looked up within requirements only. As a consequence
packages that use other packages without referencing
them explicitly will become broken. An exception from this rule
is core library which is referenced automatically.

Partially implements: blueprint murano-versioning

Change-Id: I8789ba45b6210e71bf4977a766f82b66d2a2d270

The filtering happens with testr. testr accepts regexes to limit which tests are run. The tests are filtered based upon the test name. When an attribute is added to a test the function name is modified. The function name becomes module.class.function[attribute1]. In this example there is one attribute named attribute1. If there are multiple attributes then the attributes are in a list separated by commas, so if attribute2 was added then it would be module.class.function[attribute1, attribute2].

To only run tests with a 'attribute1' attribute then use the following command:

tox -e functional -- .*\[.*attribute1.*\]

The regex would be a little different for skipping tests with an attribute. I have not tried this yet, so the regex may not be totally correct. I imagine it will look something like:

tox -e functional -- (((\w|\d)+\.?)+[^\]]$)|(\[((?!attribute2).)+\]$)"}, {'account_id': 8623, 'date': '2015-09-03 16:13:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Oof that regex looks horrible.  

There's an example from this site: https://ask.openstack.org/en/question/25742/how-to-run-testcases-in-tempest-for-a-particular-attributes-like-smokegate/

$ testr list-tests tempest.api.network | grep negative > /tmp/negative_tests

$ testr run --load-list=/tmp/negative_tests

Do you think something like that could work, too?  Could you document how to run the tests, perhaps in another patch?"}, {'account_id': 8623, 'date': '2015-09-03 16:18:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-03 16:18:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

commit_message:
Stanardized Functional Tests

The functional tests included some tests for creating AES keys with
different bit lengths. Most of those bit lengths were not valid. The
tests can cause some secret stores to return failures because the key
lengths were not valid. The tests were also setting the bit length to
different values but not modifying the payload. The payload is now
being created for the appropriate bit length.

One of the tests was passing the algorithm and bit length as part of a
storage operation. The algorithm name was invalid. This can cause some
failures on devices that do not support that algorithm.

The tests that use non-standard algorithms or bit lengths were
decorated with a non-standard-algorithm attribute. This will allow
testers to skip those tests when selecting which ones to run.

Change-Id: Ia425abef9232cd6729a23e87cbf8153f211a49a3

commit_message:
Experimental multinode job for puppet-openstack-integration

This is the first step needed to run a multinode environment for
puppet-openstack-integration module. For now, this is experimental and
will require some time to flesh out some of nodepool functionality.

Currently run_multinode.sh does not exist, however once this gate has
been added, we'll be able to upload our patch containing it.  This
will give the puppet openstack team a simple multinode job to work
with to better understand nodepool subnodes lifecycle.

Change-Id: Ibac4c9af362d9a6c548b9d0d672f9ace3020f0cc
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Copy the code of Glance V3 (artifacts) client

As Glance Program has decided not to release the client for
EXPERIMENTAL v3 API in its python-glanceclient library until the API
is considered stable, we cannot consume artifacts API from any of the
released glance clients.

It was decided (see [1]) to temporary copy the v3 client code from
python-glanceclient into the python-muranoclient so murano may consume
it without depending on custom builds of glance client. This patch
copies appropriate code.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072740.html

Implements-blueprint: artifact-repository-support
Change-Id: I7905f7c7613c976216be7887f0444e1a09835287

commit_message:
Add timeout to the openstack comamnd

* Timeout openstack command after 20 seconds
  in case if it's not responding.
* Retry failed openstack comamnds

Change-Id: I63b7d6e89888d9fc97ecf88c46a01ece80ca9c63
Related-Bug: 1490523

commit_message:
Collecting stats with enabled SSL fixed

In case of enabled SSL for cluster we should set 'https_proxy'
environment variable.
We can't validate SSL certificate due to:
 - https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1491805
 - https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1491811
As temporary workaround SSL verification disabled for stats fetchers.

Change-Id: If04d99d4293caab50f89fc51209a1e9ca071ab63
Closes-Bug: #1491015

commit_message:
Make sure Neutron_config is applied before Neutron_network

When creating a Neutron_network, the provider will read the actual
configuration file. If Neutron_config has not be applied before, the
default configuration will be used and probably Keystone
authentification will fail.

So this patch aims to make sure neutron.conf is filled before trying to
create a network.

Depends-on: Ibd90e5e159f9a1fbff3990241795894e0bdca3cc
Change-Id: Ia9141cb387a98c70cc639db724da4af4b3289d8a

subject: Make sure Nova_admin_tenant_id_setter is executed after Keystone_endpoint

commit_message:
Make sure Nova_admin_tenant_id_setter is executed after Keystone_endpoint

This patch aims to make sure Nova_admin_tenant_id_setter is run after creating Neutron
endpoint Keystone resource by using the Puppet chain arrow.
Keystone_endpoint is actually the latest resource created by Keystone
providers to make Neutron working.
If Nova_admin_tenant_id_setter resource is in the catalog, it will be executed when
keystone & glance are actually ready and not before.

Depends-on: Ibd90e5e159f9a1fbff3990241795894e0bdca3cc
Change-Id: I095834d3b483db3bf5361f00577e80cfcc6fccc6

commit_message:
Stop reading local config for domain-specific SQL config driver

When an SQL-config-based domain-specific backend was loaded the
local config file (/etc/keystone/keystone.conf) was also read. The
local config file should not be used in this case.

This caused running the tests locally to fail if there were changes
in /etc/keystone/keystone.conf.

Change-Id: Idd095b2df375329f579c164d00dfd50b41b0e96d
Closes-Bug: 1489118

This reverts commit e24ca066bf6160bc1e419aaa5d486cad1aaa937d.

Unfortunately, such a small timeout for hearbeats cause an incredible regression for Astute <-> RabbitMQ connectivity.

Basically, if Astute's sending a huge message to RabbitMQ and by some reason we aren't able to do it within 2 seconds (heartbeat timeout), the connection will be dropped by RabbitMQ server.

In fact, that's happened on SWARM while

* Astute takes almost 100% CPU usage (bug #1491794)
* Astute's sending diagnostic snapshot result message to Nailgun (more than 4MB of data).

Since heartbeats aren't solve the problem we have tried to fix, let's revert it.

Change-Id: I8734541c026b86506a6f735b1eb55371b393921c
Related-Bug: #1461562

commit_message:
Revert "Specify heartbeat for connection to RabbitMQ"

Unfortunately, such a small timeout for hearbeats cause an incredible
regression for Astute <-> RabbitMQ connectivity.

Basically, if Astute's sending a huge message to RabbitMQ and by some
reason we aren't able to do it within 2 seconds (heartbeat timeout),
the connection will be dropped by RabbitMQ server.

In fact, that's happened on SWARM while

* Astute takes almost 100% CPU usage (bug #1491794)
* Astute's sending diagnostic snapshot result message to Nailgun
  (more than 4MB of data).

Since heartbeats aren't solve the problem we have tried to fix, let's
revert the original commit e24ca066bf6160bc1e419aaa5d486cad1aaa937d.

Change-Id: I8734541c026b86506a6f735b1eb55371b393921c
Related-Bug: #1461562

Hi Chris, thanks for documenting this. I started to review it, but I don't think it flows well. I think Dmitry is right; we should write this as if it is the Liberty release, even though we don't know yet what the release will be. By that I mean that one would think we should write this using whatever defaults are in ironic, but I think we want to write it using API version 1.11. If we do that, we can put a note/link to a different section that describes the enrolling differences for Kilo. What do you think?

We really should have a separate install guide for each release. Although I am not sure what that means with the new release model we're going to use. But if we could even have something to reflect the OpenStack release cycles, that would be a good start :) Anyway, that's outside the scope of this particular patch!"}, {'account_id': 13997, 'date': '2015-08-16 10:07:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

This patch add an example of how to create a node using different
API versions.

commit_message:
Make sure rabbitmq package is installed

Ensure that rabbitmq package is installed before murano
service configuration.

DocImpact: detached RabbitMQ + Murano resulting in rabbitmq being
installed on the controller anyway.

Change-Id: Ia8852a625566ab1742e584d742e9820329328e0c
Closes-Bug: #1491334

commit_message:
Create openstack-base container

This creates and moves the dependencies for Ubuntu into a common
openstack-base container. This commit shows dramatically smaller
sizes for all non-openstack containers. The Openstack container remain
the same size.

Change-Id: I2f46420d4b9edcfddda374caddcce906fc708f6c
Partially-Implements: blueprint openstack-common-container

commit_message:
Reduce install size

This is a trade-off, it increases the base size some _but_ it
decreases the total size by a few hundred MB.

Partially-Implements: blueprint openstack-common-container

Change-Id: I1216deed122aa734e0c84325264a53711d94ea4c

I am also wondering if the use of image metadata or falvor-spec should be documented somewhere: I don't think an admin should read the code to know how to use them..."}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2015-02-10 16:20:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Thank you for your comments. After the upload of patch 5 I cannot answer in line to comments for patch 4, so I will do here. 

I will report below your comments for driver.py and my answer to them.

Line 3818
guest.os_bios_reboot_timeout = flavor.extra_specs.get(	
			'hw:reboot_timeout', image_meta.get('properties', {}).get(	
			'hw_reboot_timeout', None))	

- Claudiu Belu: I would split out those .get methods, so it is clear that you're trying to get.

image_reboot_timeout = image_meta.get('properties', {}).get('hw_reboot_timeout', None)
guest.os_bios_reboot_timeout = flavor.extra_specs.get('hw:reboot_timeout', image_reboot_timeout)

-  my answer: While I agree your proposal is more readable, the code here looks like the code just above to enable the boot menu in libvirt - I got inspiration for my patch by that code.

I don't feel much comfortable to write in a different way a code that basically does the same thing and that is so close - pep8 style guide also stress to be consistent with surrounding code.

- Claudiu Belu: Also, I don't know about this, but I also think that having values between... let's say between 0 and 2000 can cause issues.

I mean, maybe a user will think that the timeout will be in seconds and set the flavor value to 10. That will mean that the instance will reboot every 10 milliseconds? Wouldn't that be an issue? And the user won't immediately know about this. He will just see that his instance is not working.

- my answer: The reboot happens only if the instance is not able to find any bootable device. In normal situations this doesn't happen at all in openstack (you have to specify a booatble volume or an image when creating an instance and it is also the first device from which the instance try to boot), but with a boot menu enabled an user can select a non bootable volume.

Anyway with a working instance after the first reboot the instance will boot from the correct device.

Even with a broken instance (that will go in a reboot loop) the user watching the boot phase with a vnc has some time to read the logs, until the "No more bootable device" message appears. From that moment the reboot timeout starts - immediately if the it is just few milliseconds.

Anyway I don't feel like we should restrict the libvirt allowed range to values > 2 sec: for an instance with a working boot device it may be desirable to have a 0 rebbot timeout.

On the other hand I totally agree that the fact the time is specified in milliseconds should be documented somewhere, any suggestion how to do it?'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2015-02-10 17:07:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2015-02-10 17:07:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

This feels like a feature to me, not a bug fix. Its not clear to me in what cloud use cases this feature is actually useful -- I can see that a boot menu being accessing is useful for building new cloud instances, but in that case why would we want a boot timeout?'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2015-03-06 08:20:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

It is bug-related to the boot menu, which itself is not a bug, in fact was tagged as wish-list, so I agree it is a (trivial)feature and not a bug.

An enabled boot menu gives to an user the choice to select the boot source between several devices, but not all devices are actually bootable. The user can select the wrong device and the VM is stuck on boot screen.

I agree this is not an huge improvement, but it is something available in libvirt and it doesn't impact anything else in openstack, so I don't see why it should not be available in openstack as well."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-03-09 10:48:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: Code-Review-1

I am actually extremely confused about the use case at all. Why are users going into a boot menu after they do a nova boot? Why aren't their available boot options exposed as glance images or snapshots or volumes?"}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2015-03-09 12:37:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

This change doesn't introduce a boot menu, the boot menu possibility is addressed by this change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/138578/ just recently merged.

As use case for the boot menu is presented here: https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1275311

Also after being enabled via flavor extra-spec or image metadata, the boot menu requires an explicit action by the user to be shown (press f12 during the booting phase).

Anyway the bootmenu is a feature of libvirt not controlled by Openstack, so it will show any device attached to the instance as possible boot source, even the ones that are not bootable - in this it acts in the same way of a real machine boot menu. 

Exactly in the fact it is possible to choose a non bootable device as source gives an use case for the change I proposed.

To be honest I find a bit strange you ask here for use case explanation for the boot menu, Sean, since the boot menu feature got your approval."}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2015-03-09 12:47:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

Re-reading my explanation I think it may not result clear that the instance is still booted normally via the image or boot volume chosen during nova boot if there is not an human interaction requiring the boot menu (f12).

Anyway if the user requires the boot menu, the device chosen via that menu will override the default boot source, but for that session only. If the instance is restarted and the boot menu is not required, it will boot again from the default boot device - i.e. the image or boot volume specified with nova boot at instance creation time.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-03-10 10:56:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

ok, it seems like then this needs to be a safety on an existing features. I don't think we should have more flavor or image metadata here. If boot menu is enabled set it to a large value for safety.

Making this another configurable seems overkill."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-19 08:00:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Verified-1

[{'created': '2015-02-06 15:49:13.000000000', 'message': 'Enable BIOS reboot timeout for kvm/qemu instances

This change allows to set the reboot timeout in libvirt domain if the
image metadata (property-name "hw_reboot_timeout") or flavor extra spec
(name "hw:reboot_timeout") is configured to set it.
This reboot timeout controls whether and after how long the guest
should start booting again in case the boot fails.
The value is in milliseconds with maximum of 65535 and special value -1
(default) disables the reboot.
It is especially advantageous in combination with a boot menu enabled,
since in that case the user can select for error a non bootable volume.

Change-Id: I2cab3498ee947d5c35a893d75fd4715255b7751f

commit_message:
Enable BIOS reboot timeout for kvm/qemu instances

This change allows to set the reboot timeout in libvirt domain if the
image metadata (property-name "hw_reboot_timeout") or flavor extra spec
(name "hw:reboot_timeout") is configured to set it.
This reboot timeout controls whether and after how long the guest
should start booting again in case the boot fails.
The value is in milliseconds with maximum of 65535 and special value -1
(default) disables the reboot.
It is especially advantageous in combination with a boot menu enabled,
since in that case the user can select for error a non bootable volume.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I2cab3498ee947d5c35a893d75fd4715255b7751f
Related-Bug: #1275311

commit_message:
Remove the blacklisted nova-cells shelve tests

nova-cells does not support the shelve feature.
Since the nova-cells shelve tests are now disabled using
the tempest feature config options, we can remove the
shelve tests from the blacklist.

Change-Id: Ic819a3d23ab8aa78ea0cfd1673dd859f07f12b40
Closes-bug: 1491152
Depends-On: Ibf1f9aaa63e5f17b7d8774b511940ba8421e0887

"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-02-03 16:47:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I still don't understand why we're adding another metadata store when we seem to pretty much always join it when system_metadata is joined."}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2014-02-03 19:11:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Do not merge

I don't agree with exposing being able to pass arbitrary information to the driver in this way.  I can see why this would be useful, but I'd prefer that we expose something more like "available options" or "available features" and the ability for the user to specify those options/features.  This patch doesn't really play well with an environment where there's multiple hypervisor types.  I mean, you can set driver metadata, but that driver metadata may be meaningless unless you start involving the scheduler to pick a host with the correct driver (You'd have to do the same with my options/features idea as well).

Besides all of that, I also disagree with the implementation of key/value per row. We have plans to move away from that with system_metadata as we always pull all rows from the DB and it's inefficient to store everything in multiple rows.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-02-04 09:47:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

NB if you're looking at heterogeneous hypervisor deployments then the schedular problem already exists with almost every use of image metadata properties, so this proposal isn't making things any worse in that respect. I do agree that we need to standardize on a set of image property keys that are (potentially) applicable across all drivers per https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1275875   Even then though, there'd need to be some thing done in the scheduler since not all drivers will support all image property values."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-02-04 16:03:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: No score

commit_message:
Enabled passing of virt properties when creating instance

The 'virt-properties' extension provides ability to pass
'os-command-line', 'hw_qemu_guest_agent', 'vmware_linked_clone'
at instance creation time.  Libvirt driver
now checks both driver_metadata and image metadata when looking
for 'os_command_line'.

bp: add-ability-to-pass-driver-meta-when-starting-instance

Change-Id: I353393c0d36702624c657ada536233110a1db6cb

'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-02-03 10:14:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

"}, {'account_id': 1525, 'date': '2014-02-03 17:54:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Daniel,

The increase in boot time is negligible (less than a second, I can measure it if this is really a concern) and enabling it globally offers the option of using this method for recovery as well as OS installation. If we tied it to an image property, one would not have the option of attaching an additional volume to boot from as a method of troubleshooting the base install.

I'd like to think most VMs would be treated ephemerally in a cloud but that's not the reality more often than not."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-02-03 18:05:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

With the following commit we are going to gain the ability to override the per-image metadata properties at time of booting instance, so we'll still be able to turn this on on an ad-hoc basis when needed for troubleshooting

  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/68146/

On its own the boot menu may not impose huge delays, but every little delay added in the process certainly adds up, which is why this is not unconditionally enabled in libvirt in the first place."}, {'account_id': 1525, 'date': '2014-02-03 18:47:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Unless I am misunderstanding or misreading that blueprint, it sounds like the functionality will allow for passing options typically settable only in the image properties to the "boot" API call only, not reboot.  Thus, if you decide after your VM has already been created that you want to boot off an image-populated-volume, you would still be out of luck.'}, {'account_id': 1525, 'date': '2014-02-03 18:48:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Would a reasonable compromise be turning this off by default?'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-02-03 18:52:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hmm, well for the reboot call you're out of luck entirely - you can't change QEMU guest configuration at reboot since there's no point at which libvirt has control over reboot. This is something you'd have to have turned on at initial VM boot time. The image_meta properties with override at boot time are the way we're approaching this kind of problem for everything else that is at all related to guest hardware configuration decisions. Global nova.conf entries just aren't appropriate for this, not least because if 2 hosts have different values for this setting as a user you've no way to ensure you can use it."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-02-11 06:03:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-02-11 06:03:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Libvirt allow for enabling BIOS bootmenu

Extends the XML config generator to support a new bootmenu option,
controlled by a new config parameter:

    libvirt.bootmenu = True (default)

When enabled, all but AMI based instances will prompt for bringing
up a boot menu via F12. This allows booting off volumes, for
example, or any device not represented as the first disk.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Iec15e841f92994f04c0feadb22a1dfd0395fd610
Closes-Bug: 1275311

commit_message:
Neutron: Add option to set gateway when creating router

When creating a router, you can specify an external network as a
gateway, but since it requires the network ID it's not something you
can specify statically in a task config. This adds a new option,
set_gateway, to dynamically set the external gateway of a router to
the network that is created as part of the scenario.

This also adds a new function to the Neutron utils, _create_routers,
that creates a network and a given number of subnets and routers.

Change-Id: Id7101a3a47b3a009ba39f08ebd5f2b3bf2fd5ab7

commit_message:
Specify heartbeat for connection to RabbitMQ

There was default heartbeat which was set in RabbitMQ to 580 seconds.
Change it to smaller amount of seconds in order to detect connectivity
problems earlier.

Change-Id: I3674829d525006c7bfad96e725b7ab4d559144e2
Closes-bug: #1483182

commit_message:
Fix Accept header in SAML2 requests

The ; separator allows providing parameters to a type not separating
type options. This means that in strict type checks like those performed
by mod_auth_mellon the check for accept type fails.

Change-Id: Ieeaa74b304921daef68497fec77cc6629ab2f0a2
Closes-Bug: #1488722

commit_message:
unregister_machine blocking logic

Additional logic to preemptively prevent NIC removal when a
machine is unregistered by pre-validating if a node is can be
safely deleted.

commit_message:
Avoid 2.27.0 of novaclient

There is an unfortunate set of bugs out in the wild which make
2.27.0 novaclient non-working against many existing public clouds. Fixes
are in works for 2.28.0 - for now, express that 2.27.0 should not be
used.

Change-Id: Ia6cc574c8ec8bf1290f01d5a602dd2b8ee78549d

commit_message:
Make sure neutron network is created before Tempest_neutron_net_id_setter

In the catalog, Tempest_neutron_net_id_setter requires the network
created before so this manifest can be run in one single puppet run and
be idempotent.

This patch aims to require Neutron_network in the catalog before
Tempest_neutron_net_id_setter.

Change-Id: Ie17fad1ae8fd0072515ca30fcfe91df1347b3391

commit_message:
[ironic-agent] Use svc-map for enabling agent

Switch to using svc-map element for systemd based agent.

This allows both .deb and .rpm installs to share the
element for systemd based installs. There are not any
plans to package a .rpm package for upstart or sysv, so
these are left as is.

Change-Id: Idca7ad97355cae785162989774a7e6dea6fdc5b5
Closes-Bug: #1490584

commit_message:
Adds HostUtilsV2 class

Adds HostUtilsV2 class.
Moves RemoteFX related code to HostUtilsV2.
Refactors utilsfactory in order for utilsfactory.get_hostutils
to return the proper class.

Change-Id: I2077c0c3c01088c3418265c39c148141944f8eb6
Co-Authored-By: Adelina Tuvenie <atuvenie@cloudbasesolutions.com>

[{'created': '2015-08-26 18:45:56.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure rsync restarts fully during swift setup

Existing rsync stop/start handlers were relying on the pattern
parameter to the Ansible service module which relies on the results
of ps to determine if the service is running. This is unnecessary
because the rsync service script is well-behaved and responds
appropriately to start stop and restart commands. Removal of the
pattern param ensures that the response from the service command is
used instead.

Root cause of the bug is that when Keystone was changed to share
fernet secrets via rsync over ssh tunnel, an rsync process was
introduced in AIOs, Swift stand-alones, and other deployment
configurations that contain Keystone containers on the storage hosts.

The resulting rsync processes within Keystone containers pollute the
results of ps commands on the host, fooling Ansible into thinking
that an rsync service is running on the standard port when it is not.

Secondly, the handler responsible for stopping rsync was not causing
the notice for "Ensure rsync service running" to trigger cleanly in
my testing, so the tasks were changed to trigger both notices in an
ordered list.

Change-Id: I5ed47f7c1974d6b22eeb2ff5816ee6fa30ee9309
Closes-Bug: 1481121

commit_message:
Ensure rsync restarts fully during swift setup

Existing rsync stop/start handlers were relying on the pattern
parameter to the Ansible service module which relies on the results
of ps to determine if the service is running. This is unnecessary
because the rsync service script is well-behaved and responds
appropriately to start stop and restart commands. Removal of the
pattern param ensures that the response from the service command is
used instead.

Root cause of the bug is that when Keystone was changed to share
fernet secrets via rsync over ssh tunnel, an rsync process was
introduced in AIOs, Swift stand-alones, and other deployment
configurations that contain Keystone containers on the storage hosts.

The resulting rsync processes within Keystone containers pollute the
results of ps commands on the host, fooling Ansible into thinking
that an rsync service is running on the standard port when it is not.

Secondly, the handler responsible for stopping rsync was not causing
the notice for "Ensure rsync service running" to trigger cleanly in
my testing, so the tasks were changed to trigger both notices in an
ordered list.

Change-Id: I5ed47f7c1974d6b22eeb2ff5816ee6fa30ee9309
Closes-Bug: 1481121

[{'created': '2015-08-19 19:33:13.000000000', 'message': 'Make rebuild/evacuate use resource claims

We make sure that rebuild now uses claims and resource tracking. This
means that we will now be properly tracking resources for
rebuilt/evacuated instances and will potentially fail if a move of the
instance breaks policy set by the scheduler (an exception would be in

commit_message:
Make rebuild/evacuate use resource claims

We make sure that rebuild now uses claims and resource tracking. This
means that we will now be properly tracking resources for
rebuilt/evacuated instances and will potentially fail if a move of the
instance breaks policy set by the scheduler (an exception would be in
case we bypassed the scheduler).

We also make sure that we update the migration record with the current
status (either success or failure).

On a failure to claim, we will currently just error out the instance
which requires manual intervention, but taking advantage of the retry
mechanism could be added in the future.

Since none of the required args are sent yet, this change is effectively
a no-op, until we change the rebuild_instance RPC method to send the
required data over.

Related-blueprint: migration-fix-resource-tracking
Change-Id: Ia068494b1a4c43123fe172d67a81ac0b60682995

This needs version bumps, right?'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-09-02 16:18:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Getting farther in the set, I'm reminded that you split the function and the bump. I don't really understand why that is necessary or desired. I guess this is the better organization (compared to the previous), but I would think that we could still avoid altering the actual function signature of the rpc method until we're actually ready to expose it.

By the same argument as before, if someone sends the new signature with the old version, we'll honor it here even before we claim to.

If there is some compelling reason to do it this way that I'm missing, please point it out. Otherwise, I'd prefer to stick to convention."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-09-03 09:21:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-2

so lets turn this into a bug, with no string changes, but this is too late for liberty as a blueprint patch now, breaks the tracking by the release managers.'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-09-03 13:20:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Thanks John - this is basically simply bugifixing that builds upon the migration context work that is already (almost) merged so I don't think there is any controversy there.

@Dan - so if I am reading your comment correctly - you are basically saying that the best way to do this is to merge the client and server changes to the RPC signature into the same commit. I can do that, it's gonna be way more difficult to review though, and I question the need to do this.

Not bumping the version before everything is implemented on the server side (which was the original issue raised) makes a lot of sense, but not expanding the signature of the server seems overly restrictive - RPC is not a public API, the only real client is fully controlled by us, and there are no real guarantees that I am aware of other than the ones given by version numbers (which we are not breaking in this case). Having easier to review patches is a good tradeoff in this case IMHO"}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-09-03 13:22:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Another option would be to change signatures in one step, but have dummy variables exposed to implement functionality separately to make it more palatable to reviewers. This seems worse to me honestly.'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-09-03 14:44:29.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Now part of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/200485/'}]

commit_message:
compute: Make rebuild consider the node that was passed in

We add some of the keyword args that will need to be passed in for the
claims to work (scheduled_node, limits, and the migration object).

Since we will be sending the node name to the rebuild operation, we
will be able to use it and avoid a DB hit. This commit makes sure we take
advantage of that.

Change-Id: Id51c371f9875b8e2b7f4cda6f7a88273b13bb3af
Related-blueprint: migration-fix-resource-tracking

cinder-backup to use ceph.  We also create a new group called

      /etc/openstack_deploy/env.d/cinder.yml in order for this change
      to execute successfully.

"}]
commit_message:
Allow cinder-backup to use ceph

This change updates ceph_client and os_cinder roles to allow
cinder-backup to use ceph.  We also create a new group called
'cinder_backup' which allows us to only retreive the cinder backup key
if cinder-backup is actually in use.

To use, you would simply need to set cinder_service_backup_driver to
cinder.backup.drivers.ceph in your user_variables.yml file.

NOTE: You will need to update your
      /etc/openstack_deploy/env.d/cinder.yml in order for this change
      to execute successfully.

Change-Id: Ib94effa40208bbc8de0f78c5487316be007adcf1
Closes-Bug: #1481787
Implements: blueprint ceph-block-devices
DocImpact
(cherry picked from commit 44d3f25de6daab8073137c9fc76edcdfc23c716f)

I think this should happen automatically, e.g. I don't want to have to set the sorting_method. If I've set read/write_affinity then it should be set to "affinity". Otherwise leave it not set.

Possibly add an option to set it - e.g. add it to swift role defaults (but not set) and have a | default('affinity') within an if statement, like:

{%   if swift_proxy_vars.read_affinity is defined or swift_proxy_vars.write_affinity is defined %}
sorting_method = affinity
{%   endif %}'}, {'account_id': 12807, 'date': '2015-08-19 22:51:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Andy, I considered that but supporting timing as a deployment option for single-region deploys at the same time becomes more difficult to maintain as suggested in the commit. I just opted for less code as these templates are already quite difficult to read.

Are you preferring we leave 'timing' support out for now or write more template code to allow it when read_affinity is omitted?"}, {'account_id': 2799, 'date': '2015-08-21 11:08:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

On second thought - I'm not sure there is any point in having a sorting_method of "affinity" unless you are using affinity settings, so being able to override it manually is probably not something we should go for.

If at some point there is a 3rd option for sorting_method that we want to allow the use of, we may need to refigure that out, but as it stands now it seems simple enough to set that value if and when affinity settings are specified.'}, {'account_id': 12807, 'date': '2015-08-25 03:43:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-25 04:44:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add sorting_method to swift proxy config as needed

When read_affinity is used and sorting_method is not used warnings
are generated in the swift proxy log indicating that the
read_affinity is not being respected. When read_affinity is specified
this change sets the sorting_method to affinity automatically, and
otherwise uses a configured value which defaults to shuffle.

Note that write_affinity does not respect sorting_method and follows
a different code path and does not issue warnings in logs when used
without sorting_method.

Closes-bug: 1480581
Co-Authored-By: Andy McCrae <andy.mccrae@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I3cab89c95f288b4a59f4dd3c7360daca7a4f47bf

commit_message:
Update path to subunit2html in post_test_hook

Per:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072982.html

The location of subunit2html changed on the images in the gate
so update the path used in the post_test_hook.

Long-term we should just use what's in devstack-gate.

Change-Id: I5e50e7d7ad845aba26403df1df412c0a139a6dc7
Closes-Bug: #1491646

commit_message:
Murano versioning

This specification proposes set of arrangements that are going to allow Murano
keep backward compatibility with applications written for older version while
still making possible to introduce incompatible changes to any part of the
project

Change-Id: I5ac638974a3fbd5a75750f7ef5cb7a84299db499

commit_message:
[WIP] Switch to oslo-config-generator

Remove openstack.common.config package.
Remove tools/config folder.
Add etc/oslo-config-generator/cinder.conf
Add cinder.opts module and collect all options from project.

Temporary add the old and new cinder.conf.sample files for comparing.
Implement a script for comparing the old and new configuration files.

Closes-Bug: #1473768
Change-Id: I6e7be74d1a774a6fd1d6d870336cb227a1570144

commit_message:
Enable execute bit on swift sync for directories

Sometimes during sync, directories are created with
644 permissions instead of 755. This mainly impacts
controller reinstallation where resyncing existing
creates inaccessible data files.

Change-Id: I0ad8dfc308324c5a354e13331f0fb6604502b49b
Closes-Bug: #1490960

commit_message:
Rediscover hdisk if connection info refreshed

Although the UDID for a VSCSI attached volume is saved in the bdm
during attach, it can be lost if the connection information is
'refreshed' by the compute manager.  This fix rediscovers the hdisk
during detach if we cannot look it up via the UDID. One scenario
where the connection info is refreshed is live migration.

commit_message:
Fix RequestSpec.instance_group hydration

A mistake was done by hydrating the members field for the InstanceGroup object when
creating the RequestSpec object because that field is for getting the instances,
not the hosts. In order to provide that information, we need to provide a new
version of the InstanceGroup and give a lazy-load for getting it in case we want to
have it.

Change-Id: I0d892bbe490c9ee727f54077d7398cc2800ce107
Partially-Implements: blueprint request-spec-object

commit_message:
Port the AMQP1 driver to new Pyngus SASL API

Pyngus 2.0 includes a new API for configuring SASL credentials.
Previous versions of Pyngus did not provide this API - the driver had
to invoke Proton APIs in order to configure user credentials.  Moving
to the Pyngus API will preserve compatibility with older versions of
Proton, since the next release of Proton wil be changing its SASL API.

Pyngus 2.0 also adds strict enforcement of callback re-entrancy
constrants.  This patch fixes some bad driver reentrancy violations.

Closes-bug: #1473515
Change-Id: Iddccefd3ee3c9092c086fc54e3810f78d5df9338

commit_message:
Set 'heat-admin' as the default user

This patch updates the default firstboot scripts
for TripleO so that we always create a 'heat-admin'
user. This is important because Heat
recently removed the instance_user option which we used to set
the previous 'heat-admin' default user (see
I9d01c5e7de630df5058429353fa17b3536ee8807 or git commit
e423bec7f10b0f5d07f05d195b3b7860f6bceb00 in Heat for details).

Change-Id: Ib20c8375c9fb35e5221fd3aeb0c052c332c66ff3

When we use virsh define to add VM to libvirt - libvirt automatically generates MAC addressess for all interfaces. This way we can use virsh dumpxml VM_NAME to save those addresses into vm config file.

This will allow us to store MACs generated when VM is started between reboots.'}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2015-09-03 09:24:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Expose VIF net-id attribute in os-virtual-interfaces

Adds a new microversion to show virtual interface 'net-id' in
virtual interface list.

DocImpact - See nova/api/openstack/rest_api_version_history.rst
for details

APIImpact

Implements blueprint add-vif-net-id-in-vif-list

Change-Id: Ic8b26df8d7e69bd71d23dfbc983fa3449c16fa7d

commit_message:
To use id instead of name when making credentials from context

If tenant_name or user_name has chinese characters,
an 'UnicodeEncodeError' exception raised when making
credentials from request context.
There are two solutions to fix this problem:
1. Call encodeutils.safe_encode to encode the tenant_name
with utf-8 before using.
2. Modify to use tenant_id/user_id instead
of name as other OpenStack projects(Nova, Cinder, Neutron...)
did.

This patch select the  option2 to fix the problem.

Change-Id: I2510405b7b2cc9125828a19a151a56bcd44c2222
Closes-Bug: #1488754
