Great start.  I thinkthis is well done, but there are a few variations to consider:
Ideally, the Keystone server would support multiple Auth Mechanisms, to include X509 client cert as done, but also Kerberos, and Basic-Auth.  All three of these can be done on one url, bu making the X509 Auth optional, and having mod_auth_kerb kerberos fall back to  basic-auth.  So, while X509 is the first and most needed, please make it so multiple auth mechanisms are acceptable.

This attempts to map to an existing user, but we should be able to use X509 in a Federated way as well, and we should be able to use the mapping to figure out what the federated user is.  The first pass does not need to do that, but don't code to make it impossible in a future patch."}, {'account_id': 11387, 'date': '2015-04-02 17:33:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21:

Adam, not sure if I understand your comment. Neither patch you mentioned above are related to this one. Sam's patch has already compartmentalized the different functionality which makes the mapping piece reusable and shareable. This patch essentially does the following:

1. middleware to validate the client certificates based on the configured trusted issuers
2. pull out the mapping corresponding to the given trusted issuer and map the incoming client certificate attributes into an existing user
3. the scope information is pulled from the header as we've agreed on during the mid cycle
4. lookup the roles based on the information from step 2 and 3

This patch implements what's been agreed upon at the mid cycle.

Can you please be more specific on what *exactly* is missing?"}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-04-23 06:28:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

Adam, not sure if I understand your comment. Neither patch you mentioned above are related to this one. Sam's patch has already compartmentalized the different functionality which makes the mapping piece reusable and shareable. This patch essentially does the following:

  1. middleware to validate the client certificates based on the configured trusted issuers 
  2. pull out the mapping corresponding to the given trusted issuer and map the incoming client certificate attributes into an existing user
  3. the scope information is pulled from the header as we've agreed on during the mid cycle
  4. lookup the roles based on the information from step 2 and 3

This patch implements what's been agreed upon at the mid cycle.

This patch basically addressed the comments from Brant. And took out the option 'no_check_trusted_issuer'(to bypass the trusted issuers checking) that was suggested from the previous patch.

The reason is that we want to distinguish SSL certificate that can be participate in tokenless auth (i.e. server certs) versus all SSL client certificates. Two different SSL client certificate can have the exact same subject DN but different issuer.

The following example should make it clear:

- A service client sends a request with a client certificate that has the following Subject and Issuer:
   Subject: CN=nova,O=HP
   Issuer:  CN=service,O=verisign
- A end-user client sends a request with a client certificate that has the following Subject and Issuer:
   Subject: CN=abc,O=foo.com
   Isser:   CN=enduser,O=verifign
- Both Issuers' CN=service,O=verisign and CN=enduser,O=verifign are issued by CN=root,O=verisign
- In the container, admin configures CN=root,O=verisign as the trusted certificate and both requests can go through.
- We only allow the service request to participate in the X.509 tokenless authorization if we have service client certificate Issuer 'CN=service,O=verisign' setup as one of the trusted issuers in keystone.conf"}, {'account_id': 11387, 'date': '2015-05-15 17:45:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 26:

commit_message:
Tokenless authz with X.509 SSL client certificate

Implemented middleware to map an incoming trusted SSL client certificate
into Keystone auth credential so we can perform authorization without
having to issue a token.

TODO: to submit a separate patch to devstack to enable this feature.

Co-authored-by: guang-yee <guang.yee@hp.com>

SecurityImapct
DocImpact
implements bp keystone-tokenless-authz-with-x509-ssl-client-cert

Change-Id: Icc7305ca9d96f8e9cdc95ccde57de650801c6544

commit_message:
Fix import path in neutron-sanity-check for ml2_sriov opts

neutron-sanity-check fails while importing ml2_sriov
configuration. This patch fixes the import path and
also includes a unit test to avoid such issues.

Closes-Bug: #1489374
Change-Id: I4265ee78be9e7f83e35c94187d4577b32005bef9

commit_message:
Allow to use Keystone via 'keystone/api' network

Restrict access to Keystone API from network with
'keystone/api' role, so from outside a cloud it
could be reached only via public VIP.

Change-Id: I6e2004e53591e0cc0b2a5b43a83532d3de9aef9a
Closes-bug: #1489057

commit_message:
Fixed issue with cacert parameter

We need to use parameter cacert instead of ca_file parameter
to work with CA certificates like python clients for other
OpenStack services.

Also fixed typo (after copy paste from Glance code).

Change-Id: Ibe36390aab2f2edb0fe7670f76f61caeb350d34b
Closes-Bug: #1487099

commit_message:
Revert "Implement asynchronous logger for event callbacks"

This reverts commit e63709d16bd4c1949bef820ac336c9393c040d25.

AsyncLogger's worker thread takes almost 100% CPU because
it infinitely iterates over a logger queue. A simple
"sleep 0.2" will solve this problem, but I have doubts
about that AsyncLogger helps us anyway. It's better to
revert this fix and investigate a real cause of our problems.

Closes-Bug: 1491794
Related-Bug: 1487397

Change-Id: I95d57de9ef92c717b8b07f7832ab258c0b35b6a5

commit_message:
devstack: resolve image name via image-list, not image-show

python-glanceclient v1.0.0 was recently released and now defaults to
glance api V2.  The client shell for v2 does not offer referencing things
by name and requires we resolve the ID ourselves.  This switches resolving
the id by name and instead pulls it from image-list.

Change-Id: Ib215767f22e5fb8d189e34ea605d1a904d0e7d62

commit_message:
Fix silently overwrite user specified content type

Previously, even user specified the response content type of api
'catalog/packages/<package_id>/ui', which will be silently replaced
by text/plain. To improve it, add list 'specific_content_types' to
make resource controller can specify different content type for each
action. And it will raise exception when user specified content type
is unsupported.

Change-Id: I5d56461333d730f0f9fbe715e9bb066e5b004203
Closes-Bug: #1476543

commit_message:
Use domain checking for user provider

Enforce domain name checking by using domain_check method.

Note: Implements the following user story:
62-keystone-v3-implement-support-for-default-domain-if-no-domain

Change-Id: I72a7975819c8e51ed118caa0817ea5846c4d2780

commit_message:
Upgrade the OpenStack environment 6.1 to 7.0

Add chapter to Operations document with description of procedure that upgrades
Mirantis OpenStack environment 6.1 to 7.0 for limited set of Reference
Architecture options.

Change-Id: I9a0df955aa0c2feafcb6e9810144baa5a22491a4
Implements: blueprint upgrade-major-openstack-environment

commit_message:
Fix docker package name in Ubuntu 14.04 in Install Guide

This patch fixes docker package name in Install Guide.
In case of Ubuntu 14.04, the docker package name is 'docker.io', but
not 'docker'.

Change-Id: If2913cdfe370c511aaa70e8079462f76662cc116

commit_message:
Add image signing verification

This patch adds support for the image signing feature by adding the
ability for glance to verify a signature.

This patch still needs:
 * castellan added to global requirements (see Depends-On below)

Depends-On: I2283d2853d4ccd6d41d706db5b02cf6c74c5ba93
Change-Id: I0b0592a3526a4e4f5b39ae6ce8b4dedd0ccc31d9
Implements: blueprint image-signing-and-verification-support

commit_message:
Use bdm v2 to boot ebs instance for gating

novaclient 2.27.0 has a bug with legacy bdm, and fails on instance boot
attempt. This patch uses bdm v2 instead to workaround the bug.

Change-Id: I3d856b2ba4116c19ab936db63d29413fdfbf31e0

commit_message:
Adding option for Java jobs to be adapted to Oozie

Adding an option for enabling Java jobs to set the
"adapt_for_oozie" flag to automatically modify the job
configs at runtime.  Also adding a unit test that includes
the new option.

Change-Id: Iede36c178aef07912d6f69621d69c1657d1c79b4
Closes-Bug: #1445471

commit_message:
[Sahara] Move node processes selection to own tab

Sahara already have plugin that have huge amout of node processes.
So, sometimes during node group creation it's hard to find some process
from selected service.

So, this patch resolves that issue, because it move node processes selection
to separate tab, and also groups node processes by services.

Implements blueprint: sahara-node-processes-tab
Change-Id: I38cca7e687da1d1c82a5f40cb5846765aa1e43f2

commit_message:
Fix gating for DevStack switched to Nova v2.1 by default

Use bdm v2 to boot ebs instance for gating

novaclient 2.27.0 has a bug with legacy bdm, and fails on instance boot
attempt. This patch uses bdm v2 instead to workaround the bug.

Change-Id: I3d856b2ba4116c19ab936db63d29413fdfbf31e0

Use 'compute' service type by default

It was a grand error to use not default service type as a service type
by default. Now DevStack provides v2.1 by 'compute' service type, does
not provide 'computev21' at all. Because that gating fails.

Change-Id: I8a68d331583ea575a5883cd2c451245a9119016b

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded config drive enforcement

This change removes the forced use of config drive to ensure that a user
can choose to use config drive as needed. This adds ability to
disable/enable config drive and allows libvirt to listen for connections
on tcp as needed for live migrations (prohibited otherwise by config drive).

The following new variables were added to nova_common and nova_libvirt
roles, retaining their existing values:

nova_force_config_drive: always
nova_libvirtd_listen_tls: 0
nova_libvirtd_listen_tcp: 1
nova_libvirtd_auth_tcp: none

Conflicts:
  playbooks/roles/os_nova/defaults/main.yml
  playbooks/roles/os_nova/templates/nova.conf.j2

Change-Id: I1de35a4b3611b8bc33a21930dae3fd38f9aaa151
Closes-Bug: #1468514
DocImpact
(cherry picked from commit e65066cf1253c8a27d12c3e3da6797199f0016b5)

commit_message:
Updated juno to include fix for CVE-2015-3241 - 26 Aug 2015

Updates all repo SHAs to include:
 - [OSSA 2015-015] Nova instance migration process does not stop when
   instance is deleted (CVE-2015-3241)
 - Cannot rebuild a VM created from a Cinder volume backed by NetApp
   https://review.openstack.org/203253

This patch removes all SHA specifications for the OpenStack clients
so that any client requirement versions are determined solely from
the requirements of the OpenStack service and Global requirements
files.

This resolves issues where the client versions we carry are
incompatible with the services, resulting in unexpected failures.

Tempest requirements are specifically ignored as the tempest role
downloads its required clients directly from pip.

Finally, due to the change in the openstack-client version used the
heat domain/role/user tasks fail as they require the CLI to specify
the user and project domain name/id. This patch includes the CLI
changes to ensure that the deployment completes properly.

Change-Id: I88e705d063575f55c32350ead25bc7cc0bcdec08
Closes-Bug: #1489947
Closes-Bug: #1488315
Closes-Bug: #1400881

'}, {'created': '2015-08-25 09:19:01.000000000', 'message': "Fixing haproxy-playbook fails when installing on multiple hosts

This bug is triggered when haproxy is deployed on multiple hosts
and external_lb_vip is different than the internal one.
As all host receive the same configuration, and are expected
to restart the haproxy service more than once
(once during role and once post_tasks), the playbook will fail,
because the restart of the service fails. The restart of the
service fails on some hosts because haproxy tries to
start/bind to an ip the host doesn't have (avoiding ip conflicts)

This allows haproxy to bind on non_local addresses by
addng a sysctl change in the playbook: net.ipv4.ip_nonlocal_bind = 1
The sysctl is changed for the containers/systems by default.

Side-effect: other services are now able to bind on non-local addresses

This could be overriden by setting the variable haproxy_bind_on_non_local
in your user_* variables. If set to false, then the ip_non_local_bind
sysctl won't be changed.

Closes-Bug: #1487409

commit_message:
Fixing haproxy-playbook fails when installing on multiple hosts

This bug is triggered when haproxy is deployed on multiple hosts
and external_lb_vip is different than the internal one.
As all host receive the same configuration, and are expected
to restart the haproxy service more than once
(once during role and once post_tasks), the playbook will fail,
because the restart of the service fails. The restart of the
service fails on some hosts because haproxy tries to
start/bind to an ip the host doesn't have (avoiding ip conflicts)

This allows haproxy to bind on non_local addresses by
addng a sysctl change in the playbook: net.ipv4.ip_nonlocal_bind = 1
The sysctl is changed for the containers/systems
when external_lb_vip is different than internal address and
the number of haproxy hosts is more than one thanks to a group_var.

Side-effect: other services are able to bind on non-local addresses
if the sysctl is changed.

This could be overriden by setting the variable haproxy_bind_on_non_local
in your user_* variables. If set to false, then the ip_non_local_bind
sysctl won't be changed.

Closes-Bug: #1487409

Change-Id: I41b3a5a4ba2d48192b505e3720456a77484aa92b

commit_message:
Switch Rally gates to new DevStack plugin style

After this patch was merged: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190601/
Rally gates become broken.

The check in jenkis/jobs/rally.yaml that should switch to new
plugin style doesn't work (it contains bug).
At this moment we are installing 2 versions of Rally
(with new and old way) one is master another one is master + patch.

As a result Rally gates are testing Rally master instead of
proposed patch to Rally.

This patch removes check of new/old style and use always new plugin style

Change-Id: Id17c1422e4b1ff350e16f76b6fcaa1ce3aa6f6b4

commit_message:
Disable keystone service token

Disable keystone service token in post deployment actions
since that token doesn't represent a user, and carries no
explicit authorization.

Change-Id: I4f2877df1da087f10673edfc855868ebb2245be3
Closes-Bug: #1486015

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-15 17:38:37.000000000', 'message': 'Allow external services to define their providers

Service plugins may or may not have service providers. Neutron
should have no say into which providers are allowed and which
are not. This should be a responsibility of the service plugin
validation logic itself.

To this aim, this logic is removed from here and moved closer
to where it belongs.

Partial-bug: #1473110

Change-Id: Ia4cad678e6c722ca05821dbdbf05d61523246a86
'}, {'created': '2015-07-16 00:50:33.000000000', 'message': 'Try to decentralize the managemement of service providers

**WIP**

After the service split, some of the configuration, parsing and
validation was kept in the core; ultimately this needs to
decentralized and get closer to the services where it belongs.

This patch starts from ProviderConfiguration and ServiceTypeManager
classes, and attempts to rely less on hardcoded magic.

Partial-bug: #1473110

Change-Id: Ia4cad678e6c722ca05821dbdbf05d61523246a86
'}, {'created': '2015-07-16 06:58:51.000000000', 'message': 'Decentralize the managemement of service providers

After the service split, some of the configuration, parsing and
validation was kept in the neutron core; ultimately this needs to
get closer to the services where it belongs.

This patch starts from ProviderConfiguration and ServiceTypeManager
classes, and aims at removing the hard-coded elements, like the list
of known advanced services, so that in the long run we can make
Neutron easier to plug with external services.

Partial-bug: #1473110

Depends-on: I44edcceba37ac58efcc0a53c9d1f835d9530344a
Change-Id: Ia4cad678e6c722ca05821dbdbf05d61523246a86

commit_message:
Decentralize the managemement of service providers

After the service split, some of the configuration, parsing and
validation was kept in the neutron core; ultimately this needs to
get closer to the services where it belongs.

This patch starts from ProviderConfiguration and ServiceTypeManager
classes, and aims at removing the hard-coded elements, like the list
of known advanced services, so that in the long run we can make
Neutron easier to plug with external services.

Partial-bug: #1473110

marekd: I don't think that remote-id is a security mechanism here. Remote-ID is a way to determine when a path authenticates multiple IDPs you need a way to disambiguate from which one you received this assertion. 

My expectation here is that it's at least as secure because you will by default configure mellon/shib to only accept SAML assertions from the provider registered in the idp-metadata."}, {'account_id': 16523, 'date': '2015-08-31 08:57:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

LGTM'}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2015-08-31 14:47:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Jamie: This is kind of security mechanism, as you need to be sure that assertion being matched with the mapping identified by a user defined pair (idp, protocol) is realy coming from the IdP you expect. This is what remote_id was for.

commit_message:
Add federated auth for idp specific websso

This commit adds a call the federation API where federated authentication can
be initiated by knowing the identity provider ID, as well as the protocol ID.
This will result in the ability for Identity Provider specific Websso
authentication flows.

Change-Id: Ia84e2fba8337f5f1c1f59986020c7617b367bbc6
Implements: bp federation-idp-websso

commit_message:
Disable python buffering for gate checks

In order to ensure that the ansible output in the jenkins console
log is output as it comes it is necessary to turn off the python
output buffering.

commit_message:
Implement tox.ini config for bashate and pep8 tests

This patch implements tox.ini configuration for bashate and pep8
tests for the purpose of implementing the standard openstack-infra
tests for these.

Change-Id: I72623ea3d531614a803f6b97a9f61f56c376c723
Implements: blueprint gate-split

commit_message:
Switch Nova/Tempest to use/test Cinder API v2

As per https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/deprecate-v1-api
the Cinder API v1 was designated as deprecated in Juno and was meant
to be removed in Kilo, but appears to still be usable in Kilo.

This patch configures Nova to use the Cinder v2 API instead of the
v1 API.

This patch configures Tempest to test both the Cinder v1 and v2 API's
for now. Once the API is removed upstream we can change this.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1481542
Change-Id: I6513c07e1b5d5653b84ad0b2b490ac8451f2bdf1

commit_message:
Ansible register task for MariaDB incorrectly reports failure

When running register task for MariaDB we should firstly check
if operation failed before trying to parse result from json output

Change-Id: Ic331ec20990277d30b147826ff24affb27d52383
Closes-Bug: #1491751

commit_message:
REST API for Murano Dashboard.

This patch adds the start of a horizon rest api module so that
javascript can wrap it. It also provides an AngularJS wrapper.

Change-Id: I53ee3bf1c9d447e0619689e8f649146a6357207b

user_variables.yml file.

cinder-backup to use ceph.  We also create a new group called
'cinder_backup' which allows us to only retreive the cinder backup key

cinder.backup.drivers.ceph in your user_variables.yml file.

"}, {'created': '2015-08-17 12:40:21.000000000', 'message': "Allow cinder-backup to use ceph

This change updates ceph_client and os_cinder roles to allow
cinder-backup to use ceph.  We also create a new group called
'cinder_backup' which allows us to only retreive the cinder backup key
if cinder-backup is actually in use.

To use, you would simply need to set cinder_service_backup_driver to
cinder.backup.drivers.ceph in your user_variables.yml file.

NOTE: You will need to update your

commit_message:
Allow cinder-backup to use ceph

This change updates ceph_client and os_cinder roles to allow
cinder-backup to use ceph.  We also create a new group called
'cinder_backup' which allows us to only retreive the cinder backup key
if cinder-backup is actually in use.

To use, you would simply need to set cinder_service_backup_driver to
cinder.backup.drivers.ceph in your user_variables.yml file.

NOTE: You will need to update your
      /etc/openstack_deploy/env.d/cinder.yml in order for this change
      to execute successfully.

Change-Id: Ib94effa40208bbc8de0f78c5487316be007adcf1
Closes-Bug: #1481787
Implements: blueprint ceph-block-devices
DocImpact

commit_message:
Implement asynchronous logger for event callbacks

Excludes any lock operations in EventMachine event loop
and its callbacks.

Now in EventMachine callbacks all writings to log are
performed in asynchronous fashion. This way we try to
exclude possibility of blocking and getting deadlock
using classic logging mechanism, which has plenty of
locks internally.

Also similar problem was seen in the next ticket #1453573.

Co-Authored-By: Evgeniy L <eli@mirantis.com>

Closes-Bug: #1487397
Change-Id: I72d0eb01ef8c87e10003338bd3bb70e42a4b7dd6

commit_message:
XenAPI will not inject ssh-key if cloud-init

The XenAPI does not inject an ssh-key if an image
has the "cloud_init_installed" property. Cloud-init
handles key injection.

Closes-bug: 1206943
Change-Id: Iab2ce12b742599491e47a8643c5b83c8e273ad3c

commit_message:
Change get_extensions_path to remove duplicate paths

Split the api_extensions_path in get_extensions_path() so that
duplicated locations in the path can be removed.If not, then it
is possible that the same module is loaded twice due to duplicated
paths, which can cause error.

Closes-bug: #1486861
Change-Id: I7de1e20ab6ff519e51e52b869574931dcf8da797

commit_message:
Prevent ilo drivers powering off active nodes during take over

Currently, ilo drivers powers off active nodes
when a conductor takes over the node from another conductor.
This commit stops this, as active nodes shouldn't be powered
off during take over.

Closes-bug: 1490019
Change-Id: I8e54ae148ed9cfdcb6639a4d089ee82f14de53ba

commit_message:
Broaden domain-group testing of list_role_assignments

Use the new data driven test capabilities to increase our testing
of group-domain assignment listing.

Partially Implements: bp data-driven-tests
Change-Id: I345f455f9561257179412eab9d587d1afea7a46f

subject: Add support for group membership to data driven assignment tests

commit_message:
Add support for group membership to data driven assignment tests

Enable testing of effective mode for groups with the data driven
tests for list_role_assignment, plus provide one example of its
use.

Follow-on patches will expand the use of data driven test to
expand coverage.

Partially Implements: bp data-driven-tests
Change-Id: I6d6ae4e6851dfa32e3745767d4f20c74da135cdc

commit_message:
Enable tempest testing of ceilometer

This patch enables tempest testing of ceilometer in the gate
check.

Change-Id: Ic1e432f004dc8060f8d8a83521ce9c4c60e9abf7
Closes-Bug: #1481822
(cherry picked from commit 80e7086ea30a7b377171e6437ffb081d3b27881c)

So I'd just like to get this together with If461d45246e05ec13b8951662d9e3ea3de823d9f and make sure we're doing the right thing.

I'm not a big tester of this path; that said bug #1280356 describes requiring the default images even when IMAGE_URLS is set.  

this seems to cover the case of where you've set a different cirros image, but not the case where you've left it out but you really need it

Can we get this so that it closes both bugs?"}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2015-07-15 09:12:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

It's not trivial to get completely right.

As a suggestion perhaps we should always append to IMAGE_URLS as in change If461d45246e05ec13b8951662d9e3ea3de823d9f but then you need to remove duplicates.

Removing duplicates in the simple way (e.g. IMAGE_URLS=`echo $IMAGE_URLS | tr ',' '\n' | sort | uniq | tr '\n' ','`) is close, but actually the kicker is that I think upload_image expects the filename to be the unique key.  What do you expect to happen in this case?  Let the duplicate filename go through, which would result in the error from glance, or pick one of the two URLs?

I suppose the other thing we could do is change all of the additions to check if the filename is already in IMAGE_URLS before adding it, but that's going to get quite verbose and ugly."}, {'account_id': 12487, 'date': '2015-07-15 21:24:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

approach looks simple and clean, than removing duplicates'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-07-15 22:47:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Bob

Is it possible we want two separate things here?  One is for when you want to *override* the default image, as seems to be the intent of this change.  In that case, you know what you're doing.

The other seems to be when you want to append another image for other reasons, but leave the default alone.

So maybe we should support both through different variables?"}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2015-07-17 08:52:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

OK - so the all-singing-all-dancing solution would be to add a DOWNLOAD_DEFAULT_IMAGES as in the other change, then to add the simple deduplication as I proposed in my previous comment.

Let's go for that."}, {'account_id': 17169, 'date': '2015-07-22 01:41:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-22 02:53:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

I've taken the liberty of cleaning up the documentation slightly and rebasing on another little documentation clean-up.

I'm happy with the logic you may not want the default images downloaded and you can override that.

I'm still just not sold on the automatic clearing up of duplicates.  I feel like it's just better to die() and let the user sort it out.  I mean, what if it was a typo (you want ".1" and ".2" of some image, accidentally typo'd ".1" twice or something).

What I meant was _after_ setting the images, set DOWNLOAD_DEFAULT_IMAGES=False.  This would mean that if DOWNLOAD_DEFAULT_IMAGES was unset or True then we would add them to IMAGE_URLS once and then prevent them being added again.

Ian is advocating a whole-file header guard and I'm quite happy to go with that if it works.  I do have concerns whether there are other parts of stackrc that are expected to change (e.g. in the grenade case where we have two devstacks) but hopefully it'll work."}, {'account_id': 17169, 'date': '2015-08-27 08:23:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 16.'}, {'account_id': 17169, 'date': '2015-08-27 09:34:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 17.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-27 11:01:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: Verified+1

[{'created': '2015-07-14 11:18:22.000000000', 'message': 'Incorrect IMAGE_URLS for ironic and xenserver

The default setting of IMAGE_URLS is given in stackrc, while
tools/xen/README.md will still suggest user to set it in localrc with
a duplicated value(i.e. http://download.cirros-cloud.net/0.3.4/cirros
-0.3.4-x86_64-uec.tar.gz) and thus causes a conflict of image upload.

Although IMAGE_URLS could be originally set in localrc, stackrc will
partially overwrite "https://github.com/downloads/citrix-openstack/
warehouse/cirros-0.3.0-x86_64-disk.vhd.tgz" and indiscriminately append
"http://download.cirros-cloud.net/${CIRROS_VERSION}/cirros-
${CIRROS_VERSION}-x86_64-disk.img". Thus it will possibly upload the
image twice if user sets a same url in localrc and cause a
"409 Conflict" error. Actually if user follows the steps suggested by
tools/xen/README.md, the problem will definitely occur.

The same issue also happens to ironic.

Change-Id: I3ca4e576aa3fb8992c08ca44900a8c53dd4b4163
Closes-Bug: #1473432

commit_message:
Add/Overwrite default images in IMAGE_URLS and detect duplicates

IMAGE_URLS could be set both in localrc with customization or stackrc by
default. By setting DOWNLOAD_DEFAULT_IMAGES, user could choose to add
default images to IMAGE_URLS or overwrite them.

As uploading duplicate images will cause a "409 Conflict" error, a
duplicate detection will expose it earlier.

Care needs to be taken that you don't end up with a duplicate image, so
clean up Xen's README.

Depends-On: I6fbae12f950a03afab39f341132746d3db9f788c
Change-Id: I3ca4e576aa3fb8992c08ca44900a8c53dd4b4163
Closes-Bug: #1473432

commit_message:
Increase httplib._MAXHEADERS to 256.

By default Swift increase the number of max metadata count to 90
and extra header count to 32. That mean we can put 90 metadata to
Account/Container/Object by default, when user put 90 metadata to a
Account, the Account header count is close or more than 100. The
swift client unable to access Account and get an error likes,

('Connection aborted.', HTTPException('got more than 100 headers',))

So the default _MAXHEADERS(100) won't enough.

Change-Id: I5ffc4eb5d3e1ebc3dbdd7dc69376919ae3e1c5a8

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Fix exception message mistake in WSGI service

The error message when providing a backlog argument either zeroed or negative
 needs to be i18n and also fixed to match with the conditional.

Change-Id: Ib9e15091826e8a68289d90b53116837770e826c7
Closes-Bug: #1487350

commit_message:

(2 comments)

Since you updated, there are a few more spots inline.

My normal workflow testing on devstack is to just
 
 cd /opt/stack/horizon
 git review -d <patch>
 <sometimes rm -rf static>
 python manage.py collectstatic
 python manage.py compress
 sudo service apache2 restart

In this patch, also updated CUSTOM_THEME_PATH = 'themes/material' prior to collectstatic.

However, I was seeing some errors in horizon devstack log about not finding bootswatch package.  Tried some fun with setup.py and even manually pip installing the packages, but it led to other complaints.

So, I actually went to local.conf and did a RECLONE = no, did an unstack, and reran devstack, then repeated the above (including the theme setting).  The bootswatch complaints in horizon log went away, but the theme didn't seem to pick up.  I tried CUSTOM_THEME_PATH a couple different way (adding static, using absolute path), but it wasn't being picked up. The default theme just kept being served. Been pretty tired the past week, so, it is likely a foobar on my behalf."}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-08-30 23:10:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 22.'}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-08-30 23:23:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 23.'}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-08-30 23:32:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

Travis,

Ah yes ... that is because the latest devstack is not running with the latest global requirements.  Material will only work with /opt/stack/requirements with this review: 206668

The following steps worked for me:
1. unstack / clean
2. cd /opt/stack/requirements
3. git review -d 206668
4. stack
5. cd /opt/stack/horizon
6. git review -d 197821
7. Update CUSTOM_THEME_PATH
8. rm -rf static
9. *collect*
10. *compress*
11. restart apache

And now I've updated the font and icon paths in 'Material' to now fully take advantage of review 206592, and therefore, it seems to work natively on Devstack. (when your global reqs are up to date)

Thanks for pointing that out Travis \o/

I hope that Lyle can correct me if I'm wrong, but before 206592 went in, no theme other than 'webroot' would actually work on devstack *out of the box*.  Any theme running on devstack required the $webroot variable to be set.  Devstack always looked like 'default' because the 'webroot' theme inherited from 'default'"}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-08-30 23:40:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

Kelly,

There are three states to the nav:

1. Large Display
 --> Act like standard horizon ... there is a nav on the left side

2. Medium Display
 --> The nav collapses and a menu bar shows up on the top left of the nav bar
 --> When clicking on the menu bar, a dark overlay should fill the screen, and the side nav should slide out from the left of the screen, and slide out over the content in the page (the page content should not move)

3. Small Display
 --> more stuff happens to collapse the other menus

It looks like you are hitting scenario 2 or 3, but have no dark overlay.

Can you tell me how big your screen is (rough guess) and what browser this happened on?'}, {'account_id': 13785, 'date': '2015-09-01 03:59:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

[{'created': '2015-07-02 02:58:38.000000000', 'message': "Themeing Mechanism now supports 3rd party themes

In order to fascilate the bulk of the CSS Reorg effort, it will be extremely
beneficial to quickly toggle between many different themes in order to validate
proper cascading inheritance.  This work prompted the following example theme.

The 'material' theme gives an example of how to incorporate a 3rd party theme
into the new Themeing functionality.  In addition to incorporating a theme,
loaded as a static asset using requirements.txt, it also gives examples of how
to cleanly override styles, variables, icon fonts and Django templates.

Change-Id: Ic67189de5aac5ca541ad6fe82b823e8fcf318bd0

commit_message:
Theming Mechanism now supports 3rd party themes

In order to facilitate the bulk of the CSS Reorg effort, it was
extremely beneficial to quickly toggle between many different themes
in order to validate proper cascading inheritance.  This work
prompted the following example theme.

The 'material' theme gives an example of how to make use of a 3rd
party theme using the theming functionality.  In addition to
incorporating a theme, loaded as a static asset using
requirements.txt, it also gives examples of how to cleanly override
styles, variables, icon fonts and Django templates.

This theme is replacing 'blue' as the example of how to use a theme
other than 'default'.

To use this theme, add the theme to your local_settings.py:
CUSTOM_THEME_PATH = 'themes/material', recollect and recompress your
static files.

Change-Id: Ic67189de5aac5ca541ad6fe82b823e8fcf318bd0
Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-theme-css-reorg

commit_message:
Modify recommend_configs arguments in vanilla 1

Although recommentdations in vanilla 1 plugin aren't supported, the
arguments of method recommend_configs in versionhandler should be
consistent with version 2. Otherwise, the creation of cluster will
fail with Internal Server Error.

Change-Id: Ic0b6fcc4cd51bcc4095a2e3f9db80abb40b415d7
Closes-Bug: #1490723

commit_message:
Run py34 first in default tox run

this avoids py34 failure in default tox run when testrepository is
not yet initialized (e.g. fresh repo clone).

Change-Id: I95d3590ebd67dc4f2c3a53b3da50a3d3ed481f7f
Closes-Bug: #1489059

Updating the dashboard guide for Sahara

during the L cycle.  Also one correction on the endpoint to
use data-processing rather than data_processing.

commit_message:
[Sahara] Support autoconfiguration for templates

This patch introduces ability to switch on/off autoconfiguration
for cluster and node group templates.

Required saharaclient was released and added to
global-requirements.

Implements blueprint: recommend-configuration
Change-Id: I9f9b68102420d5bf147369e3e4f61f594d1b825c

[2015-08-26 00:33:58]	gyee	and the rest will be provided in the naive layer

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-05 14:09:23.000000000', 'message': "Stable Keystone Driver Interfaces

* Added a new Metaclass 'CompatiblizerMeta' that will ensure that
  + the driver version either matches the current interface version or
    the previous one
  + if its the previous, it'll introduce the compatibility methods defined
    in the 'Compatibilizer' class into the driver
  + if the 'Compatibilizer' class doesn't have a corresponding method
    implemented for any not-implemented-abstract-method of driver,
    then it'll raise exception

* Added INTERFACE_VERSION and 'Compatibilizer' classes to all 'core.py'
  files containing Driver interfaces

* Added DRIVER_VERSION to all backend
  implementations in 'sql.py', 'ldap.py' files

* Added two new exception classes pertaining to incompatibility

Implements bp stable-driver-interfaces

Change-Id: I0078f6dc32932beb6db534ecf22b160097c5a090

commit_message:
Stable Keystone Driver Interfaces

Extended support for versioned driver classes to the rest of the
backends based on the design of the initial support for catalog backend @
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/218481/

partially Implements bp stable-driver-interfaces

after some testing I came to a conclusion that at least in this particular test using cirros image would not bring any speedup due to peculiarities of dhcp client in that image (it usually takes minimum 60 sec only to get a lease while fedora cloud image is completely ready in about 16 seconds on my test rig).

Using a smaller flavor might be beneficial though as fedora + python http server is happy enough with 128 MB ram e.g. m1.micro flavor (x4 savings on RAM).

I will upload a new patch or two to check if it has any benefit (and also what would be faster, resource group of two at once, or start the instances one-by-one during test). [{'created': '2015-03-19 18:03:13.000000000', 'message': "Use CirrOS image in Neutron Loadbalancer test

This should decrease the load on the gate.

Test template was rewritten to use ResourceGroup, wait conditions and
outputs, so no other client than heat one is used, and there is no need
to check for VM connectivity, as stack status COMPLETE now quite
reliably means that the listening servers are runnning.

Also, two options where added to config:
- floating_network_name (defaults to 'public')
- minimal_instance_type (for use with cirros images, defaults to
  'm1.nano')

Change-Id: Iec8e8061f9ab3f3841fa221722b7b7805760cdf7
Related-Bug: #1433555

commit_message:
Merge Neutron AutoScaling and LoadBalancer tests

The tested use case is an autoscaling group of web app servers
behind a loadbalancer.

Test template was rewritten to use AutoScalingGroup, wait conditions and
outputs, so no other client than heat one is used.
Now there is no need to check for VM connectivity,
as stack/resources status COMPLETE now quite reliably means
that the listening servers are running.

This patch should probably also help with narrowing down the causes of
bug 1437203, since it does not checks instance connectivity with SSH.

Change-Id: Iec8e8061f9ab3f3841fa221722b7b7805760cdf7
Related-Bug: #1437203
Closes-Bug: #1435285

commit_message:
Allow specifying a region name to auth_token

The keystone that is used to validate tokens is determined from the
service catalog. If you have multiple identity entries in your service
catalog then you need to specify the region to use.

Add a region_name option.

Change-Id: I512dbcdc7031f476d691b7ce09b7c6411900ea9e
Closes-Bug: #1405717

commit_message:
Add accessor method for raw catalog content

There are cases, such as os_auth in ansible, where a user wants to
be able to get at the raw catalog content. This is often extremely
useful when debugging cloud applications.

Change-Id: Ibe51b5f1a4b1d93efb6076b5f97b0fd10376cd16

commit_message:
Rename docs dir to doc for publishing

The publishing docs expect the documentation to be present in the
/doc directory not the /docs directory.  If the documentation is in
the /docs directory, according to fungi the docs won't be published
properly.

Change-Id: I718fec7e69d298a5cb2376ca4e2455e12169566e
Partially-Implements: blueprint kola-tox-doc

What if one public volume type A being changed to private, and unfortunately, tenant T has been removed access to this type.  User Foo of tenant T has one volume X created from type A.  Foo will still be able to create clone of X, and the clone will continue to use type A.  Same for creating volume from a snapshot.  It is not a bug introduced by your change, but like I mentioned in spec, allowing changing public type to private enlarges this hole.  We need a solution here.'}, {'account_id': 4428, 'date': '2015-07-31 06:29:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Add the ability to update type public status

Currently, the v2 volume type update api doesn't support updating
volume type's public status. All volume types created are public
by default if not specified. It is not possible to update an existing
volume_type is_public status. It is necessary to add updating public
status for volume type. If a volume type updated from public to
private, the volumes previously created with this type will not be
affected, but the user without access will not be able to create
volume with this type anymore.

APIImpact: Add 'is_public' for v2 type update api.
Implements blueprint: volume-types-public-update

Change-Id: I4a5b2cf8f747c87908a09835a5edb8873c4e946b

commit_message:
Add deprecation warning to periodic tasks with parallel=False

This setting never made much sense, and with move to Futurist it is
likely to become noop.

Change-Id: Id6341e2cefcd74e0ebfe5a0a8fb32432159743fa

[{'created': '2015-09-02 15:42:45.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Do not overwrite the iPXE boot script on every deployment"

I agree with what Ruby pointed out at [1] about this change. Not
replacing the file can have bigger consequences such not getting
overwrited even when ironic-conductor is updated (in case we change the
boot.ipxe in the future).

So we should revert this patch and deal with the pain of having to
change the ipxe_boot_script config file and restart the ironic-conductor
if we want to change a custom version of the script.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/218290/2/ironic/drivers/modules/pxe.py

This reverts commit d72493deb21db90961c80757fd81d30fb39a43c8.

Change-Id: I787edfad66d3a91c9b106996a0ed5f3d7f624727
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Do not overwrite the iPXE boot script on every deployment"

I agree with what Ruby pointed out at [1] about this change. Not
replacing the file can have bigger consequences such not getting
overwrited even when ironic-conductor is updated (in case we change the
boot.ipxe in the future).

So we should revert this patch and deal with the pain of having to
change the ipxe_boot_script config file and restart the ironic-conductor
if we want to change a custom version of the script.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/218290/2/ironic/drivers/modules/pxe.py

This reverts commit d72493deb21db90961c80757fd81d30fb39a43c8.

Change-Id: I787edfad66d3a91c9b106996a0ed5f3d7f624727

commit_message:
SoftwareDeploymentGroup allow arbitrary keys for attributes

Since SoftwareDeploymentGroup is really a ResourceGroup, it's capable
of resolving any attribute supported by SoftwareDeployment, including
arbitrary outputs mapped to attributes.  Exposing these via the
SoftwareDeploymentGroup resource provides much better flexibility than
forcing users to mangle everything via stdout.

This has the side-effect of making the existing attributes somewhat
redundant, e.g:

get_attr: [a_sdg, deploy_stdouts]

is exactly equivalent to this:

get_attr: [a_sdg, deploy_stdout]

The deploy_stdout attribute should be transparently reflected from the
SoftwareDeployment resources via the normal ResourceGroup interfaces,
so we could consider deprecating the existing attributes at some point.

Change-Id: Ie3b89155d2be0050394eb7f7d5000331cde9aae0
Closes-Bug: #1488921

commit_message:
Migrate telemetry tests to the ssh-auth-strategy

Migrate the telemetry tests to the new ssh-auth-strategy format. In this case,
it is just using the common test_create_server.

Partially implements: blueprint ssh-auth-strategy

Change-Id: Ic7a5ffe08edda8e453e556175b50ac058a957e64

commit_message:
Update tempest configuration

This patch updates tempest configuration settings to move or
remove deprecated options, remove settings that are the same
as the default values, and re-order the settings to be in the
same order as the sample configuration file for easier
debugging.

Change-Id: Icefb5d4bf8a29a1e301ba5a8a74f5aa293a4fb13
Closes-Bug: #1482364

commit_message:
Removed rpc-repo upstream pip deps

Changed variables such that the upstream rpc-repo is no longer used
as a source of truth for installing pip. While the repo is still
present as a default pip index (and it should remain to be as long
as RAX is maintaining the repo) it is now only used with the scope
of the repo server.

Change-Id: I524919dc9b7ea0f69ae00227969a6421bd64ec3b
Implements: blueprint remove-upstream-repo-dependency

extreme situations require extreme measures: this effectively makes
the functional job non-voting, especially now that we're in FF jam.

commit_message:
Fix the hard-coded etcd cluster size

In before, the etcd cluster size was hard-coded to 1, since HA mode
hadn't been implemented at that time. Now, we fix it. The etcd
cluster size is set to the number of master nodes.

Change-Id: I198ca604401bc805f31e8187f5245177761edf56
Closes-Bug: #1491602

'}, {'created': '2015-06-25 11:27:40.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Switch overcloud-f21-nonha to instack

Move overcloud-f21-nonha from testing the bash element and instead make use of
instack. This currently involves a number of projects that have to get pulled
into the upstream openstack infrastructure.

This commit breaks tripleo-ci into 2 distinct code paths once all of the jobs
are ported to instack we should be able drop the legacy code path(along with
support for tripleo-incubator) and return to a single code path.

Along with this change we should also remove the ci for precise jobs, remove
tripleo-ci from all of the experimental jobs we can run on openstack services
(until we have package building for each one working) and switch
overcloud-f21-nonha to non voting(until we iron out any teething problems with
relying on the trunk repositories)

This ci job is now building centos7 images eventually we will want the instack
based CI to support both CentOS and Fedora

TODO:
  o Get logs from the deployed nodes
  o Pull in various repositories into the openstack gerrit
  o Reorganize the ci jobs

Change-Id: I09207c1f8db4e9c0fde92a254bc03fb4e6276f11

commit_message:
Switch overcloud-f21-nonha to instack

Move overcloud-f21-nonha from testing the bash elements and instead make use of
instack. This currently involves a number of projects that have to get pulled
into the upstream openstack infrastructure. There are also some workarounds in
here that we will work on removing while various dependecies move around.

This commit breaks tripleo-ci into 2 distinct code paths once all of the jobs
are ported to instack we should be able drop the legacy code path(along with
support for tripleo-incubator) and return to a single code path.

This ci builds centos7 images eventually the instack based CI to support both
CentOS and Fedora.

Co-Authored-By: Dan Prince <dprince@redhat.com>

Depends-On: I1acd19da8567ab93b5003caf67673cc70efea5fa
Change-Id: I09207c1f8db4e9c0fde92a254bc03fb4e6276f11

commit_message:
Remove grub2 in redhat-common/pre-install.d/15-remove-grub

In Id1e430e7d050a0b99ac449e2ea435e06cda1c4e6 I made the mistake of not
actually removing grub in 15-remove-grub.

This restores the removal phase and adds a bunch of comments.  It
seems the centos7 and centos (6) images have grub2 installed, but F22
does not; hence the check.

For anyone interested in the history; it seems the whole idea of
removing grub and re-installing it in the finalise stage is to do with
Ubuntu grub scripts failing in the chroot.  It is not clear this does,
or has ever, affected rpm based systems; but that's how it is, so
leave well enough alone.

The whole reasoning behind the rpm download & re-install is actually
explained in If095adc4abb52a19a3aa0b1caebfb3e4d8f605ef, but over time
the comments got lost as code moved around.  I've restored in here
some detailed explaination of why we don't just re-install the package
"normally".  I've also added a note to the pre-install of various
things that are related to this step.  Again I think there are some
questions around this that we can investigate in another change.

Change-Id: I1acd19da8567ab93b5003caf67673cc70efea5fa

commit_message:
Fix missing sql_opts

`tox -egenconfig` doesn't work, because
`magnum.db.sqlalchemy.models.sql_opts` is moved to
`magnum.db.sql_opts`.

This fixes it.

Change-Id: Ia617ee0ceae5bff7d745a9b48bfcdf9dfc00e336
Closes-Bug: #1490817

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Update port bindings for master router

An HA port needs to point to the correct host (where the master router
is running) in order for L2Population to work.

Hence, this patch introduces two fixes:
* When a port owned by an HA router is up we make sure it points to the
  right node where the master is running, or a random node if there is
  no master yet (This corner case is fixed by the 2nd bullet point).

* When a L3 agent reports it's hosting a master, we need to update the
  port binding to the host the master is now running on. This fixes
  both routers with no elected master (Yet) and failovers.

(cherry picked from commit 91d3a0219a43a2c06ea4043cc9eeb518815df391)

Conflicts:
	neutron/api/rpc/handlers/l3_rpc.py

Closes-Bug: #1365476
Co-Authored-By: Assaf Muller <amuller@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I8475548947526d8ea736ed7aa754fd0ca475cae2

commit_message:
Make TokenClientJSON deprecated

All service clients' name should not contain "JSON" because of
Ic6d4c340e145a18cd45bc6fe750e9fdc8c5d2a8d of Tempest commit.
This patch makes TokenClientJSON deprecated and recommends to
use TokenClient instead.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

commit_message:
add options to support nova test matrix

This adds 2 devstack options:

NOVA_V2_LEGACY={True/False} which is whether we'd like to force the
/v2 endpoint to use the legacy v2.0 code base.

it also provides TEMPEST_COMPUTE_TYPE as an way to pass in which
service catalog entry we'd like to use for compute testing.

We also make v2.1 the default compute endpoint, as that's what we'd
like everyone to be testing and using. The other options will let us
build jobs that nova can run to ensure those APIs don't regress.

Change-Id: Ie6b7e4290d9a1d9789d04099b3b31c9a557bc22b

commit_message:
Implement manifest-based backports

This adds the conductor implementation required to support version-manifest
backport operations. Ideally we will drop all of the relationship mapping
stuff after we released this in Liberty and roll to Mitaka. We need to
support both operations here to bridge that gap.

Related to bp/use-oslo-objects

Change-Id: I3702c02c53876a5b593ba69c6ebd607e9b6b7152

commit_message:
Initial support for versioned driver classes

- Adds a helper to deprecate old driver classes
- Implements the versioned driver for keystone.catalog
- Documents developing drivers

partially implements bp stable-driver-interfaces

Change-Id: I58f6781a4e1256ffeb0cf226140b8be245c32aac

commit_message:
Update path to subunit2html in post_test_hook

Per:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072982.html

The location of subunit2html changed on the images in the gate
so update the path used in the post_test_hook.

Long-term we should just use what's in devstack-gate.

Change-Id: I5e50e7d7ad845aba26403df1df412c0a139a6dc7
Closes-Bug: #1491646

squashed with:
--------------

Don't pass null device when attaching a volume

The v2.1 API schema rejects null device values in an
os-volume_attachments request, so only include the device in the request
if one is specified on the command line.

Closes-Bug: #1491325

Change-Id: I4fa4019f19f9af6ff350db2fb6e524fa8570a6f3

commit_message:
Adding missing spec for widgets.module.js

There is no specs for horizon.framework widgets module
definition and horizon.framework.widgets.basePath constant
provider. This patch adds them in.

[{'created': '2015-08-30 06:53:47.000000000', 'message': "Pie Charts now inherit from Bootstrap Theme

Horizon's pie charts had hard coded styles directly in the JavaScript
code.  This made it impossible for them to inherit any of their look
and feel from the install theme.  This patch fixes that problem.

It was noted, while doing the refactor, that the legend was being
implemented within D3, but this was not necessary at all, since it
has no graphing visuals associated with it.  It was impossible to
allow the legend label sizes to inherit and be configurable from
the css while they were being generated in the SVG.  The height
could never be known unless D3 knew the height of each element.

Noted Improvements:
* Consistent Colors! Colors, even for distribution charts, now come
  from the palette
* All aspects of the charts are now resizable and can inherit the
  sizes of the charts, as well as the paddings and type settings
  from the theme
* A bug in the 'Show Numbers' function was discovered and will be
  fixed as a result
* The legend symbol, which was a hardcoded cube before, is now an
  icon font, and therefore can be customized per theme.  I.E., you
  can now use rectangles, circles, ovals, smiley faces, etc
* It now inherits directly from the Theme

Change-Id: I5d5c13e57553f8b504593aac6d7611175e900f3c
Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-theme-css-reorg

commit_message:
Pie Charts now inherit from Bootstrap Theme

Horizon's pie charts had hard coded styles directly in the JavaScript
code.  This made it impossible for them to inherit any of their look
and feel from the install theme.  This patch fixes that problem.

It was noted, while doing the refactor, that the legend was being
implemented within D3, but this was not necessary at all, since it
has no graphing visuals associated with it.  It was impossible to
allow the legend label sizes to inherit and be configurable from
the css while they were being generated in the SVG.  The height
could never be known unless D3 knew the height of each element.

Noted Improvements:
* Consistent Colors! Colors, even for distribution charts, now come
  from the palette
* All aspects of the charts are now resizable and can inherit the
  sizes of the charts, as well as the paddings and type settings
  from the theme
* A bug in the 'Show Numbers' function was discovered and will be
  fixed as a result
* The legend symbol, which was a hardcoded cube before, is now an
  icon font, and therefore can be customized per theme.  I.E., you
  can now use rectangles, circles, ovals, smiley faces, etc
* It now inherits directly from the Theme

Change-Id: I5d5c13e57553f8b504593aac6d7611175e900f3c
Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-theme-css-reorg

commit_message:
Revert "Remove references to suds"

This reverts commit bcc002809894f39c84dca5c46034468ed0469c2b.

Each call to the VC has a ton of information from suds that is logged. 

This makes debugging and troubleshooting terribly difficult.

Closes-bug: #1491256

Change-Id: I43b66aa6be6fc1b2ed43650bd5cfe69963d8a16e

commit_message:
Detaching and then attaching a volume to a paused instance will failed

When you detach volume from a paused instance and then attach any
volume to same paused instance at same name of device. Libvirt will
throw error. Even use virsh command to detach device and then attach
device will occur same error.

Just disable to attach volume to paused instance. But still can detach
volume from paused instance.

Change-Id: Idac1da80e7911554a31381d5179a12117751d88e
Closes-Bug: 1427732

commit_message:
Remove/deprecate conductor instance_update()

Calls that used to proxy through conductor method instance_update()
has been converted to objects, so remove from conductor.

Change-Id: I169998c0171480c366d7cb5b66f3c5a828b4180d

commit_message:
Make compute manager instance updates use objects

This make instance updates that currently proxy through conductor use
objects to do the same.

Related to blueprint liberty-objects

Change-Id: I57730264cd1f93ea5272b7a850c9b215b12219c2

commit_message:
[Ironic]Not count available resources of deployed ironic node

Changing node's properties in Ironic after node is deployed will
count as available resources in Nova, as nova's resource_tracker
will override the *_used keys we set in the driver.

This patch changes the caculation of available resources based on
the instance flavor instead of node to avoid the issue.

Change-Id: I1a6e4501122c4781e103fd83a146e0914c7671c9
Closes-Bug: #1301279

commit_message:
Add Castellan to global requirements

Add the Castellan key manager interface library to global requirements
so projects can start using it for the Liberty cycle.

Change-Id: I2283d2853d4ccd6d41d706db5b02cf6c74c5ba93
Depends-On: Ifc05616d62fac989d16246cb492210e46953688c

commit_message:
go: replicator fix

switch from r.Read(..) to io.ReadFull(r, ...) in the replicator to make sure we
read the full json document.

Change-Id: I37402a731eb17d1397589e4a90016eece75bd368

commit_message:
Add support for effective & inherited mode in data driven tests

Support the testing of inherited role assignments as well as
listing in effective mode to the data driven tests. The first
examples that use these capabilities are also included.

Follow on patches will extend the use of this to other existing
tests, as well as to widen coverage.

Partially Implements: bp data-driven-tests
Change-Id: I676c3889b8f7216e56b9e5982463fa5d5d6aa454

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-27 21:42:34.000000000', 'message': 'kolla: Remove kolla-functional-f21 job

Within the kolla upstream, we have migrated away from a shell
script for building.  Now we use a python tool for building
all of our docker images.  The shell script job takes over
an hour, while the python script takes about 20 minutes to
produce the same results.  In addition to not wanting to
test the original build shell script because we are reomving
it, the shell script only builds the Dockerfiles not the
jinja2 templated Dockerfiles, which are shortly to be deprecated.

Change-Id: I4de8fb52c6a32b6999f6be4112fa0b76e9f0ac42
'}, {'created': '2015-09-02 21:01:53.000000000', 'message': 'kolla: Remove kolla-functional-f21 job

Remove the kolla-functional-f21 job because it only runs the
removed-from-kolla bash build scripts.  The build gating is now
handled by other jobs which run a Python based build tool.  As a
result, evreything related to the kolla-functoinal-f21 job can be
removed.

As stands now this check will always fail because the bash buid
scripts are completely removed  from the kolla repo and this check
job depends on these removed bash build scripts.

Change-Id: I4de8fb52c6a32b6999f6be4112fa0b76e9f0ac42
'}]
commit_message:
kolla: Remove kolla-functional-f21 job

Remove the kolla-functional-f21 job because it only runs the
removed-from-kolla bash build scripts.  The build gating is now
handled by other jobs which run a Python based build tool.  As a
result, evreything related to the kolla-functoinal-f21 job can be
removed.

As stands now this check will always fail because the bash buid
scripts are completely removed  from the kolla repo and this check
job depends on these removed bash build scripts.

Change-Id: I4de8fb52c6a32b6999f6be4112fa0b76e9f0ac42

commit_message:
Fix instance recovery when nova-compute goes down during reboot

This fixes InstanceActionNotFound, when an instance is restarted
during nova-compute startup and UnexpectedTaskStateError, in the
case of soft reboot.

Change-Id: I4a3554162562655b2883f51d75e2521635181b74
Closes-Bug: 1072751

commit_message:
Add unittests for Flavors in sqlalchemy

We've recently added support for Flavors in sqlalchemy bu tests were
skipped because sqlalchemy's test suite was entirely skipped. Now that
the test suite is being executed, lets test Flavors too.

Change-Id: Ibc78c8652a2e9a8d4b765b59eaa49a3abd6bd87b

commit_message:
Update path to subunit2html in post_test_hook

Per:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072982.html

The location of subunit2html changed on the images in the gate
so update the path used in the post_test_hook.

Long-term we should just use what's in devstack-gate.

Change-Id: I5e50e7d7ad845aba26403df1df412c0a139a6dc7
Closes-Bug: #1491646

commit_message:
Add information about diverse/not diverse projects

This change prints a list of the projects that meet and do
not meet the requirements for the tag team:diverse-affiliation
in a simple does not meet/meets list.

commit_message:
Ignore flavor and image find errors on server show

If there is an error finding an image or a flavor during
image show, ignore it and just print the id of the flavor
or image.  This code is also used during server create and
server rebuild, but only to display the results.

Change-Id: I5362158ab8ffc3e5a0800904d6ea15420c3a8627
Closes-bug: #1489901

We are already using uwsgi emperor mode as it provides various features of scaling up and down wsgi instances, managing their state etc. It works pretty good. That's wondering what are the reasons for this switch."}, {'account_id': 15993, 'date': '2015-09-02 16:24:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The reason for the removal of uwsgi is that it is just a container and users should be able to use the container of their choice versus being forced to use uwsgi'}, {'account_id': 1091, 'date': '2015-09-02 17:53:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

Not every client will run barbican under a container. This change forces to run under a container as it lacks concurrency support. Generally in other openstack services, service itself provides option to configure and run wsgi as separate multiple processes or workers for concurrent handling of requests e.g. cinder-api, nova-api uses oslo_service to support it.

(cinder-api) https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/cmd/api.py#L56
(nova-api)
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/cmd/api.py#L48

Do we have similar code to support in Barbican as currently uwsgi is providing that kind of support? If not, then with this change, it becomes mandatory to run Barbican under some container for any cloud deployment.

I do see nova has paste app deploy similar to what's there in bin/barbican-api but that's experimental support and seems optional. Its useful in case deployer wants to run under container.
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/wsgi/nova-api.py#L15"}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-09-02 18:57:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Test if container_sweep is executed on unmounted devices

This change ensures that container_sweep is not run if a device is not mounted
and mount_check is set to True.

Change-Id: I823083c8431d9e61fd426508033ec9188503957b

commit_message:
Add unit test for container_update for unmounted device

This unit test case gains coverage for container/update.py
where a device (i.e. sda1) is not mounted and the code
responds with a warning logger that the device is not
mounted and continues.  Coverage increases 2% as a result.

Change-Id: I33d247a930b28604093df4ade1ce7dbbd24aac54

commit_message:
NSX-mh: use router_distributed flag

Even if the plugin technically already leverages this flag as it's
used in the l3_dvr_db mixin, the logic for the NSX-mh implies that
it is the backend that decides whether routers by default are
centralized or distributed.

This patches changes the logic for the default value for distributed
routers, ensuring the router_distributed flag is honoured.

(Removed from gate: Neutron failing all unit tests)


Applied from commit: 0649bb61f97f9a24dda525ec02a8f531914ae02c
Change-Id: I6cee010622d310477867b94b754aa2260b43b879
Closes-Bug: #1483920

commit_message:
Update path to subunit2html in post_test_hook

Per:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-August/072982.html

The location of subunit2html changed on the images in the gate
so update the path used in the post_test_hook.

Long-term we should just use what's in devstack-gate.

Change-Id: I5e50e7d7ad845aba26403df1df412c0a139a6dc7
Closes-Bug: #1491646

commit_message:
Make "availability zone" field optional for host aggregates

Nova allows an admin to create/update a host aggregate without specifying
the "availability zone" but on the Horizon dashboard it is still required.

This patch makes the availability zone field optional.

Change-Id: I44a8b9ff469a203a7e1e1ae3a91e2f49bb94de86
Closes-bug: #1386076

commit_message:
api: deprecate the api v2 extension configuration

While we are removing the v2 API soon, given the v2.1 API will soon
lose the option of configuring extensions, lets also deprecate these
options in the v2 API as well. This should help advertise the move more
widely.

part of blueprint nova-api-deprecate-extensions

Change-Id: I693a6cd25ef09e3974aa8231c8b3131158c9e1bb

commit_message:
acceptance: disable lbaas service plugin

Neutron packaging seems having issues when LBaaS is enabled in
service_plugins Neutron parameter.

As a temporary workaround, we disable it so we can unblock our CI, but
keep LBaaS service installed & working, so we continue the class
testing.

Once packaging is fixed, we will enable the service plugin again.

It also drop the device_driver parameter which is already the default
one in puppet-neutron.

Partial-bug: #1490990
Change-Id: Ibd90e5e159f9a1fbff3990241795894e0bdca3cc

commit_message:
Stop Connection class modifying os_options parameter

When a caller passes an os_options dict to the Connection class
constructor, the constructor may modify the os_options dict,
which can surprise the caller if they re-use the os_options
dict. Specifically the os_options tenant_name and object_storage_url
may be modified, and the changed values would then leak through to a
subsequent Connection constructed using the same os_options dict.

This fix simply constructs a new dict from the supplied os_options.
The patch also adds a test that covers this and also verifies that
a preauth_url passed as a keyword arg to Connection() will take
precedence over any object_storage_url in an os_options parameter.

Closes-Bug: 1488070
Change-Id: Ic6b5cf3ac68c505de155619f2610be9529e15432

commit_message:
Add a new check for weak RSA and DSA key sizes

This patch adds a new check to bandit that scans for key sizes of
RSA and DSA algorithms when using the pycrypto or cryptography.io
modules.

Change-Id: I7d740eccc73a49f7ee133d90177d19d5ef7b02ba

commit_message:
Add constraints jobs to Jenkins

This adds the required jobs to jenkins to allow jenkins to call tox with
the 'constraints' factor added.  This will allow a reasonable way to
test running unit-tests against a virtual environment installed with
constraints on upper-constraints.txt

Change-Id: I17ac389f78af241917b6da7f049085f2b13d30f2
Implements Blueprint: Requirements-Management

[config-reference] Clarify encrypted volume type command

Command to set an encrypted volume type isn't clearly displayed.
It should be on one line.

Closes-Bug: #1491407

commit_message:
Raise exception for v2 with domain scope

Raise meaningful discovery exception for v2 with domain scope.
Previously, the exception reported the vague message:

    Exception raised: Could not determine a suitable URL for the plugin

Now:

    Exception raised: Cannot use v2 authentication with domain scope

Change-Id: I5cf509c24863b35deca8d13fa5655f3665c3b29a

commit_message:
Update API Reference Docs with Project Quota Information

Add a new page to the API Reference detailing the Quota and Project
Quota APIs.  Also update the pages for secrets, containers, and order
to add a the new status code that is returned when a quota limit
has been enforced.

Change-Id: I05bb3cbd7d319dd2b2a64cba7b88aba72d4b1914
Partially-implements: blueprint quota-support-on-barbican-resources

Adding documentation for test plugins

This adds general info about test plugins in tests/index.rst a
placholder file is also added for each individual test plugin,
eventually to hold detailed information on each.

commit_message:
Split functional and py27 tests

Moved tests/extensions to tests/unit/extensions, otherwise they
wouldn't have run. Renamed the files in tests/unit/extensions to be
prefixed with 'test_', to match the rest of the test files. Did a
general clean up of tox.ini so we have standard whitespace.

Change-Id: I5615bfbf2d6ff4a4bc3e66e71c2472b0d1e3a2d7

[{'created': '2015-09-02 00:27:23.000000000', 'message': "Use auth_type instead of auth_plugin by default

This was something that OSC has pushed for a long time now, and it's
better to be consistent than worry about wording.

Change --os-auth-plugin and auth_plugin= in CONF to be --os-auth-type
and auth_type= by default. We deprecated (but will probably keep for a
long time) the auth_plugin name.

Change-Id: I9748aeb4a490f88c73ef22ebe49e9b4ac6af78cd

commit_message:
Use auth_type instead of auth_plugin by default

This was something that OSC has pushed for a long time now, and it's
better to be consistent than worry about wording.

Change --os-auth-plugin and auth_plugin= in CONF to be --os-auth-type
and auth_type= by default. We deprecated (but will probably keep for a
long time) the auth_plugin name.

Change-Id: I9748aeb4a490f88c73ef22ebe49e9b4ac6af78cd

[{'created': '2015-09-01 21:28:54.000000000', 'message': "Remove the conf loading methods from loading.__init__

Ideally I would like it so that a consumer of keystone auth can import
the loading module and have access to all the CONF and CLI loading
methods they need. However we need to find a way of naming these methods
so that we can support both auth loading and session loading in the same
file.

This isn't all that difficult but it can be done after a 1.0 so just
remove them for now so we won't have compatibility issues.

Change-Id: Ic6b874bc878e72c0399f4ad91a8dcbe9e014576e

commit_message:
Add session and auth loading to loading.__init__

Now we have loading functions for both auth and session we want to mix
them into the same loading namespace so that users only have to import
one thing. To do this we need to disambiguate the names as they are
purposefully similar.

Change-Id: Ic6b874bc878e72c0399f4ad91a8dcbe9e014576e

commit_message:
Fix bodies on consolidate-console-api

During the nova commit I175a778cede8fbeee9c47a502ab7a98f6d73c074
reivews, the request/response body formats of consolidate-console-api
have been changed.
This patch applies the change to the corresponding nova-spec for
avoiding confusions.

Additional unit test coverage for core/utils.py

This commit adds unit tests for bandit/core/utils.py to bring it to
~99% coverage.

[{'created': '2015-08-31 04:06:41.000000000', 'message': 'Add Functional Tests for Quota Enforcement

This commit adds functional testing for quota enforcement covering
the unlimited, limited, and disabled quota values for secrets,
containers, orders, and consumers.

Also, this commit includes a few related clean-up items:
- Change the enforce() method to take a project object instead of ID
- Add cleanup to the consumer behaviors functional tests class
- Fix cleanup in the orders behaviors functional test class
- Use a testtools attribute to request no parallel testing for tests
  that do not support it

Change-Id: I4ad640a91ee0655076cddc449d40ba96548d6bb0

commit_message:
Add Functional Tests for Quota Enforcement

This commit adds functional testing for quota enforcement covering
the unlimited, limited, and disabled quota values for secrets,
containers, orders, and consumers.

Also, this commit includes a few related clean-up items:
- Change the enforce() method to take a project object instead of ID
- Add cleanup to the consumer behaviors functional tests class
- Fix cleanup in the orders behaviors functional test class

Change-Id: I4ad640a91ee0655076cddc449d40ba96548d6bb0
Implements: blueprint quota-support-on-barbican-resources

commit_message:
Fix jenkins failure for image not found

Seems jenkins default image API version is 2, image v2 version
not support use name as image-show. I tried latest devstack, it
calls v2 API. So in jenkins jobs let's use v1 version now.

In addition, specify the mountpoint parameter on VolumeAttachment
resource. Heat used to allow missing of this parameter but it is
not the case anymore.

Change-Id: I1ae1eb20b9552444f0242a72e958c139209bf1f6
Closes-Bug: #1491314

commit_message:
Linuxbridge-agent: fix bridge deletion

Make sure that linuxbridge agent doesn't delete
physical interfaces if they are specified in the
physical_interface_mappings.

Change-Id: I95e3c46b03ba2ae0872f5def47f26d4e8ea13094
Closes-Bug: #1334634

So I went for a run and had some time to think about this...dangerous.

I think there is a problem here.  We definitely want this change that you've proposed, but I don't think it actually solves all of the cases.  I'm -1'ing for now, but the 'fix' may in fact be a second change set.  I just want the discussion started for now.

We need Shyama to validate but I believe that the discover_hdisk call will fail if there are 'stale adapters' (mappings).

This change doesn't scrub the adapters until after the discover_hdisk is run.  It does it pretty much right before boot up (when all the other mapping work is being done).

I actually want to keep that change - its valuable for vOpt, NPIV, localdisk, etc...  But...

I think in vscsi, if the discover_hdisk fails, we should do an immediate scrub and re-run discover_hdisk.  If it still fails then we would raise the overall exception.  That would keep the speed of the overall deploy up (except for an exceptional path), while at the same time increasing the robustness.

I think that there is a specific key for discover_hdisk to fail with that we could use to identify if we need to run an interactive scrub at that point.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 13002, 'date': '2015-08-27 06:43:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I have concerns doing this in create flow rather than delete flow. Say the create fails, we remove the stale disks and adapters then delete gets triggered to remove the failed instance. here if the cinder terminate_connection fails to remove the mappings on the storage for some reason a subsequent or parallel deploy would trigger discovery of disks on the same vios and the disks we removed would get discovered again. It is not safe to remove the disks till we remove the mappings in the backend storage.'}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-08-27 11:36:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think doing it in the destroy flow also makes sense.  Doing it in the spawn flow is more of a mitigation strategy though.  Just keeps us safe.

Keep in mind though, the destroy flow should already be removing all mappings.  So this shouldn't find anything there.

One other thing to remember.  Just because this is added early in the task flow, it uses the tx_mgr (FeedTask) and the execute to actually scrub isn't run until much later.  After the hdisk is discovered."}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2015-08-27 21:18:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

This shouldn't be needed in the destroy flow.  It should only be needed (on subsequent spawns) if the destroy flow failed.

After discussions and code inspection with Drew, we've settled on the following strategy to address the chicken/egg ordering problem of hdisk discovery before scrubbing:

 o We leave the current change in place.  In cases where we don't run into the hdisk discovery problem, this will be the first thing that runs under the storage FeedTask, and it'll clean up any other kinds of storage artifacts that are left over from a previous instance with the same LPAR ID.
 o We add a condition in discover_hdisk (pypowervm) which checks for this particular failure.  (Shyama, need to bend your ear on what that condition should look like.)
 o If that failure is discovered, we explicitly run the scrub and then try discovery again.  (If this happens, the scrub from the first bullet still runs, but it's a no-op.)

Because this involves changes in pypowervm first, then adding support here, we would like to merge this change set and do that work in subsequent ones."}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-08-28 18:22:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

A minor nit in the commit message.  Otherwise a +2 from me.  Great change - will increase resiliency in the deploys'}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2015-08-28 18:46:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2015-08-28 18:46:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2015-08-28 18:47:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Scrub stale LPAR storage from spawn

Building on support in pypowervm to scrub mappings and storage elements
associated with an LPAR ID, this change set adds logic into the spawn
flow to augment the storage I/O FeedTask to do that for the LPAR ID of
the newly-created VM, in case that ID was recycled from a previously
incompletely-cleaned-up instance.

Also changed the name of the tx_mgr variable to stg_ftsk throughout, as this
will ultimately be one of multiple FeedTasks used in the various flows.

Change-Id: Id5f3201c91f3fd24a80405eb7ecfe34a641ff925
