commit_message:
Accomodate discover_hdisk generic scrub

Recent pypowervm change in branch discover_hdisk_broad_scrub removed the
lpar_id parameter from discover_hdisk and changed the logic to be
satisfactory for both migration and non-migration code paths.  This
change set rebases to accomodates that adjustment.

Change-Id: I4538d158c3aef80dab14016e4249b032ac86fe36

commit_message:
Implement Enforce Method for QuotaEnforcer

Implement the enforce function that reads the effective quotas
for the current project, collects the current usage level, and
raises an error if the requested create would exceed the quota.

Change-Id: I625d90e69f4edb3e24b740538b14a80a333bd254
Partially-implements: blueprint quota-support-on-barbican-resources

commit_message:
Adding OSSN-0055 - service accounts may have admin privs

This commit adds OSSN-0055 which describes service accounts having
cloud admin privileges in many cases.  The note shows how to check
what role an account has and recommends monitoring usage for
powerful service accounts.

Closes-Bug: 1464750
Change-Id: I016064c8650a38116d6aa8d2528b42530c795f33

[{'created': '2015-09-02 09:49:55.000000000', 'message': 'Replace incorrect safe_str

The way safe_str is used is incorrect in case of python 3 and not
consistent in case of python 2. For example the following outputs depend
on the state of the whole string rather than each character in py2:

safe_str("\u0000") => "\x00"
safe_str("\uffff") => "\\uffff"
safe_str("\u0000\uffff") => "\\x00\\uffff"

(null is encoded once as null byte, once as string "\x00")

The replacement function applies to both Str and Bytes node contexts and
ensures that both representations always agree, at least in case of the
first 256 byte values / codepoints.

The result of Context.string_val_as_escaped_bytes is always printable
ascii and should be used when strings have unknown encoding, but should
be compared to a known value.

Closes-bug: 1491313
Change-Id: I7b065d22f03c10b9d3957a403c4439d2a7d74e78

commit_message:
Replace incorrect safe_str

The way safe_str is used is incorrect in case of python 3 and not
consistent in case of python 2. For example the following outputs depend
on the state of the whole string rather than each character in py2:

safe_str("\u0000") => "\x00"
safe_str("\uffff") => "\\uffff"
safe_str("\u0000\uffff") => "\\x00\\uffff"

(null is encoded once as null byte, once as string "\x00")

The replacement function applies to both Str and Bytes node contexts and
ensures that both representations always agree, at least in case of the
first 256 byte values / codepoints.

The result of Context.string_val_as_escaped_bytes is always printable
ascii and should be used when strings have unknown encoding, but should
be compared to a known value.

Closes-bug: 1491313
Change-Id: I7b065d22f03c10b9d3957a403c4439d2a7d74e78

commit_message:
Search based on the resource type name

Adds the filtering support to resource type based on
the type name pattern.

implements blueprint heat-resource-type-search

Change-Id: Id492d260b87464af385d58db7c017ba648fde411

commit_message:
Validate support_status while searching resource registry

Validates the resource_type's support_status when it is
searched from global ResourceRegistry. This saves user from
searching for invalid support status.

implements blueprint heat-resource-type-search

Change-Id: I620ead91b024b369e4f2d8971f1190da61cfc0b2

I'll wait on +A'ing to allow more input."}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-08-29 10:47:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hmmm. Interesting idea. 

My initial thought is that I don't like it, though. Aside from a couple of contributors, python 3.x doesn't get a lot of love. I'm worried that making the tests pass may obscure that effort further. At least a non-voting failure is in plain sight, and so other contributors can see that it needs to be fixed.

Not blocking though; I'm interested in hearing what others think."}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-08-29 17:07:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think that Rob makes a really valid point.'}, {'account_id': 8984, 'date': '2015-08-31 06:28:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

@Rob. If I understood the approach correctly, what we want to do is move progressively towards py3.x and guarantee that those tests that initially passed should continue to pass while we continue the migration of the remaining test. This is temporary, the final state will resemble the py27 test scripts. Am I right? @Victor'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-08-31 07:47:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

David Lyle: "(...) I fear it will provide a false sense of completion. But blocking new breaks is valuable as well."

The up to date status of Python 3 port of each OpenStack application can be found at:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3#OpenStack_applications

As you can see: cinder, glance, heat, keystone, neutron and nova use a whitelist in tox.py for Python 3.4, their py34 gate is voting and pass.

David Lyle: "We did something similar with the flake8 rules as well, so there is precedent. I'll wait on +A'ing to allow more input."

Yeah, this approach was used in all other OpenStack projects. Good news: aodh and ceilometer had a whitelist, but the py34 section of their tox.ini file was removed since these projects are now fully compatible with Python 3.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-08-31 08:00:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Rob Cresswell: "(...) Aside from a couple of contributors, python 3.x doesn't get a lot of love. I'm worried that making the tests pass may obscure that effort further."

I'm not sure that I understood your point. Does it mean that you don't want Python 3 in Horizon?

Reminder, the rationale for adding Python 3 support: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3#Python_3

Yes, contributors may now have to fix their new changes if these changes are not compatible Python 3. The idea is to distribute the effort on all developers, so I'm not the only one fixing Python 3 issues.

You don't need to be an expert in Python 3 to write code compatible with Python 2 and Python 3. It's more difficult when you port a large code base written for Python 2 at once.

Since the py34 gate of Cinder, Nova, Neutron, etc. became voting, I didn't get any complain. Recently, a friend asked me how to use contextlib.nested() on Python 3. He got a lot of replies on the mailing list, and I completed the wiki page. The wiki page contains a list of common patterns to port code to Python 3:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3#Common_patterns

> At least a non-voting failure is in plain sight, and so other contributors can see that it needs to be fixed.

The point is making the py34 gate voting is to avoid Python 3 regressions. If it's not mandatory, I know that py34 will break, and I fear that it will not be fixed and slowly "die".'}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-08-31 10:46:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

@Victor: You've misunderstood my point. Python 3 is very desirable, but I meant that there are only 1 or 2 developers working on it. The issue with the whitelist would be, if you get reassigned to other work for example, it gets forgotten; people see "Python 3 pass" and don't feel any need to work on it. At least non-voting, there is an obvious failure, though it is difficult to gauge the impact this would have.

An alternative solution would be to leave it non-voting, and ask the cores to investigate/reject patches that cause breakages, which is what we're currently doing with some of the other non-voting tests.

Ultimately if many other projects have had success with a whitelist, and there is precedent with flake8, perhaps we should just follow suit.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-09-01 10:38:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Rob Cresswell: "(...) but I meant that there are only 1 or 2 developers working on it. The issue with the whitelist would be, if you get reassigned to other work for example, it gets forgotten; people see "Python 3 pass" and don't feel any need to work on it."

It's not a big deal if the Horizon port to Python 3 is stopped during a few months. But it would be really annoying to reintroduce code incompatible with Python 3 during this "pause". The purpose of making the gate voting is to ensure that we don't introduce "Python 3 regressions".

"An alternative solution would be to leave it non-voting, and ask the cores to investigate/reject patches that cause breakages, which is what we're currently doing with some of the other non-voting tests."

If the gate is non-voting, I'm quite sure that in a few weeks nobody will check the py34 job again, and later someone will ask to remove the py34 gate to stop wasting resources.

If we don't force developers to change, the technical debt only increase :-('}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-09-01 11:49:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Victor: This is exactly my point though. If you hide the python 3 failures behind a whitelist, nobody will pick up the work, as they will only see "passing".'}, {'account_id': 5623, 'date': '2015-09-01 16:01:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I know Victor has been working on this effort across OpenStack for going on 2 years now. I trust he will follow through. I am ok with the whitelist. I think blocking newly introduced failures is highly valuable.'}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-09-01 17:14:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2015-09-02 01:20:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2015-09-02 10:03:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow+1

I'm merging this. It has 4 +2s and a +1; this seems like enough agreement."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-02 10:03:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Run a subset of tests on Python 3

Fix "tox -e py34" by only running a subset of tests which pass on Python
3.4. It should fix the py34 gate. If the gate pass, we can make it
voting to avoid Python 3 regressions.

Then we can add more tests to this list when fixing more Python 3
issues. The final goal is to remove the whitelist when all tests will
pass on Python 3.

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: I3e56789097162f9efc93b889e54b95147ea1f2dc

commit_message:
Change JSON Home for OS-FEDERATION to use /auth/projects|domains

The /OS-FEDERATION/projects and /OS-FEDERATION/domains are
deprecated and are replaced by /auth/projects and /auth/domains.
The JSON Home document should reference the new paths.

Change-Id: I1998d748948d0e11f0b94cb0b9f7ebbfecd2342a

commit_message:
Add django-formtools to global requirements

In Django version of 1.8 formtools was moved to a separate module.
While updating requirements with Django 1.8 support
formtools was not added to global list.

For reference:
https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.8/ref/contrib/formtools/

Change-Id: I07c6df36f1d9e8a48e8b67e13962c75ff617b779

commit_message:
Provide new_xyz_ref functions in tests.core

The new_xyz_ref methods are provided in REST testcase base, but
these are not REST specific functions, and can be handy to use in
non-REST test cases.

Change-Id: I57bce8c3a78552610b58b11cd44d70cd24575bd8

Thomas Herve: Kindly note that the request_context is written to make sure that if the given ctx parameter is always of RequestContext. But when the ctx is not of RequestContext, then the existing code trying the below logic:

ctx.to_dict()

This will fail, if dict is passed for ctx. to_dict() is only available in the RequestContext. The intent here is, to convert the given dict to RequestContext. so I have updated the code to handle the dict case. Otherwise, raise the invalid exception.

I updated the test cases to consider these 3 cases: RequestContext, dict, invalid ctx.

Please let me know if this does not answer your question. thanks.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-27 17:56:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Removes dead code from context.request_context

Existing context.request_context() method has invalid
code which try to create RequestConext, but its not used
in heat anywhere. so those dead code is removed from heat.

Closes-bug: #1464655

Change-Id: Icb60f1ba40853523ef35730c2ba5bda6e5970771

Added cancel button in add rule modal

Cancel button is missing in security group's add rule modal.

This patch adding the cancel button in the ad rule modal.

Change-Id: I66114ef5037bbdba11425c0e6bd34ef56280aa03

adding developer docs guidelines about clients

this change adds some brief documentation about the usage and creation
of OpenStack clients in sahara.

commit_message:
Support is_proxy_gateway in sahara node group templates

Since 0.7.7 python-saharaclient has ability to specify
is_proxy_gateway parameter when creating node group templates.
This patch adds support for this feature to
OS::Sahara::NodeGroupTemplate resource in Heat.

Change-Id: If159436c157893a62186338323108341a3c7e869

commit_message:
Scheduler: enhance debug messages for multitenancy aggregates

Debugging issues with the multitenacy aggregate filter is difficult
as one does not know if the filter_tenant_id is matched or not.

This patch added in a log debug that indicates the reason for the
filter being valid.

Change-Id: I17a3186057071e16f3933f7872fd34186306ef74

To address this issue, added a new periodic task

commit_message:
Delete orphaned instance files from compute nodes

While resizing/revert-resizing instance, if instance gets deleted
in between, then instance files remains either on the source or
destination compute node.

To address this issue, added a new periodic task
'_cleanup_incomplete_migrations' which takes care of deleting
instance files from source/destination compute nodes and then
mark migration record as failed so that it doesn't appear again
in the next periodic task run.

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: 1392527
Change-Id: I9866d8e32e99b9f907921f4b226edf7b62bd83a7

commit_message:
Refactor list_block_devices to its own function

This function is useful in any HardwareManager that interacts with
disks. Subclassing GenericHardwareManager is not ideal for any
hardware manager that interacts with only specific devices.

Change-Id: Ib20e68a8916590513c0a825e44407a110cfbb441

commit_message:
test_volume_boot_pattern: re-use create_floating_ip from base class

At some point the code in test_volume_boot_pattern for associating a
floating IP to the server instance must have been copied into the base
scenario test class. Let's re-use what's in the base class rather than
duplicate it in test_volume_boot_pattern.

Change-Id: Ie1b442eab458ec5968e60043d29242e45b1de09c

commit_message:
Added support of multi-region environment

Octavia does not support keystone regions and can choose an incorrect
endpoint url when multiple regions provides same services.

Change-Id: I5ea9de380419592920555a2c2fe7ac6f6935e700
Closes-Bug: #1487359

commit_message:
Enable automatic sample config generation

- Added an entry_point for oslo config generator
- Added a script to enumerate config options
- Added a tox target to invoke config generator

commit_message:
Use thread executor all the time for notifier

Trying to use the greenlet executor doesn't work when we don't use
taskflow, as nothing is doing the monkeypatching. Let's use threads for
now.

Closes-Bug: #1491326

Change-Id: Ic59f75a883eff1d4f0e4683f9d8ea4d943ad7aac

commit_message:
Fix qunit selenium tests

The qunit test HTML was attempting to pull in the (now absent)
_conf.html and _scripts.html files for Javascript configuration.
This configuration has now been fixed.

Closes-Bug: 1475387
Change-Id: Ie9a8ad454ae88325ed62d55b03708db9c7a6c26e

commit_message:
Correct neutron-ns-metadata-proxy command when watch_log is False

Neutron[1] uses the option --metadata_proxy_watch_log=false to disable
log watch[2] in neutron-ns-metadata-proxy instances but should use the
option --nometadata_proxy_watch_log. It implies that
neutron-ns-metadata-proxy instances fail to start.

This changes updates neutron[1] to use the correct option.

The change also corrects associated functional tests[2], indeed
metadata_proxy_watch_log option has no effect if a log_file/dir is
defined for the agent running the neutron-ns-metadata-proxy.

[1] neutron.agent.common.config
[2] could be done by setting metadata_proxy_watch_log = false
[3] neutron.tests.functional.agent.test_l3_agent

Closes-Bug: #1490594
Change-Id: Iaec4a78847d802234c99514313440fd7c14bc554

commit_message:
Adding sni_containers to Octavia API

This just adds the API to accept it and insert into DB.  There is still some
code needed to get the parsing done in the drivers but can be done in another
review as this has become needed due to a change in the neutron lbaas octavia
driver requiring this.

Change-Id: I69c55ee44c510979296539efbf1908af9204a620
